<1ST_LINE>u w AM-VeteransMemorials     06-28 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Veterans Memorials,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sites Approved for Memorials to Women, Black Patriots, Korean War
Veterans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal commission approved sites Tuesday
for three new national memorials to women, black and Korean War
veterans, according to a published report.
   The Washington Post reported in Wednesday's editions that the
National Capital Memorial Commission voted 7-0 to approve federal
park sites in Washington and Arlington, Va., for memorials to women
who in the armed services, blacks who fought in the Revolutionary
War and veterans of the Korean War.
   The newspaper said a Black Revolutionary War Patriots Memorial
will be located in Constitution Gardens near the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial, the Memorial to Women in the Armed Forces will be placed
outside Arlington National Cemetery and the Korean War Memorial
will be erected in Ash Woods near the Lincoln Memorial.
   ``I can't believe (site selection) is finally over,'' retired
Air Force Brig. Gen. Wilma L. Vaught, who heads the Women in
Military Service for America Memorial Foundation, told the
newspaper.
   The foundation had worked to gain site approval since Congress
passed legislation for a women's memorial in 1984.
   The panel approved the sites with the stipulation that final
designs, which have not yet been completed, abide by height and
area restrictions to be determined in future commission discussions.
</TEXT>
