<DOCNO> AP880628-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0628EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Drought     06-28 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Drought,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Buoys Hopes That India's Drought Is Over</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NARSINGHPUR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rainshowers over northern India in the
past week have raised hopes of a good harvest after three years of
devastating drought.
   Farmers have dispatched tractors and bullock teams to plow their
dusty brown fields so they can begin sowing the summer crop.
   ``If it keeps raining, it will be fantastic,'' said Ram Phal, a
farmer in Narsinghpur, 25 miles southwest of New Delhi. ``I can
hear frogs croaking at night and that means a good monsoon.''
   While farmers in America's heartland hope for rain to save their
crops, weathermen in India predict this year's monsoon will be
normal this year for the first time since 1984. The last three
summers brought increasing hardship and sometimes hunger to the 534
million Indians _ two-thirds of the total 800 million population _
who depend on agriculture for their livelihood.
   ``I just grew enough to eat at home,'' said Kanwar Singh,
another farmer. ``I haven't been to the grain market for three
years.''
   The annual monsoon is the main source of irrigation for most
Indian crops. When the monsoon failed to materialize last year
after two years of below-normal rainfall, 16 of the country's 25
states suffered.
   Scientists estimate that the drought was the worst in the past
125 years. The government has spent $838 million in drought relief
measures and imported 1.5 million metric tons of cereal to
replenish buffer stocks.
   The imports of grains were the first in five years and came more
than a decade after India announced self-sufficiency in food
production.
   But in the hamlet of Narsinghpur, the macroeconomics of food
imports and production of the past years are overshadowed by clouds
in the skies and smiles on the faces of farmers.
   It is time to sow millet, and the short but timely drizzles
portend a good harvest.
   ``If God gave me clouds and sons every day, wouldn't life be
wonderful,'' said Ram Phal, who owns seven acres around the village
of 500 people. He said one more year of drought would have forced
him to sell part of his holdings.
   The Hindu, a Madras-based newspaper, said Saturday that this
year's monsoon should cover the country by mid-July, auguring well
for the summer crop.
   ``The rains will change the color of the field,'' said Ram Phal,
pointing toward his barren brown farmland now being plowed for
sowing. ``In two weeks, it will all be green.''
   Like other farmers in Haryana state, Ram Phal plants millet in
March and June and wheat in November.
   The Agriculture Ministry said Friday the food output for the
1987-88 growing season was 138 million tons, compared with 152.4
million tons for 1983-84, the last time there was a good monsoon.
   The shortages pushed prices up, and they are unlikely to drop
quickly. Stockpiles must be replenished, and the government already
is warning people _ especially grain dealers _ not to hoard.
   In New Delhi markets, wheat sells for 10 cents a pound, almost
double the 1984 prices.
   ``First there has to be a good monsoon and then a good crop,''
said Bhagwan Das, who owns a grain store in the capital. ``Then
prices will fall. Maybe by the end of the year.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
