<DOCNO> AP880628-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0003EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sweden-Vacation Bjt   06-28 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweden-Vacation, Bjt,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Northern Land Celebrates Summer With Almost Pagan Abandon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In Sweden, people take their vacations
seriously.
   Small factories close. Major industries stop production lines.
Neighborhood grocery stores lock up for the summer.
   At a time when alien submarines are constantly reported to be
reconnoitering the Swedish coast, the navy has declared its
sub-hunting unit ineffective for the next month. The sailors are on
vacation, too.
   The government has published a duty roster for July. Only four
or five ministers of the 20-member cabinet are in town.
   All over the country signs are going up: ``Stangt for
Semester,'' Swedish for ``Closed for Vacation.'' It is the national
watchword for the month.
   At least half the 343,000 businesses in Sweden are closing, said
Jan Krylborn, director of the National Swedish Organization of
Small Businesses. Among them are many of this country's 48,000
industrial plants, he said.
   Most companies that remain open are service organizations, ``the
distributors of ice cream and those kind of businesses,'' he added.
   Sweden lives under snow and ice for much of the year, so the
arrival of summer is celebrated with almost pagan abandon.
   ``Midsommar,'' the Friday nearest the summer solstice or the
first day of summer, is a national holiday.
   France and Italy, among other European countries, virtually
close down for the month of August. In Sweden, it comes earlier and
is embedded in legislation.
   Three consecutive vacation weeks during the three summer months
are guaranteed by law to every Swedish worker. Altogether, Swedes
normally get five weeks annual vacation and the governing Social
Democratic Party has made a sixth week part of its campaign
platform for next September's election.
   Most people head for cottages in the countryside or take
pleasure boats through the chain of 24,000 islands stretching along
the Baltic coast. Such luxuries became available to average Swedes
through a long-time policy of cheap tax-deductible credit.
   In addition, Swedes get days off during the year usually
associated with religious holidays. Schoolchildren get one week in
February called ``Sport Recess'' designed for skiing holidays.
   Vacations are sacrosanct, and as the Navy example shows, not
even national security can stand in their way.
   Last year, the military came under fierce criticism for letting
the entire anti-submarine unit go on vacation just after a massive
hunt for a suspected intruder in the sensitive Tore Bay in the
northern Baltic.
   ``This year not all the vessels are unstaffed,'' marine
commander Bengt Shuback told the Svenska Dagbladet newspaper. ``But
something like last year could still happen ... We are far from
effective in looking for intruders.''
   The military says foreign submarines have regularly prowled the
coastline of this neutral country for the last decade. Sweden has
not identified the intruders since officially protesting to Moscow
over a 1982 incident.
   Shuback said the navy studied proposals to keep the unit
operational during the summer, such as sending the officers on
expenses-paid winter vacations to the Mediterranean when the Baltic
is frozen.
   The idea was rejected because the officers' wives or girlfriends
would be working and their children would be in school. ``We must
give the staff their legally required three weeks in summer,''
Shuback said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0012 </DOCNO>
