<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Harris     06-28 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Harris,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diet Doctor Murderer Has `Stories From Prison'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted murderer Jean Harris' new book gives a
first-hand look at how women were treated in prison recently.
   The book's title, ``They Always Call Us Ladies: Stories From
Prison,'' is derived from how the prison refers to its inmates.
   ``As late as 1983, the official package room list issued to me
aid I was allowed to have two jock straps and 200 cigars per month.
Nowhere did it list a brassiere or lipstick,'' the former
headmistress of the exclusive Madeira School for Girls in McLean,
Va., writes.
   ``Inmates at Bedford were referred to as `girls,' or `our
girls,' and under one superintendent as `those poor devils,' until
1970 when someone ordered that we be called `ladies,''' Harris
writes. ``Today, it is the one rule that seems to have been carved
deep into the brain of every C.O. (commanding officer). They always
call us `ladies,' no matter what we're doing.''
   This is the second book by Harris, who is serving a
15-year-to-life sentence for murdering Scarsdale Diet author Dr.
Herman Tarnower. Her first, the autobiographical ``Stranger in Two
Worlds,'' was a best seller in 1986.
   ``They Always Call Us Ladies'' is a history of the Bedford Hills
Correctional Facility since its founding as a women's reformatory
in 1901. It also contains anecdotes about current inmates and
prison life, and is scheduled for publication Aug. 17 by Charles
Scribner's Sons.
   Harris and Tarnower were lovers. She shot the 69-year-old diet
doctor to death in his home on March 10, 1980, because he was
supposedly leaving her for a younger woman. While Harris contends
she shot Tarnower four times by accident as he tried to stop her
from committing suicide, jurors concluded she deliberately killed
him because he was ending their relationship.
   The 65-year-old Harris, who is not eligible for parole until
1996, works in the prison's innovative Children's Center. Bedford
Hills has a nursery where inmates can keep their babies for a full
year after birth.
   Working, writing and teaching has occupied much of Harris' time
while imprisoned. Teaching, she has maintained, ``will cure
anything short of the common cold,'' and ``it is only through our
children,'' she has said, ``that we can make a better world.''
   Prisons should work to keep family ties taut, and prisons should
work to get prisoners to read and write and develop moral
reasoning, Harris says.
   Inmates in New York generally aren't eligible for clemency until
they have served half their minimum sentence, which is 1988 for
Harris. Last year, her lawyer, Michael Kennedy, urged Gov. Mario
Cuomo to issue a waiver for Harris, saying she was ill and had done
good work on behalf of the children of Bedford Hills inmates.
Harris has had two heart attacks while in prison.
   Cuomo turned down the request for early clemency review.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0631EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrawleyPoll     06-28 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley Poll,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Finds New Yorkers Critical of Brawley Advisers, Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of New Yorkers surveyed said Tawana
Brawley's mother and advisers have not handled her case
responsibly, a poll has found.
   In New York City, 55 percent of black respondents and 84 percent
of whites surveyed also said the three advisers to the black
Dutchess County teen-ager are using her case for their own
``personal advantage,'' according to results of a New York
Times-WCBS-TV News Poll in Tuesday's editions of the Times.
   Among New York City blacks surveyed, 62 percent said Miss
Brawley's advisers had not acted responsibly, while 17 percent said
they had acted responsibly. The remainder said they did not know or
declined to answer.
   Among whites surveyed in the city, 83 percent answered ``not
responsibly'' while 5 percent said ``responsibly.''
   Fifty-seven percent of New York City blacks polled said Miss
Brawley's mother, Glenda, had not acted responsibly, while 21
percent said the opposite. Whites polled, by 85 percent to 6
percent, said she had not acted responsibly.
   Mrs. Brawley has been taking sanctuary in a Brooklyn church to
evade a court order for her arrest. She had been ordered to serve a
30-day jail sentence for refusing to answer a grand jury subpoena
to testify about her daughter's disappearance.
   In addition, the poll found that in New York City, a large
majority of white respondents and a plurality of blacks surveyed
said the advisers were lying when they said Miss Brawley had been
abducted and raped by white men in Dutchess County last November.
   Among white respondents in the city, 9 percent said the advisers
were telling the truth, 71 percent said they were lying and 20
percent had no answer. Among blacks polled, 28 percent said they
were telling the truth and 37 percent said they were lying, while
35 percent had no opinion.
   The Times said the pattern of ``expressed disbelief and
hostility'' was even stronger in interviews conducted in the
Wappingers Falls area, where the Brawleys live.
   The survey also found that the advisers _ the Rev. Al Sharpton,
and lawyers Alton H. Maddox Jr. and C. Vernon Mason, who have
counseled Miss Brawley not to cooperate with authorities _ are
widely viewed unfavorably by both blacks and whites. The view
represents a sharp shift in attitudes among blacks since January,
the Times reported.
   The telephone poll, of 1,131 adults _ 676 in New York City and
455 in the Wappingers Falls area _ was conducted Tuesday through
Saturday.
   The margin of sampling error was plus or minus 4 percentage
points for the New York City total, and plus or minus 6 percentage
points for whites or blacks separately.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-AIDS     06-28 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-AIDS,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chairman Of AIDS Panel Encouraged By Reagan's Reaction To Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No prenoon lede expected.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan expressed a willingness to
broaden anti-discrimination protections for people suffering from
AIDS, saying the nation should confront the deadly disease ``in a
thoughtful and bipartisan manner.''
   ``We've got to get moving to give people hope,'' Reagan said
Monday after getting the AIDS commission's final report. He told an
adviser to prepare ``a course of action'' for the administration
within 30 days.
   The president proposed one concrete step in a statement that for
the most part complimented the 13-member commission for its work in
raising ``our level of understanding'' about AIDS.
   Reagan came close to embracing a principal recommendation of the
study commission _ that Office of Personnel Management guidelines
spelling out protections for people with AIDS be mandatory for all
government agencies.
   He said at the suggestion of retired Adm. James D. Watkins, the
commission's chairman, he had directed the aide, Dr. Ian MacDonald,
to ``include among his priorities consideration of specific
measures to strengthen implementation of the policy guidance'' from
the OPM guidelines.
   The OPM oversees the federal government's civilian work force,
numbering more than 2.3 million.
   Many people active in the battle against the spread of the
deadly disease have said they believe it is vitally important to
assure people infected by the virus that causes AIDS that they will
be protected against discrimination at work and in medical
insurance coverage.
   ``The president should issue an executive order banning
discrimination on the basis of handicap, with HIV (human
immunodeficiency virus) infection included as a handicapping
condition,'' the panel said in its report.
   Watkins told reporters he was elated with Reagan's willingness
to consider signing just such an order.
   Watkins, talking to reporters in the White House driveway, said
while he did not want to jump to conclusions, Reagan's statement
``sends the first signal that we're on the way'' toward protecting
victims of the disease under the law.
   The former chief of naval operations said the commission hopes
the OPM guidelines, which other federal agencies may embrace
voluntarily, will be made mandatory by Reagan in an executive order.
   He said such a signal is needed because anti-discrimination
policies in the various states differ, and this has left a
confusing mix of court decisions on discrimination suits.
   ``We've pointed out that we think it's time to bring the country
together on that issue,'' Watkins said.
   When pressed to say whether Reagan had made a commitment to sign
such an executive order, he said, ``Well, take it easy. I think
it's coming.''
   Besides urging Reagan to sign an executive order, the AIDS
commission urged the broadening of Section 504 of the
Rehabilitation Act of 1973, to include protection for workers in
private life.
   Watkins called Reagan a ``compassionate humanitarian'' and said
he believed the president's thinking had changed somewhat on AIDS.
He said Reagan related an anecdote about a woman who had written
him, telling him how two of her children became infected from the
AIDS virus as a result of a blood transfusion she once had.
   ``The president felt moved by the story, and I told the
president this was not atypical,'' Watkins said.
   ``I want to express my sincere appreciation to Admiral Watkins
and all of the commission participants for their perseverance and
diligence in completing their work,'' Reagan's statement said. ``It
is my hope that we can continue to approach this problem, which is
more than a medical crisis or a public health threat, in a
thoughtful and bipartisan manner.''
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious
disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it
incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. No one is
known to have recovered from AIDS, which most often is spread
through close contact with blood, blood products or semen from
infected persons.
   Most victims have been male homosexuals or intravenous drug
abusers.
   As of June 13, AIDS had been diagnosed in 64,896 Americans, of
whom more than half, or 36,480, have died, according to the federal
Centers for Disease Control.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0637EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     06-28 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTHELLO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Curt and Kim Andrews' wedding celebration
aboard a 71-foot-long 1910 Pullman rail car was a moving experience.
   Once the couple tied the knot, a piercing whistle blew and the
partly-restored coach carrying the wedding party chugged north,
dragging 55-gallon drums.
   The Andrews ended their wedding day Saturday by traveling 40
miles from Othello to Moses Lake aboard the rail car, stopping at
Warden to pick up relatives for part of the ride.
   ``I don't think anybody in town is surprised,'' Andrews said.
``It's gotten so the car is kind of an extension of me, people
think of it when they hear my name.''
   When he bought the train car in 1984, he joked that it was lucky
he was single. ``I'm married to this car,'' he said then of his
$50,000 investment that cost another $50,000 to refurbish. ``A wife
wouldn't like the competition.''
   But, the groom added, ``It may take me a little longer to
restore it now that I have other interests.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several families are reducing their garbage
piles with help from a labor force that demands no wages, takes no
breaks, requires no supervision and needs only a warm bed and a few
food scraps.
   They're earthworms.
   Pierce County officials presented a bowl full of the slimy
creatures last week to nine families volunteering for a recycling
and composting project.
   The families were told the worms convert food into soil in a
process called composting _ if they are kept in a box with moist
bedding and fed food scraps.
   The county is teaching the families how to reduce waste dumped
in the landfills, which have polluted the groundwater and must be
closed by 1991 unless the dumping volume is reduced significantly.
</TEXT>
