<1ST_LINE>r i PM-RadioPower     06-28 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Radio Power,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ham Radio Operators Look for Alternative Power Sources</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As power sources go, electric
eels aren't too practical, but ham radio operators say in the event
of a worldwide disaster, the animals beat pushing a Volkswagen van
up a 3-mile hill.
   Ham radio operators staged a 24-hour demonstration Saturday to
test the resourcefulness of operators who provide emergency
communications for the Red Cross in times of trouble.
   At the Vancouver Aquarium in Stanley Park, a red, 40-watt
lightbulb flickered below a huge tank where two fat, 5-foot eels
swam lazily back and forth.
   Electrodes in the water carry the Amazonian eels' bursts of
power _ up to 600 volts _ to the bulb and a regulating circuit that
helps charge a special radio battery.
   ``It's the first time, to the best of our knowledge, that anyone
has stored eel power,'' said operator Steve Buchan.
   During the simulation, operators must find ways to generate
power for their radios when conventional power sources are out of
commission. Wall sockets are off limits.
   ``There are people in California right now who are pushing a
Volkswagen van 3 miles up a hill with the engine turned off and
then letting it go down the hill, generating enough power to
communicate till it gets to the bottom of the hill,'' Buchan said.
``But we think we have them beat. Biological power is something
that's unique.''
   About 250,000 ham radio operators in 140 countries _ including
the Soviet Union where ham radios reportedly are tightly controlled
_ participated in the simulation, Buchan said.
   Besides the eel-powered radios, the Communications Vancouver
team demonstrated a satellite link-up using a Soviet satellite. It
made transmissions as clear as a cross-town telephone call, instead
of the compressed radio signals that often make voices sound like
Daffy Duck.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
