<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0648EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CommercialLaunches     06-28 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Commercial Launches,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Private US Space-Launch Companies Have 20 Clients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fledgling private American space launch
industry has signed 20 customers already and may have 10 more by
the end of the year, the Transportation Department says.
   The first of the private launches, a communications satellite
for the government of India, is scheduled for launch next March by
McDonnell Douglas, according to a ``manifest,'' or list, released
Monday by the department.
   ``The manifest illustrates the significant success American
launch firms have had in capturing the major share of the world
launch markets,'' said Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley.
``American firms won 13 launch contracts last year compared to just
two by the European consortium, Ariane.''
   The commercial launchers will use federal facilities, mostly at
Cape Canaveral, Fla., and will reimburse the government for all
costs.
   Burnley said the launch contracts will provide 8,000 jobs.
   ``Eleven of the manifested payloads will be launched for foreign
customers and will offset the U.S. balance of payments by as much
as $660 million,'' he said. ``The commercial launch sector may very
well be the most active part of America's non-military space
program for the next several years.''
   Eight of the satellites on the list previously had been
scheduled for launch from the space shuttle. Late in 1986, after
the Challenger accident grounded shuttle flights, President Reagan
fostered a private launch industry by ordering the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration out of the business.
   The schedule announced by Burnley is subject to delays, not the
least of which may come because of a shortage of ammonium
perchlorate, a component of solid rocket fuel. One of the two U.S.
plants that manufacture the fuel was destroyed in an explosion May
4.
   Burnley said allocation of the scarce fuel is being worked out
among NASA, the Defense Department and his agency and that
commercial launch companies are looking for supplies from
manufacturers in Europe and Japan.
   Two of the 20 missions are suborbital flights for gravity
research, using light rockets. Seven flights are for the U.S.
government, four are for international consortia, three are for the
British and one each is for Indonesia, Japan, India and a European
consortium.
   McDonnell Douglas is launching eight of the cargoes, General
Dynamics six and Martin Marietta four. A Maryland company, Conatec,
is handling the light rocket launches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
