<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Obit-Kanof     06-28 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Kanof,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noted Dermatologist Dies After Heart Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Naomi M. Kanof, who for 50 years edited
the Journal of Investigative Dermatology, died at George Washington
University Hospital after a heart attack.
   She was 76 when she died Sunday.
   Dr. Kanof, a former head of the department of dermatology at the
Children's Hospital National Medical Center, also taught
dermatology at Georgetown and Howard universities' medical schools.
   The Dermatology Foundation named her ``Practitioner of the
Year'' in 1983.
   Dr. Kanof was born in Brooklyn, N.Y. and was graduated from
George Washington University and its medical school before
beginning her private practice in dermatology in 1938. She
continued the practice until shortly before her death.
   She is survived a son, Robert Kanof Tendler of Boston, a
daughter, Rebecca Jane Tendler of Rosemont, Pa., and one grandson.
Her husband, Max Tendler, died in 1974.
</TEXT>
