<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Newspage-Tyson-Spinks     06-28 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspage-Tyson-Spinks,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tyson Knocks Out Spinks in Big Fight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Spellings of Jem and Finnegin are cq in last graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Tyson knocked out Michael Spinks
in the first round of a championship fight, retaining the
undisputed heavyweight crown in one of the shortest such bouts in
history.
   Tyson put Spinks on his back 1 minute, 31 seconds into the fight
with a crashing left and a right to the jaw.
   It was over before a sellout crowd of 21,785 really had a chance
to settle in. The gate of about $80 million was the richest in
boxing history, according to promoter Donald Trump.
   When he came around, Spinks, 31, said, ``I finally found someone
who can beat me.''
   It was the first defeat against 31 victories for Spinks, the
former undisputed light heavyweight champion and former
International Boxing Federation heavyweight champ.
   Tyson, who weighed 218\, six pounds more than Spinks, now has a
35-0 record with 31 knockouts. He turns 22 on Thursday.
   For his pain, Spinks got a guarantee of $13.5 million. Tyson's
cut from the fight, which was televised on closed-circuit and
pay-per-view television, would be in the neighborhood of $20
million.
   The only faster knockouts in heavyweight title history were Jim
Jeffries' 55-second victory over Jack Finnegin in 1900, Michael
Dokes' 1:03 win over Mike Weaver in 1982 and Tommy Burns' 1:28
defeat of Jem Roche in 1908.
</TEXT>
