<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FuelSpills-EPA     06-28 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fuel Spills-EPA,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says EPA Hamstrung In Preventing Oil Spills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress should consider rewriting regulations
to allow the Environmental Protection Agency a greater role in
safeguarding against oil spills, says a congressional report.
   The Congressional Research Service based its conclusions on a
study of the fuel spill that began on Jan. 2 at the Ashland Oil
Inc. terminal near Pittsburgh, and affected drinking water supplies
in Ohio, Pennsylvania and West Virginia.
   CRS said in a 21-page analysis that Ashland complied with
federal standards in assuming responsibility for the cleanup of
more than 700,000 gallons of diesel fuel from the Monongahela and
Ohio rivers.
   The problem, CRS said, appears to lie in loosely-written
regulations that make it difficult for the EPA to detect problems
before they occur. The research agency said it was only after the
collapse of an Ashland tank that EPA found faults with the
company's spill prevention plan.
   The fuel tank collapse at Ashland's Floreffe Terminal that
caused the contamination stemmed from a dime-sized flaw in the
tank's nearly 50-year-old steel wall.
   Ashland and other owners of above-ground oil tanks holding more
than 660 gallons are required to file oil spill prevention plans
which must be reviewed every three years. Ashland's plan was on
file near Pittsburgh, as required.
   But the government did not learn about alleged flaws in the plan
until after the accident. EPA said in a memorandum on Jan. 15 that
Ashland's Spill Prevention Control and Countermeasures plan ``does
not adequately address spill prevention and control specific to the
facility.''
   ``Instead,'' the EPA said, ``it merely paraphrases the SPCC
regulations.''
   But Monday's report, requested by Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.,
said the EPA never saw the plan before the accident because
regulations only require that the document be prepared, not that it
be inspected by EPA.
   Under the regulations, EPA only gets involved after spills have
occurred, unless it has reason to suspect problems.
   ``Minor spills should not be the only reason for an SPCC plan to
come before federal and state officials,'' CRS said in the report.
``More automatic review by EPA and state officials might be
desired, and perhaps the regulations should state this.''
   The EPA has been reviewing whether problems with Ashland's spill
prevention plan merit penalties.
   Ashland spokesman Roger Schrum said Monday that company believes
the plan met EPA regulations.
   ``We have not been fined and it's been our contention that we
had an adequate plan,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
