<DOCNO> AP880628-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Cuba-Poll     06-28 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Poll,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 9 a.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Polls Shows Slight Majority Favors Talks with Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overwhelming majority of Americans have a
negative view of Cuba's Marxist government, but slightly more than
half favor talks with Cuba on improving relations, according to a
poll released today.
   The survey showed that 81 percent of Americans have an
unfavorable attitude toward Cuba, compared with 52 percent in 1977.
Only 1 percent see Cuba in a ``very favorable'' light.
   But 51 percent would support the United States entering into
negotiations with Cuba looking toward re-establishing normal
diplomatic and economic relations. Thirty-one percent are opposed
to that policy.
   The survey was commissioned by Potomac Associates, an
independent policy research organization at Johns Hopkins School of
Advanced International Studies in Washington. The polling was
conducted by The Gallup Organization.
   It was carried out in March and involved interviews with 1,038
adult Americans. The survey has a margin of error of 4 percentage
points.
   Based on the survey, if either of the major party candidates
indicates a readiness to improve relations with Cuba, his standing
with the voters would benefit slightly.
   Eighteen percent said they would be more likely to vote for a
candidate with that policy, while 14 percent said they would be
less likely. Most said they would not be influenced either way by a
candidate's position on Cuba.
   The United States and Cuba have not had full diplomatic
relations since 1961, but agreed to establish small diplomatic
missions in each other's capital in 1977. A U.S. trade embargo
against Cuba has been in effect since 1960.
   U.S. talks with Cuba have been limited largely to immigration
issues in recent years. There have been no serious discussions on
such subjects as the economic embargo, Cuba's ties to the Soviet
Union or its military presence in such areas as Africa and Central
America.
   A separate section of the survey examined attitudes of
Cuban-Americans living in Florida and New Jersey. Ninety-six
percent feel that President Fidel Castro is a ``bad thing'' for
Cuba, but 41 percent said they would favor U.S.-Cuban talks on
normalizing relations. Forty-seven percent are opposed.
   The margin of error among the Cuban-Americans was 8 percentage
points to 9 percentage points.
   William Watts, president of Potomac Associates, said the
willingness of many Cuban-Americans to support bilateral talks
indicates that there is no basis for the widespread notion that the
exile community is inflexibly opposed to negotiations with Castro.
   Still, the survey showed hostility toward the Cuban government
among exiles is strong.
   Eighty-six percent believe the Soviet Union has ``very
important'' influence over Cuban government actions and 80 percent
have a ``very unfavorable'' perception of the human rights
situation in Cuba. Only 6 percent would support an easing of the
trade embargo against Cuba.
   The overwhelming majority also expressed support for Radio
Marti, the Voice of America broadcast operation to Cuba, and TV
Marti, the proposed U.S. government television channel for Cuba.
   The survey also included a sampling of 94 American opinion
leaders and policy makers. Of this group, 90 percent favored the
opening of negotiations with Cuba, but Watts said the group
interviewed was too small to be considered representative.
</TEXT>
