<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-AustraliaFuture     06-28 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Australia Future,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australian Likens 21st Century Asia to 19th Century Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Links with the United States will become even
more important for Australia as its Asian and Pacific neighbors
grow stronger and more prosperous, says Australia's defense
minister.
   Europe hasn't much part to play but the coming era of Pacific
growth ``assumes a very substantial American role which makes the
alliance with the United States all the more important,'' Minister
Kim Beazley said Monday.
   Beazley covered some of the strategy issues to be aired at the
annual ministerial meeting here Tuesday and Wednesday of ANZUS, the
military alliance created at the end of World War II by Australia,
New Zealand and the United States. New Zealand was ousted two years
ago over its ban on visits by nuclear-armed or powered U.S.
warships.
   Beazley said the door should be kept open for New Zealand's
return although he saw no immediate prospect for compromise in its
dispute with the United States.
   Instead of being overshadowed by a single country, the
Asia-Pacific area in the coming decades could become a region of
``many powers competing on an equal status ... some of them
economic giants, like we had in the Europe of the 19th Century,''
Beazley said. He named Japan, China and India.
   That vision of the future was not necessarily cause for ``any
sense of alarm,'' he said, since, the Asia-Pacific countries ``not
having land borders, by and large, are capable of civilized
behavior with each other, which was not possible for the European
powers of the 19th Century.''
   The Soviet Union had been increasing its military capability in
the region, but recently ``the United states has got its strategy
together quite dramatically ... in maritime terms in the Pacific,
and I think that has, to a degree, stabilized this issue,'' he said.
   While welcoming some of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
policies, the West should press Moscow on such issues as the
massive Soviet presence at Cam Ranh Bay, Vietnam, the Australian
defense minister said.
   Ending the Vietnamese occupation of Cambodia is very much in the
Soviet Union's own interest and should be pursued diplomatically,
he added.
</TEXT>
