<DOCNO> AP880628-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0641EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe Bjt   06-28 0924</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe, Bjt,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Testimony Reveals Widespread Leaks of Secret Pentagon Info</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-forgotten courtroom testimony reveals
that private defense consultants and contractors didn't need an
underground operation to obtain classified information from
Pentagon employees. They could get it simply by asking.
   The open-door system apparently operated alongside the
clandestine arrangements between consultants and Pentagon employees
that are the subject of an intensive federal investigation.
   Investigators believe consultants using the secret system may
have bribed Defense Department officials to obtain top-secret
information, including plans of one contractor that could be sold
to another.
   Tucked away in a court reporter's records in Baltimore is a 1984
description _ and a defense _ of the more open cooperation between
some consultants, contractors and Pentagon officials.
   The information obtained in the open was important to
contractors seeking to bid on Pentagon projects. But private
lawyers familiar with the system said the information usually was
secret rather than top secret, and only consisted of Pentagon
documents, not those of contractors.
   The up-front system came to light in January 1984, when lawyers
for a private defense consultant summoned Caroline A. Chewning to
the witness stand in U.S. District Court in Baltimore.
   Then and now involved with writing programs for the Defense
Advanced Research Projects Agency, Ms. Chewning testified that
consultants and contractors with security clearances routinely
asked for key documents at offices such as hers _ which writes
``wish lists'' for futuristic military technology.
   Bribes were not necessary, she testified, because the
information was ``made available to them for free.''
   Why? Because, she testified, contractors could not possibly
submit a thorough bid for a major Pentagon project within the
required 45 days after an official notice was published.
   So officials simply handed out the information to
security-cleared consultants and contractors to give them a head
start.
   ``It's in the government's best interest that contractors have
this information. If they had to go to `official channels,' it may
take them six months. ... You're on a tight contract award basis,
and you don't have time for that,'' she said in defense of the
system.
   ``The government and private industry must cooperate in order to
get contracts awarded and material developed.''
   The Defense Department would not say Monday whether the system
has been changed. But in a speech, Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci cautioned against any hasty reforms of the defense
contracting system.
   While Carlucci said the government may terminate contracts found
to be tainted, he said ``the last thing we need now are hasty,
piecemeal changes that despite good intentions ultimately may make
matters worse.''
   Carlucci said ``no system can offer perfect protection against
the human factor. There is simply no way to devise a system that is
greed-proof.''
   The contracting system will undergo congressional scrutiny
Wednesday when the House Armed Services Committee holds the first
formal hearing on procurement practices since the fraud
investigation became public June 124.
   The first witness will be Robert Costello, undersecretary of
defense for acquisition policy.
   Also Monday, sources said 90 percent of the defense contractors
checked in a Pentagon study last year were sloppy in handling
classified documents, despite assurances given Congress by former
Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger that the program had few
problems.
   The study was done by the Defense Investigative Service but was
withheld from Congress by Weinberger because he didn't like the
conclusions, according to the sources, speaking on condition they
not be named.
   The open system of giving documents to consultants was
apparently not widely discussed at the time Mrs. Chewning
testified. The witness recalled that her ``mouth fell open'' when a
contractor she had never met called to ask her for an
interpretation of a document she had written.
   In other developments, the FBI said it investigated Melvyn
Paisley prior to his 1981 confirmation by the Senate as assistant
Navy secretary for research, engineering and systems, but it would
not disclose the results of that check.
   Federal investigators found ``stacks'' of classified federal
documents that Paisley had no security clearance to possess when
they searched his home and office, The Washington Post reported in
today's editions, citing unidentified informed officials for the
information.
   And Rep. James Florio, D-N.J., asked Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci to investigate whether favorable treatment for the Sperry
Corp., now part of Unisys Corp., was arranged by Paisley for work
on the Navy's Aegis ship-defense system. The multibillion-dollar
system had been developed and had been almost exclusively outfitted
by the RCA Corp. at its facility in Moorestown, N.J., until work
was redistributed in 1986 to include Sperry.
   Ms. Chewning testified at the trial of William V. Miller, a
private defense consultant who was charged with two counts of
conversion and unauthorized sale of government property.
   Miller was acquitted, and his attorney, Selig Solomon, said in
an interview that Ms. Chewning's testimony likely won the case for
the defense. It showed that Miller was accused of taking material
that was given to consultants all the time, he said.
   Ms. Chewning said ``95 to 99 percent'' of the information that
consultants and contractors sought from her section was willingly
handed out.
   She said the documents went through a classification process,
first in her agency and then at the Pentagon, where the documents
were reviewed.
   Discussing the sensitivity of the documents, she said, ``You
just can't hand it to someone who doesn't have a security
clearance, just because they want to bid on it.''
   ``I have not seen them handled in an unsecure manner'' within
her office, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
