<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe-Aegis     06-28 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Aegis,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmaker Questions Paisley's Role In Lucrative Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McHUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressman is asking the Pentagon to
investigate whether a key figure in the defense-purchasing probe
orchestrated a ``bewildering'' plan to share the work on a
lucrative weapons system.
   Rep. James Florio, D-N.J., asked for an investigation of the
role played by former Assistant Navy Secretary Melvyn Paisley in a
1986 decision to redistribute work on the Navy's
multibillion-dollar Aegis ship-defense system.
   Florio, in a letter to Secretary Frank Carlucci, said Paisley _
a target of the ongoing defense procurement probe _ may have
orchestrated the plan to redistribute work on the highly technical
and massively expensive system.
   ``It is distressing to see that a decision that should have been
made in the best interests of national defense might have been made
for totally different reasons having to do more with greed,''
Florio said in a statement.
   He questioned a plan overseen by Paisley to designate the Sperry
Corp. of Great Neck, N.Y., as a ``second source'' for Aegis work.
The system, one of the Navy's most advanced, was developed and had
been almost exclusively outfitted by the RCA Corp. at its facility
in Moorestown, N.J.
   Before the proposal, Florio said, RCA had successfully built and
delivered 15 Aegis systems, at below contracted prices. Aegis,
named for the shield of the Greek god Zeus, combines radar,
computers and weapons in sophisticated, umbrella-like protection
for Navy warships.
   Florio said he was puzzled by the plan to shift some Aegis work
to Sperry given RCA's good performance. ``The rationale was, at
best, bewildering,'' Florio said in a letter to Carlucci.
   ``Many of us felt from the beginning that the decision to
second-source Aegis was questionable. Recent developments make it
appear even more so,'' Florio said.
   Florio said his concern was heightened by published reports
linking Paisley, now a private defense consultant, with the giant
Unisys Corp., formed by the 1986 merger of Sperry and Burroughs
Corp.
   A report in Defense News, published Monday, quotes sources as
linking Paisley to Unisys via his close associate, William Galvin,
a Unisys adviser also said to be under investigation.
   Paisley left government in March 1987 to form a consulting
business at a Watergate complex office near Galvin's.
</TEXT>
