<DOCNO> AP880628-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Aloha-Boeing Bjt   06-28 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aloha-Boeing, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane's Maker Says It Urged Complete Inspection Before Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Co. had urged Aloha Airlines to make a
``complete structural inspection'' of four aging jets just a few
months before the roof of one of the planes peeled off in flight,
federal investigators have been told.
   Boeing says that Aloha, after first agreeing to begin the
inspections in early 1988, postponed them until the end of the year
or possibly later.
   Only after a meeting in mid-April between Boeing and Aloha
officials did the airline agree to reinstate the stepped-up
maintenance program for its four oldest Boeing 737s including the
one that broke apart during flight on April 28, according to Boeing.
   The manufacturer's assertions were outlined in documents made
public Monday by the National Transportation Safety Board, which is
investigating the accident in which a flight attendant was swept to
her death after a 20-foot section of the plane's roof tore away.
   The plane then landed safely on the Hawaiian island of Maui.
   Aloha, in separate documents filed with the NTSB, denied that it
had delayed the stepped-up inspection and maintenance program.
   ``Boeing's continued reference to delaying the repair and
maintenance of the high-cycle airplanes is simply incorrect,'' the
airline declared.
   Earlier, Aloha had asked the NTSB not to make the Boeing
documents public.
   The claims and counterclaims are likely to be a major focus of
formal NTSB hearings next month in Seattle on the Aloha accident.
The Washington Post had disclosed the existence of some of the
Boeing documents last Sunday.
   In a summary of its dealings with Aloha since October, Boeing
maintained that it repeatedly warned the airline in letters and
informal discussions that its older aircraft _ especially the four
aging Boeing 737s _ had extensive corrosion that if not corrected
could make them unsafe.
   After inspecting two Aloha planes, a Boeing consultant called
them ``among the most corroded in the 737 fleet.''
   Boeing said its manager of maintenance, Robert Oldani, told
Aloha officials that the four oldest 737s might become unsafe if
the corrosion problem were not corrected. As a result, Aloha
promised to speed its maintenance program and begin a series of
structural inspections of the four oldest aircraft, Boeing said.
   But Boeing said it learned on March 3 that Aloha had changed its
mind and would postpone the heavy maintenance checks from the
spring to the last quarter of 1988. After a meeting between Boeing
and Aloha representatives on April 14, the airline agreed to
reinstate its earlier maintenance schedule, Boeing said.
   Maurice Myers, president of Aloha, has denied that Boeing ever
suggested that any of the Aloha jets was unsafe. He complained that
Boeing did not formally provide him with an evaluation of its
findings from last fall's inspections until April.
   But Boeing cited letters from its representatives on Oct. 15 and
Nov. 13 of last year as well as ``handwritten notes'' available to
Aloha that summarized its critical survey results.
   In the Oct. 15 letter to Aloha's vice president for quality
assurance and maintenance, Everette Webb, a Boeing consultant,
wrote that the importance of eliminating the corrosion from the
older Aloha jets ``cannot be overemphasized'' in light of the high
number of takeoffs and landings and the tropical environment in
which the airline operates.
   At the time, Webb asked that the Boeing team be allowed to
examine two additional aging Aloha aircraft, including the one that
five months later would break up during flight. The planes were
scheduled to undergo heavy maintenance in late October and early
November, according to Webb.
   The Boeing team, however, never examined the plane involved in
the April accident, although the other plane cited in the Oct. 15
letter was examined in late October, according to Boeing.
   On Nov. 13 after the second Aloha plane had been examined by the
Boeing team, Webb reminded Myers, the Aloha president, that Aloha
had three of the oldest Boeing 737s still flying and added, ``As
the fleet leader, the thoroughness and frequency of structural
inspections as well as the effectiveness of preventative
maintenance is important.''
</TEXT>
