<HEAD>`Roger Rabbit' Burrows Into First; `Rambo' Blown Out Of Top 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' was bigger than
``Big,'' earning $11.2 million at the nation's box office last
weekend, while ``Rambo III'' got blown out of the top 10 in its
fifth week of release.
   The movie about a seedy detective played by Bob Hoskins who
comes to the aid of a cartoon rabbit set a record for a Walt
Disney-released film and easily beat the Tom Hanks comedy for first
place.
   ``Roger Rabbit'' opened Thursday. The Walt Disney Co. reported
the movie's five-day earnings at $14.8 million, surpassing
comparable five-day grosses for ``Three Men and a Baby'' at $13.9
million and ``Back To The Future'' at $14.7 million.
   ```Who Framed Roger Rabbit' appears to be an across-the-board
hit and we feel it is destined to join the ranks of the studio's
classics,'' said Dick Cook, president of distribution for Disney's
Buena Vista division.
   The Disney-Steven Spielberg collaboration was shown at 1,045
screens for its debut week and earned $10,742 per screen average.
   About $20 million more was expected from the sale of licensed
Roger Rabbit dolls, figurines, key rings, mugs, pencils and pens,
said Bob Solomon of Applause licensing company in Woodland Hills.
   ``Our impression is that the sales are phenomenal,'' Solomon
said Monday. ``We are also the licensor for the California Raisins,
and over this last week they have taken a back seat to Roger
Rabbit.''
   ``Rambo III,'' Sylvester Stallone's battle against the Soviets
in Afghanistan, earned $2 million for an 11th place spot, five
weeks after its release. The film, which reportedly cost $60
million to make, has so far earned $47.1 million.
   ``Big,'' which has steadily maintained the No. 2 position
despite wave after wave of new releases, earned $7.2 million, up 9
percent over its previous week. In third place was the Dan
Aykroyd-John Candy comedy ``The Great Outdoors,'' which earned
$6.12 million, while ``Red Heat'' with Arnold Schwarzenegger and
Jim Belushi took fourth place with $6.11 million.
   ```Crocodile' Dundee II'' was fifth with $5.2 million, followed
by the baseball romance story ``Bull Durham,'' which remained in
sixth place for its second week with $5.1 million, but had a 9
percent business increase.
   ``Big Business'' was in seventh place with $4.1 million;
``Willow'' in eighth with $2.5 million; ``Funny Farm'' at No. 9
with $2.2 million; and ``The Presidio'' in 10th place with $2.1
million.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release, and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' Walt Disney, $11.2 million,
1,045 screens, $10,742 per screen, $14.8 million, one week, n-a.
   2. ``Big,'' 20th Century Fox, $7.2 million, 1,377 screens,
$5,236 per screen, $42.5 million, four weeks, $15 million.
   3. ``The Great Outdoors,'' Universal, $6.12 million, 1,415
screens, $4,330 per screen, $15.7 million, two weeks, n-a.
   4. ``Red Heat,'' Tri-Star, $6.11 million, 1,892 screens, $3,233
per screen, $18 million, two weeks, $18 million.
   5. ```Crocodile' Dundee II,'' Paramount, $5.2 million, 2,284
screens, $2,279 per screen, $79.5 million, five weeks, $14 million.
   6. ``Bull Durham,'' Orion, $5.1 million, 1,297 screens, $3,491
per screen, $14.1 million, two weeks, n-a.
   7. ``Big Business,'' Disney, $4.1 million, 1,232 screens, $3,344
per screen, $20.9 million, three weeks, $15 million.
   8. ``Willow,'' MGM-UA, $2.5 million, 1,201 screens, $2,116 per
screen, $39.5 million, six weeks, $35 million.
   9. ``Funny Farm,'' Warner Bros., $2.2 million, 1,386 screens,
$1,605 per screen, $20.4 million, four weeks, $16 million.
   10. ``The Presidio,'' Paramount, $2.1 million, 1,168 screens,
$1,818 per screen, $13.4 million, three weeks, $20 million.
