<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe-FBI     06-28 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-FBI,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-White House Personnel Chief Doesn't Recall Allegatons About
Paisley</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former personnel director of the White
House says he recalls nothing unusual turning up in an FBI
background check of Melvyn Paisley, a key figure in the Pentagon
bribery probe.
   Mildred McGetrick, one of Paisley's three ex-wives, said she
told the FBI in mid-1981 that Paisley, then a Boeing Corp.
executives, was ``dishonest with money'' and also told federal
agents that Paisley took gratuities including cash and gifts.
   At the time, Paisley was under consideration by the White House
for the post of assistant secretary of the Navy for research,
engineering and systems.
   Ms. McGetrick, who was on a backpacking trip Monday and
unavailable for comment, was interviewed by the Los Angeles Times,
which published the story in its Sunday editions.
   In response, the FBI issued a statement saying the results of
its background investigation of Paisley were furnished to the White
House on Sept. 29, 1981. Paisley was nominated by President Reagan
less than a month later on Oct. 27 and confirmed by the Senate Nov.
23 of that year.
   FBI spokeswoman Sue Schnitzer said that in conducting background
checks, the bureau talks to ``as many people as we can to learn as
fully about the person as we can; if we know some enemies we talk
to them too.''
   She said the information _ derogatory or favorable _ is
forwarded to the requesting agency ``without comment or
recommendation.''
   Schnitzer refused to discuss the Paisley case, noting that
federal law prohibits the agency from disclosing details of its
background investigations.
   Former White House personnel director E. Pendleton James, who
approved Paisley for nomination, said the Paisley nomination came
in the ``crush of appointees'' during the first year of the Reagan
administration.
   He said he had no recollection of allegations of financial
dishonesty being made against Paisley.
   James said that ``FBI files were very closely held'' by the
office of White House counsel and that if derogatory information
that was found to be credible was raised in the background check
``then we would have a meeting on it, I would be briefed.''
   ``If there was such a meeting'' on Paisley, then the derogatory
information ``was not heavy enough because he was appointed,'' said
James.
   James also said that then-Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger's
office generally ``did a pretty good job of ... wading in and
saying `we want X for this job.'''
   Weinberger has said he had only a ``very indirect'' recollection
of Paisley, pointing out that Paisley was a close friend of Navy
Secretary John Lehman, who had been a consultant at Boeing, where
Paisley worked.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
