<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     06-28 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0536</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<HEAD>Nureyev Celebrated at Paris Opera Ballet Gala</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rudolf Nureyev, the most celebrated ballet
dancer of his time, was honored at the Metropolitan Opera on Monday
for his 50th birthday by the Paris Opera Ballet, which he heads,
and colleagues from his past.
   Nureyev, who hasn't retired from performing, danced in one of
the ballets, ``Song of the Wayfarer.'' Metropolitan Opera soprano
Jessye Norman sang the Mahler song cycle from the orchestra pit and
James Levine conducted.
   Nureyev danced the lead role in 1971 when Maurice Bejart
choreographed ``Song of the Wayfarer.'' He was the wanderer and
Charles Jude the ``other self'' who dances calmly, reaching to him,
trying to lead him to peace.
   Nureyev _ his birthday was three months ago _ looked in splendid
shape and his dancing was effective.
   He acted through his dancing, as he always has done, and the
``presence'' that he projects from the stage has helped make him as
famous as two other great dancers of this century, Vaslav Nijinsky
and Anna Pavlova.
   In the opening dance, Harald Lander's ``Etudes,'' which moves
from ballet practice to all classical ballet technique, the company
looked beautifully schooled. Male stars Laurent Hilare and Manuel
Legris both showed dazzling technique but neither projected
personality.
   The finale was ``Le Grand Defile,'' which dates from 1946, a
processional by the entire company. It was being done for the first
time outside of Paris in Nureyev's honor.
   After the children of the company school and dancers came 11
stars announced by name. Then entered 26 people who have been part
of Nureyev's dance life _ including Miss Piggy, with whom Nureyev
danced on TV's ``The Muppets.''
   He walked in last, embraced each and received great applause
when he greeted Dame Margot Fonteyn, his famous partner with the
British Royal Ballet. When h greeted Mikhail Baryshnikov, the
latter lifted him off his feet.
   Nureyev was the first of the famous Russian dance defectors, in
1961, in Paris. He regularly appeared with the British Royal Ballet
from the mid-1960s through the mid-1970s, danced free-lance after
that and has directed the Paris Opera Ballet since 1983.
   The evening included an American premiere, ``in the middle,
somewhat elevated,'' which William Forsythe choreographed for the
company a year ago. The company Forsythe heads, the Frankfurt
Ballet, performed here earlier in June and did more interesting
ballets than this one.
   Plotless modern ballet sequences were done for nearly half an
hour to music which sounded like a concrete-crushing machine.
Sylvie Guillem managed to look sexy during her solo. At the end,
there were many boos, covered by more cheers when the very fine
dancers bowed.
   Legris, scheduled for ``Etudes'' and ``in the middle, somewhat
elevated,'' also danced with Florence Clerc and Monique Loudieres
in a Marius Petipa pas de trois from ``Paquita'' because Jean-Yves
Lormeau was injured.
   New York Mayor Edward I. Koch presented Nureyev with a crystal
apple, the symbol of New York, after the ``in the middle'' premiere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
