<2ND_LINE>PM-Nunn-Veep,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nunn Says Vice Presidency `Not On Agenda;' Won't Provide
Background Info</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Sam Nunn of Georgia, who has been saying
he doesn't want to be on the Democratic ticket, hardened that
stance by declining to provide financial and other background
information Michael Dukakis campaign is seeking from prospective
running mates.
   Nunn said Monday in a telephone interview he has told Dukakis
he's not interested in the vice presidency, so it would be
inconsistent for him to make such background information available.
   ``He knows my position on the vice presidency,'' Nunn said.
``I've told him, I've told (Dukakis aide Paul) Brountas and others
that that was not on my agenda.''
   Brountas has been heading up the running mate search for Dukakis.
   Sources have identified Nunn as one of several prospective
running mates who have been asked to provide background information
to the Dukakis campaign.
   Nunn refused to confirm that he has been asked for such
information, citing confidentiality in his talks with the
nominee-apparent. But he said he has no plans to provide it.
   ``I'm not furnishing any,'' he said. ``I have not furnished
any.''
   He said, however, that he has a meeting set with Dukakis, who is
coming to Washington on Wednesday to meet with Democratic senators,
including some potential running mates.
   ``I plan to have a discussion with the governor ... on national
security or whatever else he wants to talk about, but I have no
plans to get into the financial information business or the medical
records or any of that stuff,'' Nunn said.
   The Georgia senator is chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee.
   Dukakis said last week that if any of the prospective vice
presidential running mates ruled themselves out ``clearly and
unequivocally, to me, then obviously I'm not going to press the
point.''
   Dukakis made that comment after Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J.,
announced through a spokesman that he was not interested in the job.
</TEXT>
