<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-PrisonProbe     06-28 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Prison Probe,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Administration Seeks Confidentiality On Appraisal Figures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The administration of Gov. Michael Dukakis, in a
change of position, is asking the state attorney general's office
whether it may keep secret the appraised price of land for a state
prison.
   The selection of a prison site in the town of New Braintree is
under investigation by the FBI, and jail opponents and others have
sought to make the controversy an issue in Dukakis' presidential
campaign.
   The state Division of Capital Planning and Operations said
Monday it is awaiting an opinion from Attorney General James
Shannon on whether it can keep two appraisals of the prison site
confidential and divulge publicly only its offering price.
   The value of the property is a key issue to those accusing
Dukakis of favoring the two owners of the proposed prison site.
   Meanwhile, the co-owners of the property in question have hired
a prominent political consultant who has worked for Dukakis, the
likely Democratic nominee.
   And in another development, a Democrat-controlled legislative
committee refused Monday to investigate on its own of the site
selection.
   Last Thursday, the capital planning division's top official,
John Carlson, said of the appraisals: ``As soon as we can share
them with the owners, which is the way the law reads, we will of
course share them with the public.''
   Now the administration is seeking Shannon's opinion on reversing
that stance.
   Kathy Robertson, a spokeswoman for the division, said releasing
the appraised value of the property could harm the state if the
land deal winds up in court. A court case could result if the state
has to purchase the property using the eminent domain process.
   ``We're trying to make public everything we can and we're going
beyond what we would normally do in making everything public,''
Robertson said.
   New Braintree Selectman Dorothea Thomas-Vitrac attacked the
administration for its change of position.
   ``They have, in fact, by backpedaling, created a new
controversy,'' she said.
   The roughly 800 residents of New Braintree have been opposed to
the prison since the proposal first surfaced three years ago.
Questions surrounding the prison intensified when the owners of the
780-acre site offered to sell it to the state in 1986 for $9.5
million, a $6.5 million profit over what they paid a year earlier.
   A Norwood development firm headed by Daniel Striar and Gary
Jacobson owns the land. Jacobson grew up in the same neighborhood
as Dukakis and has been a contributor to Dukakis' political
campaigns.
   The state Legislature's Human Services Committee, in a close
vote, rejected a bipartisan proposal to probe the prison issue and
passed the entire matter to the Senate Ways and Means committee for
a decision.
   ``I see no evidence that there's any collusion, any conflict of
interest,'' said state Rep. Paul Kollios, co-chairman of the
committee.
   Striar and Jacobson have hired political consultant Michael
Goldman to help them respond to the barrage of national publicity
surrounding the land deal. Goldman worked in the Dukakis
administration during the governor's first term and has since
represented numerous prominent Massachusetts Democrats in political
campaigns, including opponents of Dukakis.
   ``The people who are going to want to see conspiracy are going
to see conspiracy everywhere,'' Goldman said.
   He said Striar and Jacobson were referred to him by a top aide
to state auditor Joseph DeNucci, a close ally of Dukakis. DeNucci
is the former co-chairman of the Legislature's Human Services
committee, which deals with prison issues.
   Thomas-Vitrac said the hiring of a political consultant
``indicates to me that they on their own would have problems
justifying their position and they would have to have people come
in and put a spin on things.''
</TEXT>
