<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RailBill     06-28 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rail Bill,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burnley Warns Of Veto If Congress Tampers With Rail Deregulation
Act</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: May be topped.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley is
holding out the threat of a presidential veto if Congress tries to
tamper with the 1980 law that deregulated the railroad industry.
   But Sen. Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., continued to push a bill
doing just that, in anticipation of a meeting today by the Senate
Commerce Committee to act on the measure.
   Congressional and administration aides said Rockefeller was
negotiating with several railroads Monday to try to win their
support.
   The legislation would amend the Staggers Rail Act of 1980 to aid
shippers of coal, grain and other commodities who contend they are
being gouged by railroad monopolies.
   Burnley's message was in the form of a letter written to key
members of the Senate panel on Monday.
   He said in the letter that Rockefeller's measure ``would erode
the substantial gains achieved under the Staggers Act. The
president's senior advisers would recommend a veto of (the
legislation) or a bill resembling this bill if it were presented to
the president for his signature.''
   Many railroads have opposed altering the Staggers Act, which
they say gave them needed pricing and service flexibility to better
compete with trucks. Congress enacted the 1980 law to give Conrail
and other railroads incentives to rebuild failing and antiquated
systems.
   But a coalition of shippers has said the Interstate Commerce
Commission, in its interpretation of Staggers, has failed to
protect shippers, especially those dependent on a single railroad
to transport their wares.
   A key provision of the bill would force the ICC to periodically
adjust its cost index to reflect productivity gains by railroads.
The ICC uses the index to determine how much freight railroads can
increase their rates each quarter to keep up with inflation.
Shippers contend the formula does not account for gains railroads
have made to make them more efficient.
   Burnley sent his letter to Senate Commerce Committee Chairman
Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.; and to Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., the
panel's ranking Republican.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe-Carlucci     06-28 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Carlucci,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Cautions Against Hasty Reforms in Pentagon Contracting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci is urging
against too hasty reform of military procurement, saying ``there is
no way to devise a system that is greed-proof.''
   ``The last thing we need now are hasty, piecemeal changes that
despite good intentions ultimately may make matters worse,''
Carlucci said in a speech Monday at the National Press Club.
   ``I urge those who are ready now to condemn and abandon our
entire procurement system to withhold judgment until the facts are
in, and to keep in mind that no system can offer perfect protection
against the human factor,'' he said. ``There is simply no way to
devise a system that is greed-proof.''
   Carlucci also said that former Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld
and Deputy Defense Secretary David Packard will help him determine
``whether additional changes in the procurement system are in
order'' after the facts are in.
   As many as 100 military contracts may be been tainted because
Pentagon officials and private consultants allegedly provided
classified information to defense contractors to help them bid for
lucrative contracts, according the U.S. attorney coordinating the
case, Henry Hudson.
   Carlucci did urge changes in the way Congress allocates money
for weapons procurement.
   In testimony on Capitol Hill, Carlucci said, he had ``advocated
further reforms. I have said I would sign up for large savings, in
the billions of dollars, if we could put the budgeting and
programming process on a stable course.''
</TEXT>
