<DOCNO> AP880628-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Glance     06-28 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Glance,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Main Issues at Soviet Party Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at the main issues of the 19th
Communist Party conference opening today, as expressed in theses
approved by the policy-making party Central Committee:
   Freer Interparty Debate _ The theses call for freeing political
discussions from previous restrictions as long as they do not lead
to confrontation or disunity. They call for the rehabilitation of
innocent victims of Josef Stalin's purges.
   Economy _ The Central Committee's program urges greater effort
to meet consumer demand, and says that failure to do so is
``especially intolerable.''
   Science and Technology _ An acceleration of progress in science
and technology is crucial to economic progress and therefore to
social renewal of Soviet society, the program says.
   The Communisty Party's Place in Soviet Society _ Party officials
have weakened the economy, government, and the party itself by
interfering in decisions of government councils and economic
managers, according to the report. Party officials should be
limited to two five-year terms of office.
   Government Reform _ Soviets, or government councils, from the
local level to the national Supreme Soviet must be strengthened to
take on responsibility that the party has usurped, the theses
state. Party officials must learn to obey the law and the Soviet
Constitution.
   Ethnic Unrest _ The report says the Soviet Union has done much
to ensure that the country's more than 100 ethnic groups get along.
But it says the issue requires constant attention and that disputes
will be settled on the basis of ``genuine democracy.''
   Legal and Judicial Reform _ Reforms of the legal and judicial
systems must ensure individual rights and the rule of law rather
than the rule of individual leaders, the Central Committee says.
   Social Organizations _ Groups such as unions, the Young
Communist League, cooperatives and others should be given more
power to initiate legislation and cooperate with government to
solve social problems, the report says.
   External Affairs _ The report says foreign policy in the past
too often emphasized military rather than political responses, and
that Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policies take into account the
realities of the nuclear age.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
