<DOCNO> AP880628-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0309EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NorCalQuake     06-28 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NorCal Quake,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Sends Skyscrapers Swaying, But Causes Little Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM SCHIFFMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney Anthony Smith was delivering
closing arguments in court when a strong earthquake shook a
160-mile stretch of coastal Northern California, swaying
skyscapers, shattering glass and dumping store shelves.
   ``As you can see, my argument is reaching the powers that be,''
Smith deadpanned Monday, according to his associate, Reid Dworkin,
who said spectators ran out of the courtroom and the judge briefly
recessed the trial.
   The temblor, the second to rock the state in two days,
registered about 5.7 on the Richter scale, according to University
of California seismologists.
   No injuries or serious damage was reported.
   Pat Jorgenson, a spokeswoman with the U.S. Geological Survey in
Menlo Park, said the epicenter of the 11:43 a.m. quake was 16 miles
south of San Jose, near Loma Prieta Mountain on the San Andreas
Fault.
   The quake was one of the strongest in the San Francisco Bay area
on the San Andreas Fault since the ``Great Earthquake'' of 1906,
said Robert Uhrhammer at the University of California Seismographic
Stations at Berkeley. That quake, which started fires that
destroyed much of the city, had an estimated magnitude of 8.3 on
the Richter scale, which had not yet been devised.
   The 650-mile-long San Andreas Fault annually produces dozens of
quakes.
   A quake measuring 5 can cause considerable damage, while a
magnitude 6 quake can cause severe damage.
   Most people in quake-prone Northern California took the shaking
in stride, but others found it unnerving.
   On the 17th floor of the Federal Building, Oakland Hells Angels
member James ``Fuzzy'' Neal said there was ``a little bit of
panic'' in a courtroom where a drug trial was under way.
   ``It's bad enough being in a two-story house when one goes off.
I knew I couldn't run down the steps and get out,'' Neal said.
   But Ginger Johnson, a receptionist for Montgomery Securities on
the 21st floor of the landmark Transamerica building, said workers
were so unconcerned that ``our traders immediately started betting
on how big it was.'' The 48-floor pyramid-shaped tower was built to
withstand far more powerful temblors.
   In Sunnyvale, 40 miles to the south, chunks of cement fell from
the ceiling of a parking garage.
   At the Holy City Art Glass shop near the epicenter and just 100
yards from the San Andreas Fault, sheets of glass flew off racks
and stained glass windows leaning against a wall toppled and broke,
causing about $400 in damage, said artist Tom Stanton.
   Groceries at a 7-Eleven at Scotts Valley fell off shelves and
customers ``were thrown up against the outside wall,'' said clerk
Judy Young. Damage also was reported at a nearby supermarket.
   On Sunday, an earthquake measuring 4.5 to 4.7 on the Richter
scale shook a wide area of Southern California, including downtown
Los Angeles, but no serious damage was reported. At least four
people were treated for minor injuries.
   Monday's quake was felt as far north as Santa Rosa, about 60
miles north of San Francisco, and to the south about 100 miles away
on the Monterey Peninsula. Although Berkeley scientists upgraded
their magnitude from an earlier reading of about 5.0, other
agencies stuck to a lower estimate.
   The U.S. Geological Survey's National Earthquake Information
Center in Golden, Colo., estimated the magnitude at 5.0, as did the
survey's Menlo Park office.
   Estimates differ because the earthquake information center based
its estimate on body waves generated by the quake, while the
Seismographic Stations' figure is based on measurement of surface
waves, Jacobs said.
   The Richter scale gauges the energy released by an earthquake,
as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph. Each
increase of one number means the ground motion was 10 times greater.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
