<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Woman'sClub     06-28 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Woman's Club,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women's Club Charged With Discrimination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of the Woman's National Democratic
Club will vote Wednesday on allowing its 85 male members to vote or
hold office, and the club's president says the governing board has
recommended approval.
   The 66-year-old club was the target Monday of a discrimination
complaint filed by George Washington University law professor John
F. Banzhaf III.
   His complaint was filed with the District of Columbia's Office
of Human Rights ``to encourage the vote'' to give the club's male
members the same status in the organization as its 1,815 women
members, Banzhaf said.
   Jean Jenson, the club's president, said she was surprised to
learn about Banzhaf's complaint because ``we have had absolutely no
contact with him at all.''
   If Banzhaf had contacted the group, he would have learned the
club's governing board has already recommended approval of the
proposed change in the by-laws, Jenson said.
   ``We were kind of amazed he didn't do his homework on this,''
she said.
   The complaint follows separate decisions this month by the
capital's last all-male clubs _ the Cosmos Club and the
Metropolitan Club _ to admit women.
   Banzhaf had also filed a complaint against the Cosmos Club and
said he will ask city authorities to make sure the group's decision
to admit women goes beyond mere tokenism.
   Jenson said men have been club members since the 1930s. ``Men
have never indicated an interest in holding office here because
this is a volunteer organization,'' she said.
   Under D.C. law, a discrimination complaint is investigated by
the Office of Human Rights to determine if there is probable cause
to submit it to the D.C. Human Rights Commission. The law calls for
attempts at conciliation between the parties before a complaint is
sent to the commission.
   As a party to the Cosmos Club complaint, Banzhaf said he will
push for either an affirmative action program for admitting women
or the long-term monitoring of the club's membership policies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
