<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NIH-AIDSAccident     06-28 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIH-AIDS Accident,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NIH Employee Infected With AIDS Virus In Laboratory Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Institutes of Health employee was
infected with the deadly AIDS virus at work despite taking
recommended precautions, according to a published report today.
   The Washington Post reported that the NIH employee became
infected despite wearing gloves and following recommended
procedures.
   NIH officials said the employee was infected when a vial filled
with AIDS-infected blood broke in the worker's hand.
   Officials said the accident occurred a few weeks ago, and one
NIH scientist said the accident involved a safety device that is
supposed to reduce the risk of just the kind of accident that
occurred.
   ``It's there so this type of thing won't happen,'' the scientist
told the Post.
   There have been two similar incidents involving workers at
laboratories associated with NIH, but officials said this is the
first accident involving an NIH employee.
   Officials said the employee, who still works at NIH, was
diagnosed as being infected with the virus by the Clinical Center
at NIH on Monday afternoon and is receiving medical treatment. The
newspaper said officials declined to discuss specifics of the
accident and requested the employee's gender and job title be
withheld.
   Other NIH employees were informed about the accident Monday.
   Recent figures from the federal Centers for Disease Control
indicate the rate of accidental infection with the AIDS virus among
health care workers is only a fraction of 1 percent, with only 15
documented cases following accidents involving contamination from
needles or broken glass.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, attacks the body's
immune system. No one is known to have recovered from the illness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
