<DOCNO> AP880628-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BishopsConference Bjt   06-28 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bishops Conference, Bjt,0657</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Bishops Decide To Formulate New Paper On AIDS Education</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM KRATTENMAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLLEGEVILLE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Roman Catholic bishops
decided to revamp their stand on fighting AIDS to quell a division
within the church, but stopped short of condemning a paper that
tolerates teaching about condoms.
   The National Conference of Catholic Bishops concluded Monday by
unanimously approving a decision to appoint a committee to draft a
new AIDS paper. The updated document would be drawn in closer
consultation with the Vatican and acceptable to the entire
conference, church leaders said after a closed session at St.
John's University.
   ``The division among ourselves, the teachers, is reflected among
the people,'' said a statement released by Cardinal Joseph
Bernardin of Chicago, who made the motion for the new paper. ``We
cannot allow it to continue festering. Our unity must be restored
so we can get on with our business.''
   ``The Many Faces of AIDS _ A Gospel Approach'' was approved by
the conference's administrative board and released last December
but stirred controversy with the portion about condoms.
   While stressing abstinence from sex outside marriage and
fidelity within marriage, the statement noted that many in society
reject church teachings on sexuality and said education programs
could include ``accurate information about prophylactic devices''
as a means of preventing transmission of the deadly disease.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is spread mainly by the
exchange of blood or semen during sexual contact or by intravenous
drug use.
   A Vatican official charged the authors with causing confusion in
the church, which objects to birth control.
   Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, head of the Vatican Congregation for
the Doctrine of the Faith, also chastised the administrative board
that approved the paper for not consulting with the Vatican.
   Bernardin told the news conference that when the administrative
board approved the ``Many Faces'' paper, ``we sincerely felt it was
based on sound theology.
   ``Now some questions have risen whether the document does have
some ambiguities. Those points have to be discussed,'' he said.
   Bernardin said the new policy paper can ``put to rest any doubts
which might exist regarding the church's teaching on sexuality and
how that teaching applies to the current crisis.''
   But conference leaders did not retract the paper as some critics
urged. Rather, they said it should be a foundation for the
still-to-be appointed authors of the new paper.
   ``We're not replacing it. The first document stands,'' said
Archbishop John May of St. Louis. ``This new document will be a
document of the whole conference, all the bishops together.''
   An outright scrapping of the paper, Bernardin said, also would
have sowed dissension among bishops.
   ``Withdrawal could give the impression that the entire document
is flawed and that the entire administrative board was in serious
error,'' he said. ``Such action could reopen the debate with
greater intensity.''
   May apologized for the administrative board's ``mistake'' in
releasing the AIDS document before the full conference of roughly
300 bishops could review it.
   On the other hand, he said, ``Many bishops were clamoring for
something to use in their general communities.''
   May said he hoped a new policy could be drafted for
consideration at the next conference, to be held in November in
Washington, D.C. He said some of the authors of the first paper
might be appointed to work on the second.
   In previous business at the four-day conference, the bishops
approved a a report about the morality of U.S. nuclear policy,
opposing arms build-ups but stopping short of taking a strong stand
on disarmament. The bishops also said they didn't think it was
morally wrong to pursue research on the ``Star Wars'' defense
initiative, but said they couldn't endorse deploying such a system.
   The bishops also approved a campaign to raise $20 million to
help orders support their retired members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
