<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     06-28 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans Warned of Poisoning Danger From Imported Ceramic Ware</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seemingly safe ceramic ware commonly used at
dinner tables, particularly plates and pots from abroad, may
threaten owners with deadly lead poisoning and authorities can do
little to check the hazard, federal officials told Congress.
   Frank E. Young, head of the Food and Drug Administration, told a
congressional hearing on Monday that despite stepped-up efforts,
the agency can never check each shipment of ceramics and is not
authorized to inspect foreign products.
   ``The thousands of trucks and automobiles crossing the border
simply cannot be effectively inspected or their cargos tested for
lead,'' said Young.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., who chaired the hearing of the oversight
and investigations panel of the House Energy and Commerce
Committee, said there are ``serious deficiencies'' in the FDA's
efforts to control ceramic ware.
   However, Wyden said a major part of the hearing was educational.
``Without adequate education about this problem, many individuals
will continue to purchase dangerous items for food service,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Anti-Khomeini Marchers Cite Recent Military Victories in Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 2,700 opponents of the Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini marched to the White House to mark the seventh anniversary
of their group's expulsion from Iran and to celebrate a recent
military victory along the Iran-Iraq border.
   Two members of Congress addressed the rally Monday, comparing
the exiled People's Mujahedeen of Iran ``freedom fighters'' the
