<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0240EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>b i AM-France-TrainCrash 6thLd-Writethru a0456 06-28 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Train Crash, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0456,0816</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Train Crash in Paris Station Kills at Least 37</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE death toll. Picks up 4th graf
pvs, `Philippe Rouvillois...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR10, 12, 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commuter train whose brakes apparently failed
slammed into another train at an underground platform of a busy
Paris station, killing at least 37 people and injuring 32,
officials said.
   It was the worst train accident ever in the capital, authorities
said. The death toll was expected to mount to 40 once all the
bodies were removed from the twisted wreckage.
   Officials said the eight-car commuter train, coming from the
southeastern suburb of Melun, rammed into the front of a four-car
train that was preparing to leave an underground terminus at the
Gare de Lyon station in eastern Paris.
   Philippe Rouvillois, president of the railroad authority, known
as the SNCF, said the moving train had a ``braking problem'' and
its driver alerted passengers to move to the rear.
   ``When the driver noticed a problem with the brakes, he asked
travelers in the train to move toward the back,'' Rouvillois said.
   He said the train went about 500-600 yards past a red light as
it was approaching the Gare de Lyon, one of the busiest train
stations in Paris. The Gare de Lyon is a stop for the city's
subways and handles commuter traffic as well as intercity trains.
   An unknown number of bodies remained inside the wreckage. Fire
officials said they thought all survivers had been removed. It was
not immediately known if any Americans were among the victims.
   At least 15 people were seriously injured, officials said.
   Passengers in shock wandered through the station or sat on the
platform beside the twisted wreckage.
   About 250 rescue workers struggled through the night, sawing
through the tangle of metal looking for more survivors. Forty fire
engines, 15 ambulances and a helicopter were at the station.
   Police said it would be several hours before the last bodies
were freed. They said both trains were crowded with commuters when
the accident occurred at 7:10 p.m. (1:10 p.m. EDT) but the total
number of passengers was not known.
   Rescuers pulled the first body from one of the cars about two
hours after the accident. Witnesses said the impact of the speeding
train hitting the one parked on the tracks forced the cars of the
first train into and on top of one another.
   The French news agency, Agence France-Presse, quoted railway
authority officials as saying the inbound train was moving at 45 to
50 mph when it entered the station.
   In addition, train authority officials said the train leaving
Paris was several minutes behind schedule.
   The state prosecutor for Paris, Michel Raynaud, opened an
investigation into the cause of the accident.
   Police cordoned off the area, but from an adjacent platform it
was possible to see the twisted wreckage and the emergency medical
center set up to treat the injured.
   Authorities said the cause of the accident had not been
determined. Officials of the state-owned railroad Societe Nationale
Chemin de Fer said the moving train might have entered the
underground track too fast and been unable to stop.
   Patrick Michelin, director of the Gare de Lyon, said the
arriving eight-car train may have had brake trouble.
   ``It looks like we have a problem with brakes and we have to
find out the origin of it,'' he said.
   Transport Minister Louis Mermaz, Mayor Jacques Chirac of Paris
and police chief Jean Paolini went to the station to oversee the
rescue and preliminary investigation.
   On the platform beside the tangled steel, medical workers cared
for a dozen injured passengers. Some lay on stretchers, bleeding
badly. A sheet covered a child's body.
   The conducter of the stationary train, who was not injured,
said: ``All at once I saw the train coming toward me at high speed
and I had just enough time to jump onto the platform.''
   A person who saw the accident from the platform said: ``The
shock was extremely violent and the noise was enormous and
resounding. I was on the platform when I saw the train arrive,
running at what seemed to be an extremely high speed.
   ``I told myself, `It isn't possible; it will stop.' But it
smashed into the other that was parked. Two cars were completely
flattened. On the platform, people began to panic and then run in
all directions.''
   Raoul Viger, commanding the fire brigades, said the rescue task
was difficult because, ``to get to the living trapped in the cars,
we have to crawl over dead bodies.''
   As news of the accident spread, hundreds of people arrived at
the station looking for family members and friends, police said.
</TEXT>
