<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-28 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slides, Stocks Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped below the 131-yen level in
foreign exchange trading in Tokyo on Tuesday, while stock prices
fell marginally.
   The dollar opened at 130.48 yen, down from Monday's close of
131.70. It mainly fluctuated between a low of 130.38 and a high of
131.25 before finishing the day at 130.95.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 121.20-point loser Monday, shed another 36.92
points, or 0.13 percent, to close at 27,398.09 points.
   Shunsuke Kato, a dealer at the Bank of Tokyo, said local
investors sold the dollar in early morning trading following an
overnight decline in New York, which he said was ``triggered by
intervention on the part of the U.S. Federal Reserve Board.''
   The move ``gave us the impression that there would be a limit on
the dollar's rise,'' Kato said.
   One analyst at a major local securities firm, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said Tuesday's early drop in the dollar was
only a slight correction. He said the currency's rise above the
131.00-yen level in the past week was too fast, adding that
``dealers are more likely to buy the currency in the mid-130 yen
point.''
   The analyst predicted the dollar would continue to gain ground
against the yen this week, and said ``dealers will probably test
even the 135.00-yen level because the Bank of Japan has said it
will not intervene.''
   However, Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa on Tuesday told a
regular news conference that the recent dollar rise was ordinary
fluctuation, and said the central bank will step into the market if
necessary.
   The Monday dollar closing capped a six-day winning streak during
which the currency rose by a total of 4.82 yen. It was the highest
finish for the dollar since Dec. 10, when it closed at 132.18 yen.
</TEXT>
