<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Politburo     06-28 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Politburo,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Politburo: Arguments in the Kremlin, Special Privileges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-Soviet-Party, Bjt
^By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Mikhail S. Gorbachev's ruling Politburo
engage in arguments during their closed-door meetings that
sometimes render the body deadlocked, the editor-in-chief of the
party daily Pravda says.
   The editor, Viktor G. Afanasyev, was one of two Communist Party
insiders to shine the light of glasnost on the Politburo, offering
a rare glimpse of the privileges and rigors that come with
membership in the inner circle.
   Also discussing the party's pinnacle with foreign reporters
Monday was Igor Shvets, an official on its policy-making Central
Committee.
   He acknowledged that Politburo members earn more than four times
the average factory worker's pay, saying they don't stand in line
for potatoes because ``they are always on duty.''
   Despite Gorbachev's policy of ``glasnost,'' which has opened
many facets of Soviet society to scrutiny, little is known about
how the country's supreme political institution functions.
   The Politburo customarily issues a laconic statement following
its regular Thursday meetings, but it never provides a detailed
account.
   Afanasyev said he has attended Politburo meetings under both
Gorbachev and the late President Leonid I. Brezhnev. He said
Gorbachev's Politburo bears little relationship to Brezhnev's,
whose members ``would talk for an hour, and they'd rubber stamp the
decision, and that was that.''
   The editor disclosed that after the Chernobyl nuclear power
plant explosion in April 1986, the Politburo met in emergency
session for 1{ days to discuss the crisis.
   ``There aren't any basic controversies or contradictions up
there,'' Afanasyev said of the Politburo. ``The need for
perestroika is not being questioned. ... But there is argument;
there is discussion, there is sometimes heated discussion. There's
been a lot of protracted argument sometimes.''
   Shvets suggested crisis management is not unusual for the
Kremlin's top leadership. ``There is no day or night for them,'' he
said. ``They are always on duty.''
   Dissenting views among members of the Politburo and of the
party's second-most powerful institution, the Secretariat, have
sometimes left the groups deadlocked, Afanasyev said.
   ``Sometimes a session of the Politburo or Secretariat cannot
resolve the issue in its entirety because there are different
opinions,'' he said. ``Then the question is looked into in greater
depth, and only after it's analyzed in all its aspects is the final
decision taken.''
   Alluding to reports that Politburo members enjoy access to
special stores that carry commodities not generally available in
this country and that they have hard-to-find foodstuffs delivered
to their homes, Shvets added, ``It wouldn't make sense to have them
stand in line for potatoes.''
   However, he insisted, ``They have no special privileges. The
only privileges they have are related to their protection,'' he
said, citing secluded country retreats known as dachas as an
example.
   Shvets said the perquisites of Politburo members did not change
when Gorbachev's came to power in March 1985.
   He also said they earn about the same as a government minister,
$1,350 to $1,700 a month. A typical Soviet factory worker makes
about $340 a month.
   Afanasyev said there is a formal 10- to 15-minute limit on how
long each Politburo member can have the floor, but that members
often get around the rule by seeking the floor several times.
   He denied the Politburo is split into camps with some members
following Gorbachev and others siding with Yegor K. Ligachev, the
Kremlin's No. 2, who is seen as a conservative force in the ruling
body.
   He did say, however, that members display different outlooks
depending on whether they are career Communist Party officials like
Gorbachev or technocrats, people who rose from the ranks of
administration or plant management.
   Some people, he said, reached the Politburo or the Secretariat,
which runs the party and nation from day to day, ``from what you
might call the technocracy. Others have been party functionaries
all their lives, and of course, the way various questions are
discussed, the inflections, if you will, will be different.
   ``This is the only area where I see a divergence of opinion, but
not on political issues.''
   Afanasyev did not say which party leaders he was referring to
when he mentioned technocrats, but under Gorbachev, many men with a
strong background in economic management, including Premier Nikolai
I. Ryzhkov, a former factory director, have assumed top
responsibilities in the party and government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
