<1ST_LINE>u i BC-U.S.OfficerKilled 3rdLd-Writethru a0496 06-28 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-U.S. Officer Killed, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0496,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Attache Killed By Bomb</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. military attache to Greece was
killed Tuesday by a car bomb that blew his armor-plated automobile
off the small side street where he lives, officials said.
   A police spokesman, who requested anonymity, identified the
victim as Navy Capt. William Nordine. Neighbors said he apparently
was driving to work.
   A Pentagon spokesman in Washington, Maj. Alan Frietag, did not
release an identity, but said the senior military officer assigned
to the U.S. embassy in Athens, a Navy captain, was killed in a bomb
blast near his home.
   The explosion occurred at 8:06 a.m. (1:06 a.m. EDT) in the
Kefalari district of the northern Athens suburb of Kifissia, where
many American and foreign diplomats live.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility.
   The bomb had been placed in the trunk of a parked car and the
force of the explosion decapitated Nordine and sent him through a
side window of his car, police said.
   They said the explosion lodged the officer's car in a steel
fence across the street.
   U.S. embassy officials on the scene refused to comment, but
people living in the neighborhood said Nordine was apparently
driving to work.
   ``He lived up the street with his wife and children. He drove to
work around this time every day,'' said a person living nearby,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The booby-trapped car was destroyed in the blast, which was felt
for miles around the area, shattering windows in surrounding homes.
   Frietag said that at about 1:15 a.m. EDT ``a bomb exploded near
the home of the U.S. defense attache. He was in a car and the bomb
exploded outside the car. He was killed in the explosion.''
</TEXT>
