<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Tyson-Spinks-Scene 1stLd-Writethru a0492 06-28 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tyson-Spinks-Scene, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0492,0711</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>From Ringside To Rafters, Fans Enjoy The Fight `Scene'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS graf after 2nd and SUBS 10th pvs, `Actor Sean ...'
with two grafs to UPDATE with report that Sean Penn slammed a TV
cameraman into an elevator door.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   A longer version moving on sports wires
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It took just 91 seconds for boxing
champion Michael Tyson to knock out Michael Spinks, but it took 47
minutes to introduce all the celebrities at ringside.
   Talk about a sideshow.
   Actor Sean Penn reportedly slammed a TV cameraman into an
elevator door.
   Frank Sinatra rubbed elbows with actors Don Johnson, Chuck
Norris and Bruce Willis. Young actors Matthew Broderick and Judd
Nelson drew adoring screams from young fans in the crowd.
   Comedians Richard Pryor and David Brenner mingled with singers
Natalie Cole and Sheena Easton at the Convention Center.
   Boxing legends were plentiful Monday night, including Joe
Frazier, Sugar Ray Leonard and Marvelous Marvin Hagler. Muhammad
Ali received the longest standing ovation of any celebrity
introduced under the hot lights.
   But Tyson's wife, actress Robin Givens, was booed, probably in
response to reports that the marriage was on the shakes. But top
``hate award'' honors went to New York Yankees' principal owner
George Steinbrenner, who was booed so loudly that ring announcer
Michael Butler had to hesitate a minute before continuing the
``beautiful people'' roll call.
   The host of the extravaganza, Donald Trump, and his wife, Ivana,
chose to sit next to a presidential candidate, Jesse Jackson. In
the hubbub, secret service agents pushed and shoved to form a human
chain around the Democratic hopeful.
   At a prefight cocktail party, Trump toasted his celebrity guests
with champagne and fancy foods. In what seemed worlds away, fans
who truly cared about the fight's outcome took the day off from
work and paid $300 each for their rafter seats, enjoying prefight
meals of beer and junk food.
   In the end, the fan in the stand probably had less heartburn
than the entertainers.
   Penn and his movie star wife, Madonna, literally ran in and out
of the cocktail party at the Trump Plaza Hotel _ without a bite to
eat _ after dozens of reporters and photographers descended upon
the couple. Madonna grinned in delight; Penn looked annoyed.
   As a crowd of photographers went into action, Penn said,
``That's it man,'' then grabbed a TV cameraman by the shoulders and
pushed him into an elevator door, according to the New York Daily
News.
   Comedian Milton Berle tried taking bites of his gourmet dinner
in between interviews, but ultimately sent his food back to the
kitchen.
   ``It was cold,'' he said, shrugging.
   Actors Warren Beatty, Jack Nicholson and singer Paul Simon
grinned at each other in amusement as the same pack of journalists
fell onto the table in front of them. Blinking their eyes at the
hundreds of flashbulbs and only smiling in response to questions,
they, too, didn't eat a bite.
   Nicholson, a veteran of these prefight parties, came prepared
with his own bottle of mineral water.
   Outside the din, up in the rafters, Debbie McPhee and her
daughter, Noel, of Wheatfield, Ind., relaxed before the main bout.
   ``We had calzone for dinner on the Boardwalk,'' Noel said.
   Both were delighted with the view from their seats, almost in
the last row.
   A few rows away, Joe Paone sat with five other men, from Hudson,
N.Y. They had crammed into a van the night before, drove seven
hours to Atlantic City and had beer for dinner.
   ``This is a mission,'' Paone said. ``Maybe we'll have a piece of
pizza after the fight.''
   The $300 price tag on their seats did not bother the diehard
fans.
   It also didn't bother the celebrities who were Trump's guests.
   ``They let me in for nothing,'' joked comedian Jackie Mason.
``At these prices, I'll watch anything.''
   Comedian Billy Crystal, however, said, ``I'm a big fight fan.
... I'm glad to be here. If I wasn't doing what I'm doing in life,
I wouldn't be here. It's the price you pay for being here.''
</TEXT>
