<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-28 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollars Drops After Record Performance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar today dropped from a six-month record
high posted the previous day, while stock prices on the Tokyo
exchange closed slightly lower after rebounding from heavy
early-morning losses.
   The dollar opened the day's trading at 130.48 yen, down a strong
1.22 yen from Monday's close of 131.70. It moved mainly between a
low of 130.38 and a high of 131.25 before finishing the day at
130.95 yen.
   King Ogino, a dealer at Goldman Sachs, said the dollar's loss
against the yen was driven by a comment from Finance Minister
Kiichi Miyazawa, who during a regular press conference dismissed
recent currency changes as ordinary fluctuations. The minister said
the central bank would step into the market if necessary.
   Ogino said the statement led to ``depressed dollar-selling at
the 130.80-130.90-yen level'' and further profit-taking sent the
currency to about 130.85 yen before it rebounded slightly.
   Today's loss snapped the dollar's six-day winning streak during
which the currency rose by a total of 4.82 yen. Monday's close of
131.70 yen was the highest finish for the dollar since Dec. 10,
when it closed at 132.18 yen. The next day, the currency tumbled to
128.75 yen.
   Ogino said the mood on the foreign exchange market for the rest
of the week would be dictated by movements of the central bank.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, meanwhile, the Nikkei Stock Average
of 225 selected issues, a 121.20-point loser Monday, regained lost
ground following heavy morning losses. But it still ended the day
at 27,398.09, down 36.92 points, or 0.13 percent.
   The main market barometer had dipped 257.47 points by
mid-morning but climbed back, led mainly by large-capital issues,
including steels and low-priced blue chip stocks, traders said.
   Volume on the first section was estimated at 2.5 billion shares,
nearly three times the 850 million shares that changed hands Monday.
</TEXT>
