<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-28 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Drenches Southwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms lingered in the Southwest
today after spawning a twister in New Mexico, drenching an Air
Force base in San Antonio, Texas, and flooding streets in a Texas
county.
   The Northeast, north-central states and much of the Pacific
Northwest enjoyed cool weather, but it was still warm in the
northern Plains and the South, where 10 temperature records were
broken or tied Monday.
   Rain today extended from Arizona to Texas. A few showers and
thunderstorms also fell on the northern Rockies, as well as western
South Dakota and northwest Minnesota, two states hit by the
drought. Showers and isolated thunderstorms fell across north
Florida.
   The strongest Southwestern storms were clustered between
Cotulla, Del Rio and San Antonio, Texas. More than 2{ inches of
rain drenched Randolph Air Force Base in San Antonio in less than
an hour Monday night, and urban flooding occurred in eastern Bexar
County.
   A tornado touched down 15 miles north of Carlsbad, N.M., on
Monday night, but no damage was reported.
   In Florida, evening storms unleashed wind gusting to 55 mph and
hail as big as ping pong balls that damaged car windshields near
Cherry Lake.
   Temperatures dipped into the 40s in the northern Applachians,
and the 40s and 50s were common in Oregon and Washington state.
Temperatures were mostly in the 50s from the Great Lakes to the
upper Ohio Valley and the northern and middle Atlantic Coast.
   In Youngstown, Ohio, it was 45 degrees early today, tying the
record low for the date set in 1970.
   By contrast, temperatures were in the 80s in sections of the
northern Plains and the Gulf Coast, with a few readings in the 90s
across the desert Southwest.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from the Pacific Northwest to the Colorado Rockies, the southern
High Plains and Texas; scattered showers and thunderstorms from the
northern Great Lakes into New England, and across much of the
Florida Peninsula; and mostly sunny, dry conditions for the rest of
the nations.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 80s or 90s for much of
the nation; the 60s and 70s across the Pacific Northwest and from
the upper Great Lakes to the upper Ohio Valley and New England; and
100 to 105 degrees in the Rio Grande Valley, the Northern
California valleys and the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees at Bradford, Pa., to 94 degrees at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 71 fair; Boston 60 partly cloudy; Buffalo 56
fair; Charleston, S.C. 66 fair; Cincinnati 56 fair; Cleveland 53
fair; Detroit 58 fair; Miami 77 fair; New York 64 fair;
Philadelphia 61 fair; Pittsburgh 52 fair; Portland, Maine 55
cloudy; Washington 68 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 77 partly cloudy; Chicago 64 fair;
Dallas-Fort Worth 83 partly cloudy; Denver 68 fair; Des Moines 66
fair; Indianapolis 63 fair; Kansas City 68 fair; Minneapolis-St.
