<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     06-28 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Won't Let Defense Call Meese in Wedtech Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Bronx borough president denied taking
even ``one cent'' from anyone at Wedtech Corp., and the judge ruled
that Attorney General Edwin Meese III can't be called as a defense
witness.
   The former Bronx leader, Stanley Simon, who is on trial with
Rep. Mario Biaggi and five others for alleged corruption involving
the defense contractor, took the witness stand in his own defense
Monday.
   Also Monday, U.S. District Judge Constance Baker Motley said
testimony from Meese or a former top aide, whom the defense also
wanted to call, was ``irrelevant to this case.''
   The defense maintains that it was Meese and others with ties to
the Reagan administration _ not the defendants _ who ``acted
corruptly'' in helping Wedtech obtain no-bid government contracts.
   The defense says Wedtech officials had links to Meese through
San Francisco attorney E. Robert Wallach, a longtime Meese friend
under indictment for allegedly taking money from Wedtech to
influence the attorney general. Meese has not been charged with any
wrongdoing.
   But prosecutors in the 17-week-old trial asserted the request
was ``a very obvious effort to confuse and divert the jurors.''
   Simon, Biaggi, Biaggi's eldest son, Richard, and four others are
charged with turning the now-bankrupt Bronx company into a
racketeering enterprise that paid millions of dollars in bribes to
obtain the minority set-aside contracts.
   In addition to Meese, the defense wanted to call former Meese
aide and Wedtech employee James Jenkins.
   ``It is imperative now to show the actual extent of Meese's and
Jenkins' corrupt involvement in this matter,'' Dominic Amorosa,
attorney for Richard Biaggi, wrote the judge last week. ``Only by
doing this will Richard Biaggi be able to present a full picture of
the scheme to frame him and his father.''
   In a letter opposing the defense request, Assistant U.S.
Attorney Howard Wilson said it was ``in reality, an attempt to
cause a minitrial on the issue of the guilt of the attorney
general.''
   Wilson asked Motley not to allow Amorosa ``to turn this
proceeding into a circus, from a trial of his client and Mario
Biaggi into a trial of Ed Meese and others.''
   Earlier, Simon, the first defendant to testify, said he never
took bribes or kickbacks.
   ``Absolutely not,'' said Simon, who is accused of demanding
$50,000 in cash, campaign and charitable contributions from Wedtech
in return for his help in obtaining a city lease for the company.
   Simon denied ever making the request of Wedtech Chairman Fred
Neuberger, who testified for the government in exchange for
leniency.
   ``Did you ever get a cent _ one cent in cash from any Wedtech
person?'' asked defense attorney Maurice Nessen.
   ``No!'' Simon replied.
   He said his 1985 re-election campaign received two checks
totaling $15,000 from Neuberger and his partner, John Mariotta, who
is also a defendant in the trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
