<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     06-28 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold ,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls on Reported Intervention, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped rapidly in moderate trading
today following reports that European central banks moved in
concert to stem its rise.
   Gold prices were higher.
   Dealers said the central banks of West Germany, Britain, France,
Italy and Switzerland sold dollars in the market to prevent the
currency from rising further.
   The dollar had reached its highest levels in eight months
against European currencies, buoyed by lack of central bank
intervention and strong demand, particularly from Japan.
   Today's intervention followed reported dollar sales by the U.S.
Federal Reserve on Monday.
   ``For the first time in months, we seem to see something like a
coordinated intervention,'' one dealer at a West German bank said
on condition of anonymity.
   A senior trader with a major Italian commercial bank in Rome
said: ``The central banks are making it loud and clear they want a
dollar below 1.80 marks for the moment.''
   Another trader in Italy argued that the dollar's recent rise had
been too swift for central banks and the reported intervention
should be seen as a signal to the market to calm down.
   ``Today's joint effort by central banks was designed to deflate
the dollar slightly. But the market still remains bullish on the
dollar,'' he said.
   But the West German dealer said the market's sentiment on the
dollar already has cooled a bit, with most dealers seeing the
currency as overbought.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday,
were:
   _1.7965 West German marks, down from 1.8185
   _1.4880 Swiss francs, down from 1.5050
   _6.0625 French francs, down from 6.1385
   _2.0293 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0460
   _1,335.00 Italian lire, down from 1,353.48
   _1.2065 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2075
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7272, stronger
than $1.7030 Monday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.75 yen to a closing 130.95. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 129.97 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $443.75 a troy ounce, up
from late Monday's $441.50. At mid-morning today, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $443.85.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $444.00, up from $443.00 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.16 to close at a bid of
$446.30.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.96 a troy
ounce, up from Monday's $6.84.
</TEXT>
