<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pope-Plot 1stLd-Writethru a0524 06-28 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope-Plot, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0524,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Austrians Say Papal Plot was Hoax, but Two Arrested</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Austrians calling plot a hoax,
no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The interior minister said today that two
Turks had been arrested for claiming they wanted to kill Pope John
Paul II and accused the two of perpetrating a hoax to gain
publicity.
   ``During the papal visit, there was no attempted
assassination,'' Interior Minister Karl Blecha told reporters
following a Cabinet meeting today. On Monday, the pontiff ended a
five-day Austrian pilgrimage.
   A U.S. television network reported Monday that a plot to
assassinate John Paul during the recent visit was uncovered and
foiled in Vienna.
   But Blecha, whose ministry oversees many police and security
functions, said the plot was nothing more than a hoax to ``to grab
the attention of the world news media.''
   ABC News quoted unidentified sources as saying two Turks were
the prime suspects in the alleged assassination attempt that was to
have taken place last Thursday, the first day of the visit.
   The network reported that the assassination attempt was to take
place as the pope arrived at St. Stephens Cathedral in Vienna. It
said it had learned that police believed shots were to be fired
from a construction site across from the cathedral.
   ABC News said the Austrian government had confirmed that,
following a tip, its anti-terrorist police found photographs ``that
show several sniper positions in the building plus firing angles to
the square.''
   The network said police apparently foiled the alleged plot when
they raided an Islamic prayer building used primarily by Turkish
immigrants.
   Speaking of the pair's arrest two days before the pope arrived
in Vienna, Blech said: ``No weapons were found, only a warning
pistol unable to shoot bullets.
   ``They were arrested and charged with faking a criminal act but
were not kept in jail,'' he said.
   The interior minister did not identify them or say where they
were.
   According to Blecha, one of the suspects told police on June 13
that an attempt on the pope's life was planned. After further
investigation, police discovered the second man, who turned out to
be the first suspect's accomplice, Blecha said.
   It was not immediately clear why they sought the publicity or
how they may have intended to escape responsibility themselves.
   In Ankara, Yahya Kucuk, head of the political division of
Turkey's General Directorate of Security, said officials had no
information or query from Vienna in connection with Turks involved
in a foiled plot against the pope.
   In 1981, a Turkish terrorist shot and wounded the pope in St.
Peter's Square in Rome.
</TEXT>
