<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0755EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EmbattledEditor     06-28 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Embattled Editor,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Civil Libertarians Support Indicted Editor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTREE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil libertarians are outraged that the
editor of a small newspaper serving the black community was
indicted on a charge of criminal libel for a column criticizing two
politicians.
   ``Free speech means nothing if someone can go to jail for
criticizing the government,'' said Steven Bates, chairman of South
Carolina's chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union.
   The ACLU said it will petition for dismissal of the charges
announced Monday against Jim Fitt, editor of The Voice, a
Williamsburg County weekly with a circulation of 2,300.
   State Rep. B.J. Gordon, who is black, and state Sen. Frank
McGill, who is white, brought the charges in response to a May 17
column in which Fitts urged voters to reject the politicians in the
June primary and accused them of stealing.
   Representatives of reporters' groups called the indictment a
step backwards.
   ``I'm really appalled,'' said Jane Kirtley, executive director
of the Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press in Washington.
``You don't throw people in jail in this country for stating an
opinion.''
   If convicted, Fitts faces up to $5,000 in fines and a year in
prison on each of the two counts.
   Kirtley said she could not recall a case in which a journalist
was sent to prison for libel.
   McGill and Gordon, both Democrats and the county's
representatives in the Legislature, won the election.
   Fitts, 62, wrote in part: ``I will say to you, without fear of
contradiction, if every black in Williamsburg County would start
stealing today and steal every day for the rest of their lives,
they could not steal as much as those two have stolen during their
time in power.''
   The column gave no specifics. When asked later what he thought
they had stolen, Fitts said only that they had taken the pride of
people of Williamsburg County.
   Fitts said Monday he expected the indictment and would ask to
have the trial moved out of the county.
   ``The power structure has long roots in Williamsburg County,''
he said.
   Wallace Connor, the attorney for McGill and Gordon, said Fitts
was only seeking publicity for his newspaper.
   Fitts showed no emotion as the indictment was read. Afterward,
he told reporters: ``I'm not surprised. I'm not disappointed. And I
welcome the opportunity to be heard in court. I got what I wanted.
   ``We need some relief in order that the county can grow
economically,'' he said.
   Williamsburg County, with about 40,000 people, ranks 43rd among
the state's 46 counties in per capita income, with an average of
$7,579 in 1986, the latest available figures. More than 60 percent
of the agricultural county is black and about a quarter of its
residents are on food stamps, according to the state's Division of
Research and Statistics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
