<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Amnesty-Irish     06-28 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty-Irish,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judicial Probe Demanded into Disputed Killings by Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international human rights group today demanded
the British government set up a judicial inquiry on Northern
Ireland, claiming existing rules are inadequate to prevent killings
by security forces.
   Citing 25 deaths of unarmed people at the hands of security
forces in disputed circumstances since 1982, Amnesty International
said an inquiry was ``vital to ensure that effective procedures and
safeguards are instituted'' to prevent ``unlawful killings.''
   The group released a report focusing on six deaths in late 1982
that prompted accusations that police were then operating a
``shoot-to-kill policy'' against suspected guerrillas in the
British-ruled province and that they subsequently covered it up and
obstructed an independent official investigation.
   Spokeswoman Fae Junaid said Amnesty believed the need for an
inquiry had become more urgent because it said the government
failed to deliver on promises made this year to hold inquests and
disciplinary proceedings against officers allegedly involved in the
1982 incidents.
   The 94-page report said existing rules were ``inadequate in
enforcing exacting standards for the behavior of security forces to
prevent the excessive use of lethal force.''
   It said few such cases have been prosecuted, and ``in these
cases, most defendants have been acquitted.''
   A judicial inquiry was needed because government investigations
were ``an inadequate means for bringing out the full facts,'' it
said.
   Amnesty pointed to an account by John Stalker, a detective sent
from Britain to investigate the 1982 killings. Stalker claims he
was blocked when he got close to proving the existence of a
``shoot-to-kill'' conspiracy.
   The London-based organization noted that the government admitted
in January that Northern Ireland police officers tried to pervert
the course of justice, but that for ``national security'' reasons
no one would be prosecuted.
   The report said most unarmed victims of police and army
shootings since 1982 were Roman Catholics, and some belonged to the
mainly Catholic Irish Republican Army and Irish National Liberation
Army fighting to rid Northern Ireland of British rule.
   It recognized that the police and army were prime targets of IRA
and INLA attack, but insisted that ``the rule of law does not
permit the exclusion of any citizen from the criminal justice
system.''
   The government has refused to set up a judicial inquiry, saying
the police and army are best equipped to investigate disputed
incidents.
   The report also complained that ``the main procedure used in
Northern Ireland for making facts public, the coroner's inquest, is
so severely restricted that it cannot serve as a mechanism for
investigating the full circumstances surrounding any incident of
killing.''
   Amnesty said that since prosecutions were so rare in shootings
by security forces, inquests were bereaved families' only means of
discovering the truth.
   But it said inquests were sometimes delayed for years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
