<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HealthInsurance     06-28 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Health Insurance,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coalition Unveils Blueprint For Health Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``basic benefits package'' _ a blueprint for
health insurance _ has been unveiled by a coalition of businesses,
labor unions, medical organizations and insurance companies.
   It was devised by the Health Policy Agenda for the American
People and is designed to become the standard by which private and
public health insurance plans are measured, officials said.
   Consumers can use it as a checklist to use when comparison
shopping for a comphrehensive health insurance policy, they said.
   The group unveiled its plan at the American Medical
Association's annual policymaking convention. The coalition was
launched at the AMA's initiative and began work last year.
   ``What it says is there are certain health insurance benefits
that should be included in a basic package. It is a blueprint for
health benefit plans,'' said Diane McCarthy, a member of the
committee that developed the package.
   ``It defines the specific types of coverage and services that
should be in a basic benefits plan, but it is not a mandatory
formula. Americans should consider this a core set of benefits to
use as a guide to tailor specific benefits plans and to help them
comparison-shop for insurance,'' Ms. McCarthy said.
   According to the coalition of 172 public and private
organizations, a basic health insurance package should cover such
items as:
   _ Maternity and child care, including pre- and post-birth
examinations, along with some benefits for well-child care.
   _ Immunizations and periodic medical examinations for early
detection of illness.
   _ Semi-private room and board in a hospital.
   _ Treatment by doctors and surgeons inside and outside the
hospital.
   _ Mental health treatment, including for drug and alcohol abuse.
   _ Home health-care, nursing home care and hospice care at home
for people with a terminal illness.
   ``Prior to this time, no one has been able to define the level
of health care to which every American ought to be entitled,'' said
Dr. James Todd, speaking for the AMA, which helped develop the plan.
   Gene Kimmelman, legislative director for the Consumer Federation
of America, another coalition member, said 37 million U.S.
residents now have no health insurance and an additional 30 million
to 40 million have inadequate insurance
   The health coalition estimated that such a health insurance
package would cost $270 a month for a family or $110 for an
individual.
   Such a plan would have a $200 deductible for the first hospital
admission in any calendar year, a $100 individual deductible for
all other covered services or a maximum $250 family deductible.
   It also would require consumers to pay 20 percent of the costs
for covered services up to a maximum of $1,500 for an individual or
$2,500 for a family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
