<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PanasonicReturn     06-28 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panasonic Return,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Built TVs Shipped to Japan Amid Predictions More Will Follow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKLIN PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weak dollar, a productive workforce
and American hardwood combined to convince Japanese electronics
giant Matsushita to make Panasonic TVs here and start shipping them
back home for sale.
   ``Japan is a different market, and these sets today represent an
honest attempt to market and sell a product based on conditions
there ... not just send over whatever we build,'' Richard Kraft,
president of Matsushita Industrial Co., said Monday as the first of
5,000 sets were loaded for shipment.
   Kraft said the two most important factors in the decision to
build the sets in this Chicago suburb were savings of about 10
percent and the design of the cabinet, which makes extensive use of
U.S. hardwoods and craftsmen.
   He said he could not estimate what the 27-inch sets would cost
in Japan, but a comparable product for the U.S. market would range
between $1,500 and $2,000.
   While U.S.-made materials account for about 70 percent of each
set, Kraft noted the televisions are unusuable in this country
because the settings, power supply and frequencies are adapted for
foreign use.
   The plant manufactures more than one million sets annually for
the North American market. By designing the product specifically
for sale in Japan, Kraft predicted Americans can make genuine
inroads into the Japanese market.
   ``Hopefully, this is just a small beginning to what ultimately
will lead to a more balanced trading situation between all
countries of the world _ but especially the United States and
Japan,'' he added.
   Gov. James R. Thompson joined the plant's executives and 800
workers for a brief ceremony, then lauded the company for paying
attention to the new realities of global business.
   ``Americans are always being eternal optimists, believing what's
good enough for us is good enough for the rest of the world,'' said
Thompson.
   ``But there are cultural differences, consumer differences and
technology ... and all play a role in the success of marketing a
product. This is what the smartest business have always done,'' the
governor said.
</TEXT>
