<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArmenianWitness     06-28 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Armenian Witness,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian-American Videotapes Protests In Soviet Armenia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A television producer who traveled to
strife-torn Soviet Armenia showed videoptape of about 50,000
protesters thrusting their fists into the air and chanting ``We
want freedom.''
   The rare sight, a revealing look at civil unrest behind the Iron
Curtain, was shot by Ashot Dorian, an Armenian-American freelance
cable television producer.
   Dorian was recently in the area, which has been closed to
Western reporters and camera crews, for two weeks to attend a
festival honoring an Armenian classical music composer.
   He said some of his footage will be shown on a public access
cable television show he produces.
   ``My videotape footage shows both the desperation and the
determination of the people there to have justice and human rights
for the Armenian people,'' Dorian said Monday. ``I saw things that
people from the West don't have an opportunity to see.''
   Footage of one rally he screened for The Associated Press
revealed a crowd of about 50,000 who raised their arms with
clenched fists in a defiant pose as they shouted ``We want
freedom'' and ``We will fight to the end.''
   Soviet Armenians want to annex a disputed region called
Nagorno-Karabakh from neighboring Azerbaijan. Nagorno-Karabakh is a
community of mostly Christian Armenians surrounded by the
predominantly Moslem republic of Azerbaijan.
   In recent months, thousands of Armenian demonstrators have
marched in the streets. At least 35 have been killed in
confrontations with police, and hundreds have been injured.
   Labor strikes, hunger strikes and rallies have erupted in
several cities in Soviet Armenia, but Communist Party officials
said Sunday that Armenian residents in Nagorno-Karabakh have called
off their general strike.
</TEXT>
