<2ND_LINE>PM-Industrial Accident, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0549,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Dead, 20 Injured In Cyanide Accident At Plating Company</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with 20 injured, correcting location</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An industrial accident involving cyanide
poisoning today left four people dead and 20 injured at a northeast
Indiana plating company, officials said.
   A spokesman at Bastian Plating Co. said the accident occurred at
about 5 a.m. Bastian Vice President Dennis Fry said four workers
died and several more were taken to DeKalb County Memorial Hospital.
   Fry said he did not know what chemical was involved or how many
workers were in the plant at the time of the accident.
   ``There was no explosion. It was an industrial accident,'' Fry
said.
   Hospital spokeswoman Maryellen Schimmoller said 20 people were
being treated for what she believed was cyanide poisoning.
   ``At this point everything's hectic,'' Ms. Schimmoller said.
``We're putting people in quarantine. They're having to be very
careful with what they're handling.''
   Lt. Ken Hollingsworth of the Indiana State Police said the
accident involved cyanide poisoning. Hollingsworth said one Auburn
police officer also was hospitalized for observation.
   No additional details were immediately available. Auburn is
about 135 miles east of Chicago.
