<DOCNO> AP880628-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0928EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-HumanRights     06-28 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Human Rights,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Calls for Greater, But Still Limited, Rights</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviets should be free of interference in their
private lives and able to speak their minds provided they do not
oppose the political structure or the Communist Party's monopoly on
power, Mikhail S. Gorbachev said today.
   In his speech opening the 19th Communist Party conference at the
Kremlin, the Soviet leader touched on political and judicial
reforms, the rights of religious believers and the demands of
political and ethnic dissidents.
   ``The entire law-and-order structure of ours is called upon to
guarantee strict observance of the citizens' rights to the
inviolability of private life and the home, privacy of
correspondence, postal and telegraph messages,'' he said.
   The Soviet legal system must ensure that a person is innocent
until proven guilty and that all people get equal treatment before
the law, the Soviet leader said.
   Those rights and the right to speak out on the issues before
Soviet society have been violated since the time of dictator Josef
Stalin and must be restored, he said.
   But the reform-minded Soviet leader drew a line at challenges by
ethnic minorities to the existing boundaries of the Soviet Union
and by political dissidents to the Communist Party's monopoly on
power, which is proclaimed in the Soviet Constitution.
   ``Some think that any questions _ from the redrawing of borders
to the establishment of opposition parties _ can be resolved''
through glasnost, his policy of greater openness, Gorbachev said.
``The Central Committee believes such abuses of democratization run
counter to the tasks of perestroika, contradict the peoples'
interests,'' he said.
   He expressed confidence that Soviet people could tell the
difference between ``genuine champions of perestroika and glasnost
from those who are guided by goals alien to the goals of socialism
and the one-party sytem.''
   Even though they have a different world view than Communists,
``all believers, irrespective of their faith, are equal citizens of
the Soviet Union,'' Gorbachev said.
   A new law on freedom of conscience now being written will ensure
equal treatment for believers, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
