<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Palestinians     06-28 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Palestinians,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defeated Arafat Loyalists Evacuate Beirut Camp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 150 guerrillas loyal to PLO chief
Yasser Arafat today pulled out of a refugee camp devastated by the
artillery of Palestinian dissidents who dealt their mainstream PLO
faction a major setback.
   Syrian soldiers at the entrance to the Chatilla camp in Beirut
searched the defeated fighters and confiscated their arms. Two
bodies, a man and his fiance, were carried on stretchers to two
waiting ambulances.
   The loyalists had fought the dissidents for two months for
control of of Chatilla and an adjacent shantytown, Bourj
el-Barajneh.
   Today, they were put in three trucks bound for the southern port
of Sidon, about 25 miles to the south, but were stopped on the way
by a leftist Lebanese militia that controls the city.
   Libyan escorts tried to persuade the militiamen to let the
Palestinian evacuees enter and the Syrian officers who accompanied
the convoy from Beirut turned back after giving the guerrillas back
their weapons.
   In all, 127 people have been killed and 527 wounded since May 1,
when fighting broke out between loyalists and opponents of Arafat
in Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh.
   The Syrian-backed dissident Fatah-Uprising faction, led Col.
Saeed Mousa, overran Chatilla in a 13-hour battle Monday. Most of
Arafat's 200 fighters then surrendered to Syrian and Libyan
officers.
   Another 60 loyalists held out until early today, when they
emerged from Chatilla's ruins escorted by 30 Libyan officers and
soldiers.
   Fatah-Uprising then seized a large ammunition dump in Chatilla
that belonged to the mainstream faction, a Palestinian official
said.
   Syria has thousands of troops enforcing security in west and
south Beirut, but none made any attempt to stop the fighting for
Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh, which flared despite reconciliation
between Arafat and Syrian President Hafez Assad in April to end a
5-year-old feud.
</TEXT>
