<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0957EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-JVCJazz-Mingus     06-28 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-JVC Jazz-Mingus,0435</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Band Celebrates Lush Mingus Arrangements in JVC Concert</HEAD>
<NOTE>With Laserphoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY HANSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than nine years have passed since Charles
Mingus, the seminal jazz bassist and composer, died at age 56 in
Mexico, where he was being treated for Lou Gehrig's disease.
   During that time, Mingus' innovative compositions and
arrangements have been perpetuated in performances by the Mingus
Dynasty Band, an ensemble of varying personnel led by trombonist
Jimmy Knepper, who played with Mingus in the late '50s and '60s.
   An expanded version of the Mingus Dynasty Band celebrated the
late jazz bassist with a joyous JVC Jazz Festival concert Monday
night at the Kaufmann Concert Hall at the 92nd Street Y.
   Although fewer than half the seats in the 926-seat hall were
filled, those in attendance got a pleasurable lesson in what made
Mingus such an influential force as jazz moved from bebop into the
more eclectic styles of the 1960s.
   Monday night's band combined elements of the old _ former Mingus
bandsmen Jaki Byard on piano, Jack Walrath on trumpet, John Handy
on alto saxophone and Knepper _ with the young _ Jon Faddis on
trumpet and Craig Handy (no relation to John) on tenor saxophone.
   Mingus' lush arrangements, in which the horns and saxophones
weave dense patterns of sound as a backdrop for the soloists, were
as fresh as when he did them more than two decades ago.
   The set opened with ``Jump Monk,'' Mingus' up-tempo appreciation
of the late pianist Theolonius Monk.
   Another object of Mingus' affection, Duke Ellington, provided
the inspiration for ``Duke Ellington's Sound of Love,'' a lovely
ballad launched with a moving solo by Byard.
   Mingus' genius as a composer and arranger came through most
strongly in ``Stop, Look and Listen,'' an ambitious collection of
rhythms, moods and styles from his acclaimed album on the Impulse
label, ``The Black Saint and the Sinner Lady.''
   Rounding out the band was Sam Burtis on trombone and tuba, David
Murray on tenor saxophone, Nick Brignola on baritone sax, George
Mraz on bass and Billy Hart on drums.
   Monday's concert opened with a courageous set by pianist Geri
Allen and her trio. The program of original compositions started
slowly, but gradually picked up excitement as the trio warmed to
the occasion.
   Although largely in the avant-garde style of polytones and
polyrhythms, Ms. Allen's music retained sufficient melodic content
to hold the audience's interest, and she received a warm ovation.
   The JVC Jazz Festival continues in New York through Saturday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Paris-Train 3rdLd-Writethru a0536 06-28 0802</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Paris-Train, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0536,0826</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more deaths, official saying
it is probable final count from scene, additional comments from
train company official, edits throughout. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescue teams today pulled more bodies from the
crumpled steel of a runaway commuter train that slammed into a
crowded train about to leave a Paris station. At least 55 people
were killed.
   A fire department spokesman said the death toll was probably
final from the scene of the Monday evening crash, the worst rail
accident in Paris history. But the spokesman, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said some of those hospitalized were in grave
condition.
   Officials said 15 passengers were seriously hurt, another 17
were injured less severely and 14 more were treated at the scene.
   Philippe Rouvillois, director general of the state-owned train
company known as SNCF, said the company, the Transport Ministry and
judicial officials had begun into the cause of the crash at the
Gare Lyon, the city's largest train station.
   Another company official, Roger Gerin, said the ``origin of the
accident was in difficulties with the braking system but we do not
know the exact cause.''
   Authorities said the eight-car commuter train, coming into an
underground track at the busy station in eastern Paris, split open
the first of the stationary train's four cars.
   The moving train was sliced open lengthwise and the stationary
train buckled upward.
   Two young riders, a man and a woman, were discovered early today
trapped under a mound of steel. The woman, kept on an emergency
life support system while rescue workers tried to saw her out,
could not be saved.
   The man's legs had to be amputated to remove him.
   Gerin said the engineers of both trains were well qualified. He
said both engineers jumped from the trains before the collision.
   He said the engineer of the moving train, Daniel Saulin,
realized the brakes were not working and warned passengers to move
to the back of the train.
   The engineer of the train in the station, Andry Tanguy, also had
time to warn passengers. Announcements over loudspeakers told them
to leave the train.
   Gerin said trains undergo maintenance four times a year, in
addition to routine checks. He said the commuter train had been
checked three days earlier.
   Gerin confirmed that the train entered the station traveling at
40 to 50 miles per hour.
   Before the accident, Gerin said, the train had made 15 stops and
the brakes worked normally at each of the stops.
   He said a passenger pulled an alarm signal, causing the train to
stop at a station five miles from Paris that is not normally a stop.
   ``During this 26-minute stop, the engineer experienced
difficulty in trying to re-arm the brake system, but he resumed his
trip,'' Gerin said.
   As he approached the station, the engineer experienced more
braking difficulties and alerted the stationmaster, Gerin said.
   At midmorning, two diesel trains attached to an enormous steel
cable were used to pull apart the trains. Rescue workers carried
the dead away from the wreck on stretchers or in plastic bags.
   Rouvillois said the moving train _ coming from the southeastern
suburb of Melun _ went through a red signal light about 500-600
yards from the station.
   ``When the driver noticed a problem with the brakes, he asked
travelers in the train to move toward the back,'' Rouvillois said.
   ``All at once I saw the train coming toward me at high speed and
I had just enough time to jump onto the platform,'' said the driver
of the standing train, who was not injured.
   About 250 firefighters were helping with the rescue and
recovery, aided by medical teams and dozens of police.
   Officials said the train that was hit was full and behind
schedule by several minutes.
   The Gare de Lyon, on the right bank of the Seine River, is the
largest of six major train stations in Paris, covering nearly 15
acres. It is a stop for the city's subways and handles commuter
traffic as well as intercity trains.
   The last major train accident in Paris was in January 1981 at
the Auber station, when two suburban trains collided, killing one
person and injuring 71.
   Two major train accidents occurred in France in August 1985. Two
trains collided Aug. 3, 1985 on a one-way track at Flaujac-Gare in
the southwest, killing 32 people and injuring 160. On Aug. 31, a
derailed train was hit by another at Argenton-Sur-Creuse in central
France, killing 43 people and injuring 37.
   The train crash was the second major transportation accident in
two days in France. On Sunday, a new Air France Airbus 320 crashed
at an air show near Mulhouse in eastern France, killing three
people and injuring 50 others.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
