<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MysteriousBoy     06-28 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mysterious Boy,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Identified as Runaway from Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mexican woman has identified as her son
a partly deaf young boy who was found last fall wandering near
downtown Juarez, Mexico, a newpaper reported today.
   Micaela Aguilera de Garcia, 32, of Tampico, Mexico, said Monday
she is making plans for a reunion with the boy she believes is her
9-year-old son, nicknamed Chuy. Tampico is on the Gulf of Mexico
1,120 miles southeast of Juarez.
   ``I'm at peace now _ now that I know he's all right,'' the woman
told the El Paso Times.
   Because the boy does not speak, write or use sign language, U.S.
and Mexican officials have been unable to determine where he is
from. He was nicknamed Sabath because he was found on a Saturday.
   The FBI was called into the case when Mexican officials noticed
Sabath prefers American food and cartoon characters to their
Mexican counterparts, leading them to believe Sabath could be
American.
   FBI agent Terry Kincaid said he had heard reports about the
Tampico woman.
   ``We have reports from Tampico, Mexico, from both a lady who
thinks it's her son and from ... authorities who think the picture
of Sabath they were shown is the same boy who they picked up about
a year ago,'' Kincaid said.
   He said photographs were being sent from Tampico, and they will
be shown to the boy.
   Aguilera's search for her missing son had taken her to crowded
cities and remote villages along Mexico's Gulf Coast during the
past nine months.
   She was arranging transportation to Juarez, across the border
from El Paso. Sabath has been living in a shelter for neglected and
abandoned children in Juarez.
   The woman, a housekeeper who lives with her mother and four of
her five children, said she would consider giving up the child if
that would get him into a specialized school for the deaf. She said
her son had run away from home in the past.
   Mariana Paredes de Aguilera, the boy's grandmother, grasped
Sabath's picture and with tears welling in her eyes said, ``Oh,
that's him. My God, it's him.''
</TEXT>
