<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis-Veep 1stLd-Writethru a0453 06-28 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Veep, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Camp Says No Rush to Pick Running Mate; Nunn Says Not
Interested</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT new 7th graf with Foley report bgng ``House
Majority...; SUB 7th graf pvs bgng ``Requests for'' to delete
outdated reference to Foley</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee-to-be Michael
Dukakis will step up his search for a running mate this week by
meeting about 30 senators, among them prospective candidates for
the No. 2 spot on the ticket.
   Dukakis, back from a four-day vacation, planned to tout his
record on housing issues today before heading to Washington on
Wednesday to meet with the senators.
   On the Capitol Hill itinerary is a meeting with Georgia Sen. Sam
Nunn, who said Monday he was not providing the Dukakis campaign
with background and financial information it has requested of
prospective running mates.
   ``He knows my position on the vice presidency,'' Nunn said in a
telephone interview.
   Nunn said he had told the Massachusetts governor and Dukakis
campaign chairman Paul Brountas that a spot on the Democratic
ticket is ``not on my agenda.'' Brountas is heading the search for
a running mate.
   Another prominent senator, New Jersey's Bill Bradley, last week
said he had informed Dukakis that he did not want to be considered.
   House Majority Leader Tom Foley of Washington also declined to
provide personal background and finances to the Dukakis campaign,
the Seattle Post-Intelligencer reported today.
   Requests for background and financial information from
prospective running mates have gone out in the past two weeks.
Those under consideration, according to sources, included Jesse
Jackson, Sens. Bob Graham of Florida, Nunn, John Glenn of Ohio, and
Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, and Rep. Lee Hamilton of Indiana.
   Sen. Dale Bumpers of Arkansas as well as Missouri Rep. Richard
Gephardt, also reportedly have been asked to provide information to
Brountas.
   Dukakis' decision to schedule the meetings with senators on
Wednesday pushed back by a day a campaign swing through the
Midwest. Dukakis will return to Washington before next month's
Democratic National Convention to hold similar sessions with House
members, his campaign said.
   Aides, meanwhile, said there was no timetable for making or
announcing the choice for the second spot on the ticket.
   The Massachusetts governor has said he hoped to select a running
mate prior to the Atlanta convention, scheduled for July 18-21, but
aides were quick to deny a report in the Boston Herald that the
decision might be made as early as Monday.
   ``That's wrong,'' Brountas said in a telephone interview. ``It's
going to take more time than that to get the work all done.'' He
did say, however, that it would ``make a lot of sense'' to complete
the search in advance of the convention.
   Private campaign polling on the strengths and weaknesses of
potential running mates has not been completed. While early
campaign polls had general questions about the No. 2 spot on the
ticket, current polling is more detailed.
   The polling won't be finished this week, said one campaign
source.
   Although Dukakis himself says he dislikes polling and contends
it will have little impact on his decision _ a position shared by
Brountas _ other ranking campaign officials are awaiting the poll
results.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
