<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-AMA-AIDS     06-28 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AMA-AIDS,0675</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMA Trustees: Prisoners Should Be Tested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Medical Association committee
recommended today that the AMA adopt new proposals for battling
AIDS, including a call for AIDS testing of all prison inmates and
for tracing the sexual partners of AIDS victims.
   Many doctors had opposed the proposal for mandatory testing of
prison inmates during a hearing Monday before the committee.
   The House of Delegates is scheduled to vote Thursday on the AIDS
proposals, which were drafted by the AMA's Board of Trustees.
   The trustees' report, debated Monday, recommended that states
``give serious consideration'' to contact tracing of all AIDS
victims. And it called on federal and state governments to expand
treatment programs for intravenous drug abusers.
   The report also recommended that U.S. women infected with the
AIDS virus avoid breast feeding to reduce the chance of giving the
disease to their children and called for ``vigorous enforcement''
of existing anti-discrimination laws to protect AIDS victims.
   In addition, the board called on President Reagan to create a
new national AIDS commission, identical to the one that just
finished its work, ``to provide the essential coordination between
public and private institutions that are addressing AIDS.''
   The AMA's board also issued four background reports on related
AIDS issues, and individual state delegations have proposed five
additional AIDS policies.
   ``This is a disease we can't become casual about,'' said Dr.
John Dawson, an AMA trustee and surgeon from Seattle. ``We're still
waiting for the explosion of cases that will arouse the country.''
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome destroys the body's ability
to fight disease and is spread primarily through sexual
intercourse, shared hypodermic needles and from mothers to their
infants. It is fatal and incurable.
   By 1991, the nation likely will have 270,000 cases of AIDS, the
report said.
   Dr. Robert Bernstein, the Texas health commissioner, opposed
testing prisoners for AIDS because most state correctional systems
can't segregate AIDS victims from other inmates.
   ``Why test if you're not going to do anything about it?'' he
said. He also estimated that it would cost at least $120,000 to
conduct just one round of testing on Texas' 40,000 prison inmates.
   But Dr. John Watson of Columbus, Ga., said he favored testing
prisoners as a way of protecting inmates who don't have AIDS
because of the prevalence of homosexual rape in prisons.
   The AMA trustees also recommended that states seriously consider
launching a program of contacting the sexual partners of AIDS
victims in an effort to slow the disease's spread among
heterosexuals.
   ``You have the potential for a frightening expansion of AIDS
into the heterosexual community,'' Dawson said. ``That's where
contact tracing would be important.''
   A separate AMA trustees' report focusing on intravenous drug
users recommends that federal and state governments increase
spending for free drug treatment programs.
   ``Experts in the field agree that this is the most important
step that can be taken to reduce the spread of (AIDS) infection
among intravenous drug abusers,'' the report says.
   It also calls on authorities to clean up ``shooting galleries''
where addicts gather to inject drugs because they pose a potential
for spreading the disease.
   The hearing committee also recommended that the AMA delegates
adopt the following AIDS proposals calling for:
   _ The federal government ``to continue to'' quickly investigate
new, experimental AIDS treatments so that they can be made
available as soon as possible to victims of the disease.
   _ The AMA to study the issues surrounding whether doctors
infected by the AIDS virus should be allowed to continue to
practice medicine.
   _ The government to begin a second nationwide study to determine
the rate of the disease's spread.
   _ The government to prevent discrimination against AIDS victims
in employment, housing and other areas.
   ``The more discrimination that goes on with AIDS,'' Dawson said,
``the more you're going to drive it underground and have difficulty
dealing with it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
