<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PrisonEscapees     06-28 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prison Escapees,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>15 Prisoners Wound Selves to Protest Contraband Searches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDDYVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 15 prison inmates slashed themselves
with razors and broken light bulbs to protest surprise searches
after eight other inmates escaped from the facility earlier this
month, a prison spokesman said.
   Meanwhile, two of the Kentucky State Penitentiary escapees who
spent a week on the run before being recaptured in a shootout were
charged Monday with attempted murder and being persistent felony
offenders.
   Three prisoners are still at large from the June 16 jailbreak.
   The approximately 15 prisoners who wounded themselves in
protests Saturday and Sunday were housed in the penitentiary's
segregation unti, Cellhouse 3, where problem inmates are kept, said
prison spokesman Barry Banister.
   He said none of the injuries was serious.
   Banister said a few inmates were treated at Caldwell County
Hospital in Princeton, while others were admitted to the prison
medical unit.
   ``They feel like we've mistreated them,'' Banister said. ``It's
not really unusual after something like this is instituted.''
   The searches were an attempt to regain control over the
cellhouse, from which the eight inmates had escaped. Banister said
the five recaptured inmates were not involved in the protests.
   Inmates, however, are still managing to get razor blades, he
said. ``It's amazing how they can hide them.''
   In Taylor County, convicted murderers Ronnie Hudson, 29, and
Joseph Montgomery, 27, both of Louisville, were also charged with
being felons in possession of weapons. They were recaptured
Wednesday after police spotted them running through a field.
   Of the three remaining escapees, Banister said prison officials
had heard little since they were spotted June 21 in Memphis, Tenn.
</TEXT>
