<HEAD>Sikh Extremists Kill Six People In Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists killed six people in
several attacks in the northern state of Punjab, the United News of
India reported today.
   The agency said a group of militants fatally shot a woman and
injured her daughter in Lahora village in the Jalandhar district
Monday night. The assailants also shot and injured an accountant in
the same village.
   The militants also opened fire in the neighboring village of
Bhantura, killing one man, the report said.
   A milkman was shot dead in another attack in Jalandhar district,
the agency reported.
   Three other people were gunned down in the the past 24 hours in
attacks by Sikh extremists in the Punjab districts of Amritsar,
Hoshiarpur and Gurdaspur, the report said.
   The latest killings raised to at least 1,417 the number of
people killed this year in attacks blamed on Sikh militants.
   Sikhs make up 2 percent of India's 800 million people but they
are a majority in Punjab state. Sikh radicals, who claim they are
discriminated against by the majority Hindus, are fighting for a
separate homeland in Punjab.
</TEXT>
