<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WheelSentencing     06-28 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wheel Sentencing,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Assistant Judge Sentenced In Perjury Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RUTLAND, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge rejected pleas for a no-prison
sentence and ordered a former assistant judge to serve 45 days in
jail for lying at an inquest into whether she had falsified court
files to claim pay when she hadn't worked.
   District Court Judge Francis McCaffrey on Monday sentenced Jane
Wheel to between one year and three years on each of three counts,
then suspended all but 45 days. Wheel must also perform 1,500 hours
of community service over three years.
   ``It is my belief, after searching my soul, that not to impose
some time would diminish the seriousness of this offense,'' said
McCaffrey.
   Wheel's case attracted wide attention because of her ties to
three state Supreme Court justices, who along with Wheel were
charged with judicial misconduct in 1987 in separate, non-criminal
proceedings. The justices were accused of misusing their power in
order to protect Wheel.
   Wheel was found guilty Feb. 22 of lying during a 1986 inquest
into whether she falsified court files to show she heard cases on
days for which she had claimed pay.
   Attorneys for Wheel say the conviction will be appealed.
   Wheel, 55, faced up to 45 years for her conviction on three
charges of false swearing.
   Defense lawyer Richard Davis urged leniency before the
sentencing.
   ``I hope, your honor, in the long run Jane Wheel will be
vindicated,'' Davis said. ``She doesn't deserve what she has been
put through. She doesn't deserve one more minute of pain and
suffering.''
   But David Suntag, the assistant attorney general who prosecuted
the case, urged a jail sentence because he said Wheel abused her
public trust.
   ``There is no one better to know how important affirming,
maintaining and promoting the judicial system is than Jane Wheel,''
said Suntag.
   Wheel held the elected post of assistant judge in Chittenden
County, the state's most populous county. The assistant judges, who
need not be lawyers, sit on Superior Courts with the presiding
judge, who is a lawyer. She lost a re-election bid two years ago
after the allegations surfaced.
   During the nearly month-long jury trial, Wheel's lawyers
portrayed her as the victim of a court employee's vendetta and a
drive by members of the legal community to weaken the office of
assistant judge.
   Charges against two of the state Supreme Court justices were not
pursued. The third justice, retired Justice William Hill, was found
guilty on several counts by the Judicial Conduct Board. The state
Supreme Court will ultimately decide whether Hill was guilty of
misconduct.
</TEXT>
