<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EPADepartment     06-28 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EPA Department,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Want to Make EPA Part of Cabinet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Republican senators running for
re-election today introduced a bill to elevate the Environmental
Protection Agency to Cabinet-level status.
   Conceding that the bill has little chance of passage this year,
one of the five, Sen. David Durenberger of Minnesota, said the
measure was meant as ``a signal. We want environmental protection
to receive a higher priority than it has in the past.''
   Cabinet status would give EPA more clout in dealing with other
government agencies, including Cabinet-level departments; enhance
its status in international negotiations and put environmental
issues closer to the Oval Office, the senators said.
   ``We want the next president of the United States directly
involved in making environmental policy,'' said Durenberger.
   Another sponsor, Sen. John Heinz of Pennsylvania refused to take
the opportunity to criticize President Reagan's environmental
record.
   ``Given where the United States was in 1980 and 1981 and his
experience, I think the president would agree concern over the
environment has sharply increased in the past six or eight years.
That's true for him and it's true for us,'' Heinz said.
   In addition to Durenberger and Heinz, the initial sponsors were
Sens. John Chafee of Rhode Island, Robert Stafford of Vermont and
Lowell Weicker of Connecticut.
   Durenberger said he believed Vice President George Bush, certain
to be the Republican nominee for president, had an open mind on the
issue and he did not know how environmentalists or industry would
react.
   Some Democrats might join his group as co-sponsors, he said.
   The National Wildlife Federation, the nation's largest
environmental group with close to 5 million members in affiliated
organizations, endorsed the bill as ``long overdue.''
   EPA Administrator Lee M. Thomas told reporters in a recent
conversation he believed that as a general proposition EPA should
be a Cabinet department, but saw no need to act in the current
administration because the agency in fact had equal status with
others participating in the sub-Cabinet Domestic Policy Council.
   EPA was formed out of pieces of the Interior, Agriculture and
Health, Education and Welfare departments under an executive order
of President Nixon in 1970.
</TEXT>
