<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthernIreland     06-28 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northern Ireland,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Damages School Bus and Injures One Child</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today on a
school bus carrying at least a dozen children, injuring a
15-year-old girl and the driver, police said. The outlawed Irish
Republican Army claimed responsibility.
   Several other children sustained minor cuts and bruises and were
treated for shock at a hospital and later released, police said.
   The IRA said in a statement that one of its units was
responsible for the explosion in which a civilian was ``regrettably
injured,'' a tacit acknowledgment that the attack went awry.
   The IRA, which has targeted Northern Ireland's security forces
in its fight to end British rule in the Protestant-dominated
province, said it would hold an investigation into the bombing,
   Police say the driver, a part-time member of the locally
recruited Ulster Defense Regiment had been targeted by the IRA. He
suffered eye injuries from flying glass in the bombing.
   Gillian Latimer, 15, suffered chest, rib and arm injuries,
police said. She was transferred to the Royal Victoria Hospital in
Belfast where her condition was described as serious.
   At the time of the explosion at 8 a.m., the bus was driving
along Lower Main Street in Lisnaskea in County Fermanagh, 8 miles
from the border of the Irish Republic, said a Belfast police
spokesman, who asked not to be identified.
   The bus was carrying a dozen Protestant and Roman Catholic
children who attend secondary school in Enniskillen, about 10 miles
away, the spokesman said.
   The bomb, made of between 2 and 3 pounds of explosive, was
planted in the engine compartment of the vehicle, the spokesman
said.
   ``We have no idea how it was detonated,'' he added.
   The explosion caused extensive damage to the front of the bus,
the spokesman said.
   Enniskillen, the largest town in Country Fermanagh, was the
scene of an IRA bombing last November that killed 12 Protestants
attending a memorial service for Britain's war dead.
   Ken McFarlane, superintendent of the Royal Ulster Constabulary
in County Fermanagh, denounced ``the crazy recklessness of
terrorists'' who ``have no regard whatsoever for life, even the
lives of children.''
   ``What has happened is terrible in itself, but what might have
happened, for all the terrorists care, is appalling,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
