<1ST_LINE>u a PM-GasExplosion 3rdLd-Writethru a0585 06-28 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gas Explosion, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0585,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gas Blast Kills 2, Injures 8</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with six grafs, body of man who caused blast found,
death toll two, ID of boy, condition; picks up 6th graf pvs, ``A
man xxx. Adds byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers used a crane and dug with their
hands today to save a 3-year-old boy from the rubble of a house
that police said had been deliberately filled with natural gas and
then ignited, killing two people and injuring eight others.
   The boy was found about ``10 feet under the rubble in what was
apparently the first floor,'' said Deputy Fire Commissioner Roger
Ulshafer. He had been there for about nine hours.
   The child ``didn't seem to be burned too badly. He was breathing
on his own after firefighters gave him mouth-to-mouth
resuscitation,'' Ulshafer said. ``It's overwhelming, getting that
little boy out easily.''
   The boy, identified as Harry Mertz, was taken to a nearby
hospital, where he was listed in guarded condition with burns over
11 percent of his body.
   The body of the man who caused the explosion, identified by
police Capt. James Powell as Richard Litostansky, was found in the
basement.
   ``Friends and neighbors have said he threatened suicide. For the
past several weeks whe's been talking it up pretty good. Apparently
he was in the basement, opened the gas line and blew it,'' said
Detective Mike Boyle.
   A man called the 911 emergency telephone number Monday saying he
had turned on the gas to the two-story rowhouse and planned to
ignite it, said Detective Robert McGarry.
   He demanded to speak to a police officer, but no officer was
available, McGarry said.
   Two of the injured were officers who were investigating the
telephone threat when the house exploded. They had called the
Philadelphia Gas Works to turn off the gas, police said.
   The gas company cut off the lines shortly after midnight, said
Avrom Steinbrook, the utility's manager of public relations.
   The gas-filled house and another next door collapsed, McGarry
said.
   An 82-year-old man was pronounced dead at Episcopal Hospital,
where three of the injured were also taken.
   One officer was in stable condition with head trauma and the
second officer was treated and released, said Episcopal nursing
supervisor Linda Keyte. A man who Ms. Keyte said was apparently the
step-father of the 3-year-old boy and two other children who were
injured suffered chest injuries.
   A 4-year-old girl was in stable condition for smoke inhalation
and her 8-year-old half-brother was in serious condition with
second-degree burns over 20 percent of his body at St.
Christopher's Hospital for Children, said nursing supervisor D.
Volker.
   Two elderly women were also treated and released from St. Mary's
Hospital.
</TEXT>
