<1ST_LINE>u a PM-DemonstrationArrests 1stLd-Writethru a0590 06-28 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Demonstration Arrests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0590,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>13 People Jailed After Refusing To Leave Toledo Council Chambers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS four grafs at end with more detail and background</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 13 black ministers and civil
rights leaders today after they refused to leave Toledo City
Council chambers during a protest over the suspension of three city
workers.
   Some of those who were arrested were dragged or carried out of
the chambers while an estimated 300 people in the room prayed and
asked for an explanation of the suspensions.
   Police said 13 of those arrested were charged with disrupting a
lawful meeting and criminal trespassing. They included Lee
Williams, head of the Northwest Ohio chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
   The group had occupied council chambers at about 9 a.m. City
Council members waited to start their meeting, then asked police to
arrest the demonstrators.
   The group was protesting the suspension of three black employees
of the city's Community Development Department three weeks ago
after a U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development
investigation revealed deficiencies in Toledo's housing
rehabilitation program.
   A spokesman for the group, the Rev. Franklin Freeman, said
shortly before his arrest, ``We will not leave. They haven't
listened to us. It isn't a democracy when you don't listen to the
people.''
   Those who were arrested were released on their own recognizance
after being booked.
   The Rev. Floyd Rose, executive director of the Coalition for
Economic Justice, said after his release, ``We will not stop. The
city has to address the issue.''
   The problems in the Toledo program include double-billing for
some improvements and failure of houses to meet city codes after
being rehabilitated. The three workers in the city community
development department were suspended pending an investigation, but
no charges have been filed in the cases.
   Freeman said moments before his arrest that he wants a council
committee to hear what the three suspended workers have to say
about the allegations and that he has requested a federal
investigation into the way City Manager Phillip Hawkey handled the
suspensions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
