<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--911Chitchat     06-28 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--911 Chitchat,0164</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>911 Operators To Be Punished For Chatting On The Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two 911 operators were suspended with pay for
chatting with each other instead of answering emergency telephone
calls, police said.
   ``Throughout the course of these conversations, incoming 911
emergency phones could be heard ringing in the background,'' their
letters of reprimand said.
   Police spokesman Sam Harlan said no emergency calls went
unattended. ``Other people just had to to do the work they weren't
doing,'' he said.
   The women were suspended last weekend pending a decision by
Chief Clarence Dickson on their punishment. The investigation began
after a co-worker saw the women using an interoffice intercom line
for an unusually long time.
   The women said they handled incoming calls while talking to each
other. One blamed a supervisor who she said dislikes her.
   The women, five-year veterans, are seeking help from their
union, saying other emergency operators also chatted on the
intercom system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
