<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseProbe-Principals 1stAdd   06-28 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Principals, 1st Add,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: the investigation.
   </HEAD>
<BYLINE>DEFENSE CONTRACTORS</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _McDonnell Douglas Corp. Investigators searched offices of
company executive Thomas Gunn, seeking confidential or classified
documents on the F-16 jet produced by competitor General Dynamics
and classified information on the $35 billion Advanced Tactical
Aircraft program. A search warrant also said Paisley had given Gunn
and the company secret information on the proposed U.S. sales of
McDonnell Douglas' F-18 fighter airplane in Europe and Korea.
   _United Technologies' jet engine-making subsidiary, Pratt &
Whitney. Its Washington offices were searched after the FBI alleged
that it possessed sensitive documents that rival General Electric
Co. had submitted in competing for contracts to build the F-404
engine and engines for the Navy's V-22 Osprey, a tilt-rotor
aircraft. A search warrant sought information on the relationship
between Pratt & Whitney executive Eugene Tallia, Paisley and Galvin.
   _United Technologies' Norden Systems Inc. unit, which designs
and builds military electronic communication systems. Three offices
were searched in Connecticut.
   _Unisys Corp. Offices in Eagan, Minn., and Great Neck, N.Y.,
were searched. The company makes specialized computers at Eagan and
defensive electronics in Great Neck. The office and home of Great
Neck plant official Dennis Mitchell were searched.
   _Teledyne Electronics, a division of Teledyne Inc. The company
produces aircraft electronics testing equipment contracted through
Berlin's office at the Pentagon.
   _Northrop Corp. The company's contract to build a Navy target
drone appears to be under investigation, the New York Times reports.
   _Loral Corp. Offices in Yonkers, N.Y., and Akron, Ohio, were
searched. The company designs military electronics.
   _Cubic Defense Systems of San Diego, Calif. Company builds an
electronic pilot training system used by the Air Force and Navy.
   _Armtec Inc. of Palatka, Fla. Offices were searched.
Manufactures wiring harnesses and is in the congressional district
of Rep. Bill Chappell, D-Fla., who reportedly has come under
scrutiny in the investigation. The firm's president, William
Roberts, says FBI agents told him he was a target of the
investigation. Roberts worked in government marketing for Sperry
Defense Products. Sperry Corp. later became Unisys.
   _Whittaker Corp. of Farmington, Ark., a defense electronics
company whose command and control systems unit was searched. Parent
company of Lee Telecommunications. Investigators are looking into
ties with Marine Corps contracting supervisor Jack Sherman,
according to the Wall Street Journal. Scott Lamberth of Farmington,
Ark., who works with Whittaker, was served with a search warrant.
   _Hazeltine Corp. of Greenlawn, N.Y., and Arlington, Va.
Hazeltine is a manufacturer of communications equipment and
subsidiary of Emerson Electric Co.
   _Litton Industries Inc.'s Data Systems Division in Van Nuys,
Calif., which produces command control systems for air, ground and
sea combat.
   _Varian Continental Electronics of Dallas, manufacturer of radio
transmitters.
   _Executive Resource Associates Inc. of Arlington, Va., searched
for documents relating to the company's performance evaluation
contract for the cruise missile.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>CONTRACTORS SUBPOENAED</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   _Martin Marietta Corp.
   _Hercules Inc.
   _An El Monte, Calif., division of Gould Inc.; documents
subpoenaed concerning the division's Navy electronics work.
   _Electronic Data Systems Corp.
   _BDM International Inc.
   _LTV Corp.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>CONGRESSMEN</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The following congressmen have been described as under scrutiny
in the probe, although chief prosecutor Henry Hudson has said no
member of Congress is a target of the investigation. No subpoenas
or search warrants have been issued for the congressmen or their
staffs.
   _William Chappell, D-Fla., chairman of the House Appropriations
subcommittee on defense. A company in his congressional district,
Armtec, was served with a search warrant in the probe and the
company's president, William Roberts, is a longtime friend of
Chappell.
   _Roy Dyson, D-Md., met with former Unisys vice president Charles
Gardner in Great Neck, N.Y., to discuss company's defense
contracts. Campaign contributors include several whose offices were
searched as part of the probe, including Kenneth Brooke, who is
Galvin's stepson; Jeffrey Zuba, who operates Zubier Enterprises of
Harrisburg, Pa., a consulting firm and contractor.
   _Thomas Downey, D-N.Y.
   _Andrew Ireland, R-Fla.
   _Samuel Stratton, D-N.Y.
</TEXT>
