<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BrawleyCase 1stLd-Writethru a0528 06-28 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brawley Case, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0528,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freedom for Brawley `Wiretapper' Still Unresolved</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with McClease being held without
bail. Pickup 8th graf, `McClease said during xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The self-proclaimed surveillance expert who
claimed to have recorded conversations between Tawana Brawley's
advisers but turned over blank tapes to federal authorities was
ordered held without bail today.
   Meanwhile, a poll released today shows a majority of New Yorkers
say the teen-agers advisers have acted irresponsibly.
   Samuel McClease, 26, of Jersey City, N.J., said last week he had
taped conversations between the Rev. Al Sharpton and two legal
advisers concerning the Brawley family in which they cast doubt on
the black teen-ager's accusation that she was raped by six whites
last November.
   But McClease was charged Saturday with one count each of
obstruction of justice and perjury after it was revealed the tapes
he submitted were blank.
   U.S. District Judge Shirley Wohl Kram said she had heard nothing
during arguments that ``would assure his reappearance in court.
Therefore I am going to direct that Mr. McClease be detained.''
   McClease's father, Dennis McClease Sr., told reporters he would
retain lawyer Barry Slotnick on his son's behalf and would file an
appeal of the bail ruling.
   At a hearing Monday, Assistant U.S. Attorney Federico E. Virella
claimed that the maximum five-year sentence and $250,000 fine
McClease faces if convicted of perjury and obstructing justice,
coupled with his checkered military and employment records, made
him a poor candidate for release on bail.
   But Magistrate James Francis IV disagreed and ordered McClease
released on $100,000 unsecured bond. Prosecutors appealed the
ruling to Kram.
   McClease said during an interview broadcast June 20 on WCBS-TV
that Sharpton hired him to plant voice-activated listening devices
in the home and office of Brawley attorney C. Vernon Mason and in
Sharpton's own home.
   In the televised interview, McClease said the tapes revealed
that there was no evidence to support the teen-ager's allegations,
and that the advisers knew this.
   ``He continues playing a game with the grand jury,'' Virella
told the magistrate, adding that McClease had evaded appearing
before the grand jury until he was granted immunity concerning the
tapes.
   Virella did not say if the tapes existed, only that the tapes
turned over last week were blank.
   McClease's attorney, Leonard Joy, said the move to detain
McClease was an example of the ``annoyance and vindictiveness of
the government.''
   The poll, meanwhile, shows a majority of New Yorkers say Miss
Brawley's advisers have acted irresponsibly in their handling of
the case.
   In New York City, 55 percent of black respondents and 84 percent
of whites surveyed also said that Sharpton along with attorneys
Mason and Alton Maddox Jr. are using her case for their personal
advantages, according to The New York Times-WCBS-TV News Poll.
   Among city blacks surveyed, 62 percent said Miss Brawley's
advisers had acted irresponsibly, while 17 percent said they had
not. The remainder said they didn't know or declined to answer.
   Among whites surveyed in the city, 83 percent said the advisers
had been irresponsible; 5 percent disagreed.
   The telephone poll of 1,131 adults _ 676 in New York City and
455 in the Wappingers Falls, Poughkeepsie and Newburgh area _ was
conducted between Tuesday and Saturday. The margin of error was
plus or minus 4 percentage points for New York City, plus or minus
5 percentage points in the Wappingers Falls area and plus or minus
6 percentage points for whites or blacks in the city.
</TEXT>
