<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Farming     06-28 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Farming,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Addresses Two Sore Points: Farming & Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet citizens were alerted by their leader
Tuesday that price increases may be in store, along with a change
in the way farmland is managed, as part of his efforts to solve
chronic food shortages.
   In a speech to a national Communist Party conference at the
Kremlin, Mikhail S. Gorbachev said it is necessary to revamp the
state-controlled pricing system to bring about ``the swiftest
possible saturation of the market with food products.''
   ``Without price reform, we will not be able to achieve concrete
results in the economy,'' he said.
   Gorbachev, who said last year that bread was so cheap in the
Soviet Union that children used loaves to play soocer, said it was
``not a normal situation'' to continue paying out the massive
government subsidies that keep down the price of food.
   ``It is absolutely necessary to solve this problem no matter how
difficult this may be,'' Gorbachev said, without suggesting a date
for the implementation of price changes.
   Soviet economists have been talking since at least last year
about possible price reform as part of Gorbachev's program for
``perestroika,'' or economic and social restructuring, and many
Soviets feel price increases on such heavily subsidized staples as
milk, bread and meat are in the offing.
   Gorbachev also said proposals on reform now under ``deep study''
will be put up for nationwide discussion, and that any government
gains as a result of price reform will be handed back in full to
the populace. He did not say how that would be done.
   Gorbachev, the son of a Russian peasant who once was the party's
chief for agriculture, said it was also necessary to change the way
work is conducted on the vast network of state and collective
farms, which are a perennial sore spot in the Soviet economy.
   ``Everything depends on how quickly we will make people
interested and organize the work of collectives on the basis of
lease and contract, on how extensively we will draw the workers in
agriculture into this process and make the farmer a genuine
master,'' he said.
   Gorbachev did not propose an end to state farms, where farmers
have traditionally received a salary similar to those who work in
factories or offices. But he called for a nationwide program to
permit families to lease farmland from their collectives and till
the soil themselves, which he said experiments had shown resulted
in dramatically bigger crops.
</TEXT>
