<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Reaction     06-28 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Reaction,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All Eyes on Gorbachev at Department Store</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A salesman at Moscow's Central Department Store
took the TV set out of its box Tuesday, plugged it in and flicked a
switch. The familiar face of Mikhail S. Gorbachev appeared on the
screen, live and in color.
   The inaugural images were a test not only of the $1,280
Soviet-made set but also, symbolically, of ``perestroika,'' the
restructuring of Soviet society Gorbachev was promoting in the
broadcast from the Kremlin's glass-and-marble Palace of Congresses
a few blocks away.
   The televisions for sale at the downtown store are among the
consumer products Gorbachev complained the Soviet Union doesn't
produce enough of or make good enough.
   When Gorbachev began his address at 10:15 a.m., about 50 Soviets
crowded around a dozen sets on display. Most, however, quickly lost
interest, and their number dwindled to six. One who stayed was
Gennady N. Sasnovsky, a 26-year-old construction engineer who was
passing the time while his wife shopped elsewhere.
   ``We have problems up to here,'' said Sasnovsky, drawing his
hand across his throat.
   The chief concerns, he said, involve economics _ a topic to
which Gorbachev devoted much of the first two hours of his address
to the 5,000 delegates to the nationwide Communist Party conference.
   ``The tragedy is that the working man lives worse than he who
sits behind a desk,'' said Sasnovsky.
   In his speech, Gorbachev attacked the party and government for
what he said was its reluctance to reward good workers with higher
pay and punish bad workers with wage reductions.
   Some changes are already being made. Sasnovsky said the
construction enterprise where he works recently began operating
under the self-financing system Gorbachev has implemented and that
he now is eligible for bonuses of up to 40 percent of his monthly
salary if he does a good job. Sasnovsky said his regular pay is the
equivalent of $305 a month.
   He said Gorbachev's main task is to ``awaken the people. They
aren't used to being active.''
   Asked whether he thought the proposals before this week's party
conference would improve things, he said: ``I think they are not
sufficient. They should be more radical, sharper.''
   As the conference opened, red banners hung from lampposts
throughout downtown, and the stern visage of Vladimir I. Lenin,
founder of the Soviet state, stared down from building-tall
portraits erected for the occasion.
</TEXT>
