<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--WalkerArraignment     06-28 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Walker Arraignment,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Union President Arraigned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of a national postal union will
go to trial in August on charges of embezzlement and filing false
union records, officials said Tuesday.
   Herbert Walker, 45, of Cincinnati, president of the Post Office
Mail Handlers Union, pleaded innocent Tuesday in U.S. District
Court to a 50-count indictment before federal Judge Joseph
Kinneary, said a spokeswoman for Kinneary's office.
   Walker was charged June 16 with embezzling more than $99,000
while head of union Local 304, which represents 3,200 workers in
Ohio, Indiana and Kentucky. He was elected to the national post in
December after eight years as the local's president.
   Three labor organizations represent postal workers.
   The indictment alleges that Walker deposited checks payable to
the local in his own account and wrote checks to himself from union
accounts. He also allegedly altered records to make it appear
checks to himself were for union expenses.
   U.S. Attorney D. Michael Crites said a union audit revealed
funds were missing.
   No specific August date was set for Walker's trial.
</TEXT>
