<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Sandinista-Death 2ndLd-Writethru a0518 06-28 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sandinista-Death, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0518,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Defector's Died From Natural Causes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs, autopsy report concluded death by
natural causes; CORRECTS date of death to June 18 or 19 sted
Sunday, picking up 6th graf pvs, In 1986 xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of a Nicaraguan defector who
publicly accused the Sandinista government of murder and drug
trafficking was the result of natural causes, police said today,
dismissing suggestions the man may have been murdered.
   An autopsy on Jose Alvaro Baldizon, 29, concluded he was killed
by a burst artery in the brain, said Sgt. William Talbott,
detective bureau supervisor in Bell, the suburb where Baldizon
lived.
   A State Department official in Washington had suggested
Baldizon, who told Congress in 1986 that the leftist Sandinistas
trafficked in drugs and murdered 2,000 political opponents, might
have been poisoned while dining at a Nicaraguan restaurant June 18.
   He died in his sleep June 18 or early June 19, Talbott said. The
detective said many hours passed between Baldizon's meal at the
restaurant in Huntington Beach and his death, and that he ate
dinner with his family the evening of June 18.
   State Department officials in Washington, who spoke on condition
they not be named, had said Baldizon became ill after eating at a
Nicaraguan restaurant he frequented, and said his death had the
``appearances of poisoning.'' The death appeared to have occurred
under ``mysterious circumstances,'' the officials said.
   Nicaragua's government press reported Baldizon's death and
blamed the CIA, State Department officials said.
   But the Los Angeles County coroner found the cause of death was
congenital cerebral aneurysm, Talbott said.
   ``With everything that he's been involved in, people were
looking at it kind of funny,'' Talbott said of the death. ``(But)
as far as the criminal end of it's concerned there's nothing going
on.''
   Baldizon's sister, Rosanna, declined Monday to speculate
publicly on the cause.
   ``All we know is that he died during the night. I cannot comment
on the cause of his death,'' Miss Baldizon said. ``We have no proof
of anything.''
   In 1986, Baldizon testified before Congress in an attempt to
convince lawmakers that additional funding was needed for the
Contras fighting the Nicaraguan government.
   He claimed among other things that the Sandinistas murdered
2,000 political opponents through a systematic policy of ``special
measures,'' or assassinations ordered, by Interior Minister Tomas
Borge or his chief deputy.
   Baldizon crossed the border from Nicaragua to Honduras in July
1985 and began making allegations of Sandinista atrocities and drug
trafficking.
   He claimed Sandinista army units dressed like the Contras and
killed Sandinista supporters so that the rebels would be blamed. He
presented no specific evidence as to when or where such actions
occurred.
   Baldizon told Congress that Borge and other Nicaraguan officials
helped to send cocaine to the United States via Miami, and that he
had seen Interior Ministry documents confirming the activity. He
said money from the drug transactions were being used to finance
espionage.
   He testified before the House Foreign Affairs Committee Task
Force in March 1986 that Borge had issued in 1982 ``an order that
all cocaine, dollars and gold had to be turned in to his office.
   ``It was obvious that the confiscated narcotics, gold and
dollars were being sent to places not provided for by law and those
involved were being set free,'' he told the task force.
   Baldizon's allegations were disputed by Americas Watch, a U.S.
human rights group that said he had repeatedly changed his stories.
   Baldizon's survivors include his wife, Maria, and son, who
remain in Nicaragua, Miss Baldizon said.
</TEXT>
