<DOCNO> AP880628-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ChildCare     06-28 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Care,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governors Say Limited Child Care Expansion Would Be Better Than
Nothing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two governors on Tuesday urged Congress to
pass a major child care expansion bill this year, even if a tight
budget means lawmakers cannot fund the entire $2.5 billion plan.
   ``Anything you give, I'll be grateful for,'' Arkanas Gov. Bill
Clinton, a Democrat, said. ``Don't pass nothing just because you
can't get as much money as you want.''
   ``Whatever way you can help us, we need that help,'' added New
Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean, a Republican. ``Whatever money you give us
will be put to extraordinarily good use.''
   Clinton and Kean testified before the Senate Labor and Human
Resources subcommittee on children, family, drugs and alcoholism as
the panel considered the $2.5 billion Act for Better Child Care, or
ABC bill. The measure is sponsored by subcommittee chairman
Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., and supported by women's, labor, medical
and children's groups.
   Three-fourths of the ABC money would help pay day care expenses
for families making less than 115 percent of a state's median
income. The remaining money would be for training and salaries of
child care workers, renovation of facilities and referral programs
for parents.
   Money would only be available to day care homes and centers that
met minimum federal standards developed by an advisory panel.
   Supporters of the bill have been pursuing an all-or-nothing
strategy, saying no child care bill would be better than a weak
one. Dodd has said he would rather hold the bill for the next
administration than pass a plan he considers inadequate.
   However, Dodd on Tuesday referred to ``a national crescendo of
support'' for federal action on child care and indicated
congressional action may be imminent. ``We don't have a lot of time
here,'' Dodd said. ``There's a moment for these kinds of things and
then other things will take over.''
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, a member of the Senate Appropriations
Committee, said lawmakers would not be able to get $2.5 billion for
the child care bill. Clinton said a good framework and a little
money would suffice for this year.
   Clinton and Kean asked Dodd to re-examine a number of
controversial sections of his bill. Echoing criticism by
conservative groups and lawmakers, they said the bill makes
day-care aid available to too many families at the higher end of
the income scale and asked Dodd to reconsider eligibility standards.
   The governors also said the private sector in day care should be
stressed more strongly; that there should be more flexibility in
using the money, possibly through a broad child care block grant;
and asked Dodd to delete the provision imposing national day-care
standards on states.
   ``Congress should resist the temptation to tell the states what
should be done and how they should do it,'' Kean said. ``Uniform
regulations would not account for differing regional needs.''
   But Dodd said the governors would be ``shocked to find the
tremendous disparity in standards'' from state to state and cited a
review by Deborah Phillips, a University of Virginia researcher.
   In her testimony, Phillips said 28 states have no group size
requirements for child care centers, 28 states have no training or
experience requirements for family day care providers, and
staff-to-infant ratios vary from 7-to-1 in Georgia and North
Carolina to 3-to-1 in Kansas, Massachusetts and Maryland.
   ``We would never want you to give us a lot of money to pour it
into dangerous, unhealthy, unsound day care,'' Clinton told Dodd.
He said a compromise might be to require the development of model
child care standards, with state and local officials included in
the process.
   Some 100 child care bills are pending in Congress, ranging from
tax credits to businesses that establish child care centers to tax
credits to all families with preschool children. One bill would
increase the existing social services block grant and another would
limit provider liability through risk pools. Others propose to give
vouchers to poor families and-or money to day care providers for
capital improvements.
</TEXT>
