<HEAD>Oglesby Named Deputy Chief of Staff at White House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan announced today the
appointment of M.B. Oglesby, a Washington lobbyist and former White
House official, to succeed Kenneth M. Duberstein as his deputy
chief of staff.
   Duberstein has been promoted to chief of staff, effective
Friday, succeeding former Sen. Howard H. Baker Jr. Baker says he
plans to return to Tennessee.
   Oglesby's appointment will be effective July 5, the White House
said.
   Oglesby is vice chairman of the board of Hecht, Spencer &
Oglesby Inc., a firm of government relations representatives in
Washington. He joined the firm in March 1986 after resigning his
White House post of assistant to the president for legislative
affairs.
   Oglesby, 47, is a former deputy and acting director of the State
of Illinois office in Washington and a former executive assistant
to Rep. Edward Madigan, R-Ill., Before coming to Washington, he was
an assistant to Gov. Richard Ogilvie of Illinois.
   Reagan said Oglesby ``was a member of our first term team and
brings a wealth of experience which will be valuable to the
vigorous pursuit of our agenda for the next six months.''
   The White House also announced that John C. Tuck, who has been
deputy assistant to the president and executive assistant to the
chief of staff, is being promoted to assistant to the president and
director of the office of the chief of staff.
