<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Defense Probe,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Briefed on Defense Procurement Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan got another in a series of
updates on the defense procurement investigation today, spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater said, and ``wants the matter cleaned up as rapidly
as possible.''
   Fitzwater said he could not go into detail about the discussion,
but that Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci reviewed several matters
that have been discussed publicly, such as the reassignment of
certain Defense Department employees.
   Carlucci told Reagan he has established a ``joint action group''
to ``review the situation on a continuing basis and to make changes
where necessary'' if problems crop up, the spokesman said.
   Fitzwater said Reagan agrees that Carlucci should make any such
corrections ``as soon as possible.''
   The president ``wants the matter cleaned up as rapidly as
possible, both from the standpoint of the investigation of
individuals and the procurement system at the Pentagon,'' Fitzwater
said.
   Under investigation are allegations that defense contractors and
consultants, many of them former military men, bribed Pentagon
officials for contracting details that could be vital in winning
contracts worth billions of dollars.
