<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Angola     06-28 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolans Reject Talks With Savimbi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top official of Angola's Marxist government
on Tuesday ruled out talks with U.S.-backed rebels and said
one-party rule for his homeland is the best assurance for national
development.
   Minister of State Pedro de Castro Van-Dunem told reporters that
multiparty democracy has failed elsewhere in Africa and would not
enable Angola to fulfill the goal of achieving a national identity.
   He said the solution for Angola is for the UNITA rebels, who
have waged war against the country's leftist government for 13
years, to lay down their arms and participate in national
reconstruction.
   Van-Dunem, who was accompanied by two other senior Angolan
officials, met with reporters as UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi was on
the second day of a Washington visit aimed at rallying support for
national reconciliation talks between the warring parties. Savimbi
was to meet late Tuesday with Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   Last week, officials from the United States, Angola, Cuba and
South Africa met for a second time in six weeks to discuss the
possibility of a peaceful settlement in Angola.
   South Africa, along with the United States, supports Savimbi's
movement with military equipment and other items. South Africa sent
several thousand troops to Angola last year. Some have been
withdrawn and an undetermined number remain.
   Van-Dunem said Angolan authorities are willing to talk to South
Africa but not to Savimbi's envoys because ``they are not the
masters of their own interests.''
   Angolan Justice Minister Fernando Franca Van-Dunem said he views
the UNITA insurgents as ``ancilliary forces'' of South Africa. At
another point, he said that from the beginning, Savimbi ``has
always appeared as a man sent by somebody else.''
   The Reagan administration has been supporting Savimbi since
1985, seeing him as an ally in its quest to encourage the removal
of more than 40,000 Cuban troops based in Angola.
   The administration also supports the concept of bringing an end
to the fighting in Angola through national reconciliation talks.
   But the Angolan representatives expressed strong opposition to
achieving a peaceful settlement through an electoral process.
   Van-Dunem, the justice minister, acknowledged that the Angolan
president is not the product of an electoral process but said the
country does elect representatives at the provincial and municipal
levels. Some candidates, he added, are not members of the ruling
MPLA party.
   His colleague, the minister of state, said it is not the policy
of the Angolan government to ``smash UNITA'' once peace is achieved.
   ``We do not identify with the objectives of UNITA, which are to
liquidate the people of Angola,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lefebvre     06-28 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lefebvre,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Catholics Pray For Church Unity As Schismatic Consecration Nears</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope-Cardinals Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swiss Roman Catholics began three days of fasting
and prayer for ``unity of faith'' Tuesday before a scheduled
consecration of rebel bishops that would formalize the first major
split in the church since 1870.
   Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre, who began campaigning against the
``satanic influence of liberalism'' in the church after the Second
Vatican Council reforms of the 1960s, plans to consecrate the four
bishops Thursday at his seminary in Econe, Switzerland.
   Only the pope can name bishops and the Vatican has told
Lefebvre, 82, that consecrating the traditionalist bishops without
approval will mean automatic excommunication _ ejection from the
church _ for all involved.
   Lefebvre's traditionalist movement argues that canon law allows
disobedience to papal authority in a ``situation of emergency.''
The archbishop himself has dismissed the threat of excommunication
as ``without value.''
   Excommunication would create the first schism in the Roman
Catholic Church since Old Catholics broke with Rome over the
doctrine of papal infallibility proclaimed by the First Vatican
Council in 1870.
   The call to pray for ``unity of faith'' among Catholics was
issued by Bishop Henri Schwery of Sion, president of the Swiss
Conference of Bishops. His diocese includes Lefebvre's first
traditionalist seminary, at Econe, where the consecrations are to
be conducted in a huge tent already erected in front of the
buidling.
   Switzerland's bishops urged prayers for unity ``at this very
difficult moment.'' Hans-Peter Roethlin, spokesman for the bishops'
conference, said special services were being held in nearly all
parts of Switzerland, which counts about 3 milloin Roman Catholics
among its 6.3 million people.
   ``Although we must not give up hope that Lefebvre will abandon
his plans, the prayers are chiefly meant to increase awareness of
the importance of church unity,'' Roethlin said in an interview.
   A West German newspaper quoted a leading member of the
traditionalist movement Tuesday as expressing certainty more talks
will be held with the Vatican after the consecrations.
   ``It is only a matter of time until we sit down together
again,'' the Rev. Franz Schmidberger was quoted as saying in an
interview with the newspaper, Die Welt.
   ``Until then, our position will not change,'' he added, in an
apparent reference to automatic excommunication.
   In the Sion Diocese, the faithful were urged to pray and fast
until noon Thursday, about the time the Econe ceremonies are
expected to end.
   Lefebvre says consecrations are necessary to ensure continuity
of the traditionalist movement after his death. He has said it
would be ``orphaned'' without bishops to ordain traditionalist
priests.
   Assisting him at the ceremony will be an 84-year-old former
Brazilian bishop, Antonio de Castro Mayer of Campos, the only one
of more than 2,000 bishops of the church to lend public support to
Lefebvre's 18-year-old campaign against church reforms.
   Lefebvre says the reforms of the Second Vatican Council, which
met from 1962 to 1965, put the church on a course of
``auto-destruction'' by introducing modern rites in the vernacular
and intruducing other ``modernist'' elements.
   His campaign caused Pope Paul VI to order his suspension from
priestly and episcopal functions in 1976, which barred him from
celebrating Mass or giving the sacraments.
   He ignores the ban as ``illegal,'' continuing to ordain new
priests and open new seminaries and other traditionalist centers
throughout the world. His followers use the Tridentine Mass, a
traditional Latin rite for which permission is required.
   On Wednesday, the day before the consecrations, Lefebvre plans
to ordain 16 new traditionalist priests, bringing the total to more
than 220.
   His movement claims millions of followers, but Vatican spokesman
Joaquin Navarro extimates the number at 60,000-80,000. A petition
circulated two years ago urging the Vatican to lift sanctions
against Lefebvre obtained 135,000 signatures.
   The four bishops to be consecrated are Richard Williamson, 48,
who was born in Britain and heads the traditionalist seminary in
Ridgefield, Conn.; Bernard Tissier de Mallerais, 43, executive
director of Lefebvre's movement; Alfonso de Galarreta, 31,
Spanish-born head of the seminary in Argentina, and Bernard Fellay,
30, a Swiss who is the movement's chief administrator.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
