<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DaytimeEmmys     06-28 0556</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Daytime Emmys,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Daytime Emmys Struggle for Attention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No doubt about it, they just don't get the same
attention that their prime-time counterparts do, but don't try to
tell Phil Donahue, who has an office full of them, that Daytime
Emmys aren't important.
   ``The daytime schedule always been a kind of stepsister to the
prime-time schedule ... but I think that stopped bothering us a
long time ago,'' said Donahue, who noted that doing five shows a
week ``is a very challenging assignment.''
   ``You can't just be good on Tuesday, you have to be good all
through the week,'' said Donahue, who recently celebrated the 20th
anniversary of his talk show.
   Donahue will be host Wednesday for the ``Daytime Emmy Awards
Presentation,'' to be carried live beginning at 3 p.m. EDT on CBS.
   The awards go to top daytime drama, talk show, children's
programming and game show, among other categories. They will be
presented in the ballroom of the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel in New York.
   CBS' ``Pee-wee's Playhouse,'' the innovative live-action show
starring comedian Paul Reubens as a oversized kid in a tiny suit,
topped the technical awards last year but lost out as best
children's show to PBS' long-running ``Sesame Street.'' Both are
nominated again this year along with public television's ``Mister
Rogers' Neighborhood.''
   ``Pee-wee'' had the most total nominations this year _ 14 _ and
won three technical Emmys that were handed out Sunday.
   Vying for best daytime drama this year are NBC's ``Santa
Barbara'' and ``All My Children,'' ABC's ``General Hospital'' and
CBS' ``The Young and the Restless'' and ``As the World Turns,''
last year's winner.
   Best game or audience-participation show will be chosen from
among CBS' ``The Price Is Right'' and ``The $25,000 Pyramid'' and
NBC's ``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``Win, Lose or Draw.'' Except for
Pat Sajak of ``Wheel,'' all the game-show hosts were nominated in
their category, plus Alex Trebek for ``Classic Concentration.''
   ``Donahue'' will go up against ``The Oprah Winfrey Show,'' which
won last year as best talk or information program. Both are
syndicated. Winfrey also won as best host. Also nominated are the
syndicated ``Wil Shriner Show,'' and PBS' ``The Frugal Gourmet''
and ``This Old House.''
   Susan Lucci is nominated as outstanding lead actress in a drama
for the ninth time. She has never won. She plays Erika Kane
Montgomery in ``All My Children.'' Luccia will be up against
Elizabeth Hubbard from ``As the World Turns,'' Erika Slezak of
``One Life to Live,'' Helen Gallagher of ``Ryan's Hope,'' and Marcy
Walker of ``Santa Barbara.''
   Larry Bryggman, who won last year's lead actor award for his
role as Dr. John Dixon in ``As the World Turns'' is nominated again
along with Robert Gentry and David Canary, both of ``All My
Children,'' Stephen Nichols of NBC's ``Days of Our Lives'' and A.
Martinez of ``Santa Barbara.''
   Last year's winner for best animated program, ``Jim Henson's
Muppet Babies'' on CBS, was nominated again this year along with
NBC's ``Smurfs'' and ``Alvin and the Chipmunks,'' CBS'
``Storybreak'' and the syndicated ``Disney's Duck Tales.''
   ABC received two nominations for outstanding children's special
for ``Just a Regular Kid: An AIDS Story'' and ``The Kid Who
Wouldn't Quit: The Brad Silverman Story.'' CBS received two
nominations for ``Never Say Goodbye'' and ``What If I'm Gay?''
</TEXT>
