<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush-AIDS     06-28 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-AIDS,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Endorses Law Barring Discrimination Against AIDS Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush today
endorsed the recommendation of a federal advisory commission on
AIDS for a law barring discrimination against people suffering from
the deadly virus.
   ``I think it is needed,'' Bush said, less than 24 hours after
the advisory panel presented its report to President Reagan.
   ``I think it is important to do a lot to lay to rest some of the
fears. There is a lot of misunderstanding,'' Bush said.
   Announcing his position, Bush acknowledged that he was getting
out ahead of Reagan, who did not comment on the recommendations.
Instead, Reagan directed his drug policy adviser, Dr. Ian
MacDonald, to come up within 30 days with `a course of action that
takes us forward.''
   Bush said Reagan ``did the right thing. ... How can the White
House be asked to take an instant position?''
   When it was pointed out that Bush was doing just that, the vice
president said Reagan ``just saw this thing yesterday. He's not
running for president. Maybe he wasn't asked the question, either.''
   Bush, certain to be the Republican presidential nominee, said
``I've got a different role here. I want to say what I think.''
   He spoke with reporters on Air Force II on a flight to northern
California.
   He planned to tour NASA's AMES Research Center at Mountain View
and then travel to San Franciso, a city whose homosexual population
has been devastated by AIDS.
   Bush, asked if the government should spend more on AIDS
research, said, ``No.'' He said he based his feeling on the advice
of experts at the National Institutes of Health.
   ``We have the proper level of funding. It's close to $1
billion,'' Bush said.
</TEXT>
