<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrademarkBattle 1stLd-Writethru a0665 06-28 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trademark Battle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rolls-Royce Takes on Pet Casket Business</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Fixes style to Rolls-Royce, with hyphen, throughout.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Luxury automaker Rolls-Royce may like to carry
its passengers in style over the highways of life, but it doesn't
want people to mistakenly think it takes family pets into the
hereafter.
   The British company is challenging a logo used by a company that
makes caskets and burial kits for pets.
   Rolls-Royce has filed documents with the U.S. Patent Office in
Washington, alleging that Pet Rest Inc., owned by Mike and Sandy
McCormack, has adopted a logo confusingly close to its own.
   Pet Rest's logo includes a capital P and an interlocking capital
R. Rolls-Royce said it has used two interlocking capital Rs to
identify its company since 1925.
   ``Literally, I sat down with a tablet and drew variations of the
letters P and R, side-by-side, up and down and interlocking,''
McCormack said. ``We tried to find any way that the letters could
work well together in a logo. It was by chance that we selected the
one we use today.''
   The McCormacks founded their business three years ago in Lima,
about 75 south of Toledo. Mrs. McCormack said the burial kits
include satin-lined burial capsules, suggestions for a memorial
service and even grief counseling. Prices range from $80 to $1,499
and kits can accommodate pets as large as a Doberman pinscher.
   The company could gross up to $1 million this year, the
McCormacks said.
   Mrs. McCormack learned of the challenge from Rolls-Royce this
month by registered letter.
   ``It was very surprising,'' she said. ``We were just astounded
that anyone could confuse a Rolls-Royce product with a Pet Rest
product.''
   She said the PR logo is not stamped on the burial kits, but is
used on boxes and in advertising.
   Attorneys for Rolls-Royce declined to comment. But in documents
filed with the appeals board, the attorneys argue that the
similarity of the trademarks might give rise to a mistaken belief
that Pet Rest's products originate from or are sponsored by
Rolls-Royce.
   The McCormacks plan to fight _ at least for now.
   ``Rather than come on with a lawsuit against a small company
like ours, they'll just fight the trademark year after year with
the hope that after five years and perhaps $25,000, if we can even
afford to drag it on that long, we will give up,'' Mrs. McCormack
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
