<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-CentralAmerica 1stLd-Writethru a0663 06-28 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Central America, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz to Offer Support to Latin Democracies, Lawmakers Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs of Fitzwater comment after 6th graf, ``One
participant''</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   By JIM DRINKARD=
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George Shultz's trip to
Central America this week will have the primary purpose of
``shoring up'' the four democracies in the region by demonstrating
long-term U.S. support, according to congressional leaders who met
with Shultz on Tuesday.
   During a 1{-hour breakfast with House Speaker Jim Wright, House
Minority Leader Robert Michel and other leaders, Shultz made no
mention of renewing military aid to the Contra rebels fighting
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government, participants said.
   ``He says what he really wants to do is to shore up and
reinforce our commitment to the success of the four democratic
countries in the region,'' said Wright, D-Texas. The speaker called
the discussion a sign of a ``shift in emphasis'' by the
administration.
   ``There's a presumption that he wouldn't be doing this unless
there were a reason, some change in policy, some thought as to
where they're going,'' said one Democratic leadership aide,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Shultz leaves Wednesday for a three-day trip to Guatemala, El
Salvador, Honduras and Costa Rica. He does not plan to visit
Nicaragua, where talks between the Sandinista government and the
U.S.-backed rebels remain stalled.
   One participant, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Shultz
told the leaders: ``This is not a Contra aid trip. This is a peace
and democracy trip.''
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater conceded that the
U.S. push to democratize Nicaragua has stalled and said further
decisions on strategy must await completion of Shultz's trip to
Central America.
   Amid increasing reports that Contra troops are returning to
their base camps inside Nicaragua, and with no new peace talks
scheduled, Fitzwater was asked whether Reagan had decided to submit
a new aid package to Congress.
   ``We will not have any judgment on the package until sometime
after'' Shultz returns from the region on Friday, he replied, ``and
we don't have a specific schedule, even on that.''
   Wright, who has been the chief opponent of administration
efforts to send weapons to the anti-Sandinista rebels, said Shultz
appeared to recognize that Congress is in no mood to vote further
military aid.
   ``Maybe rather than trying to send more weapons ... it might be
mroe useful to make a convincing demonstration of our long-term
support of democracy in those countries that practice it,'' Wright
said.
   Michel, R-Ill., acknowledged there was no current sentiment in
Congress for a renewal of military aid, but he said there was a
need to do something ``to put (the talks) back on track and to put
the Contras in a better position. That's a congressional
responsibility.''
   He said during the meeting, Shultz showed an interest in
multilateral talks that would include all Central American
countries, including Nicaragua, and could lead to regional
non-aggression treaties and the expulsion of foreign military
advisers from Nicaragua.
   There was also some discussion about the possibility of a
regional economc aid package that could serve as an added
enticement for the Sandinistas to conclude a peace accord and make
democratic reforms, participants said.
   Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., said Shultz told the bipartisan
leadership group that the rebels are interested in resuming the
peace talks that broke off earlier this month, but do not want to
hold the talks in the Nicaraguan capital of Managua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
