<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeamsterPlea     06-28 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamster Plea,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamster Official Pleads Guilty To Misdemeanor Conspiracy Charge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teamsters Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Teamster organizer accused of accepting a
bribe from an FBI agent posing as a Hollywood producer who wanted
to make a non-union movie has pleaded guilty to misdemeanor
conspiracy.
   Russell J. Masetta of Teamsters Local 848 in El Monte, who was
originally indicted on a felony charge, entered his plea Monday.
   The government said it would recommend a maximum six-month
sentence, but U.S. District Judge William D. Keller said Masetta
can withdraw the plea if he is sentenced to serve any time in jail
in addition to a period of probation.
   Masetta's attorney, Richard Beck, said he expects Keller to look
at his client as ``a family man'' with no prior convictions.
   Masetta admitted he conspired with a reputed Mafia captain to
accept about $1,000 from the undercover FBI agent he believed to be
a film producer.
   In exchange for the money, Masetta allegedly promised the
producer initially that the union would not try to organize workers
on the production, said Richard A. Stavin, a special attorney for
the Justice Department's organized crime strike force in Los
Angeles.
   Masetta accepted about $200 before backing out of the deal,
Stavin said.
   He was charged in the conspiracy case with Luigi Gelfuso Jr.,
who has been described by prosecutors as a reputed Mafia captain.
   Gelfuso has denied any connection with organized crime, as has
Masetta.
   Masetta was originally indicted on a felony extortion conspiracy
charge alleging that he and Gelfuso planned to take $25,000 from
the film producer.
   The government's key witness died of cancer, though, and the
charge was reduced to a misdemeanor through a plea bargain.
   Masetta's plea was entered one day before the federal government
charged that the International Brotherhood of Teamsters is
dominated by organized crime and filed a civil suit in New York to
force free elections and other reforms in the nation's largest
union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1758EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--MichiganPrimary     06-28 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Michigan Primary,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michigan Panel Votes to Restore Presidential Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Michigan House Elections Committee
voted unanimously Tuesday in favor of reinstating a presidential
primary election in 1992.
   Under the Senate-passed bill, which now goes to the full House,
voters would have to declare in advance whether they wanted to vote
on the Republican or Democratic side.
   The provision was added by lawmakers to meet the Democratic
National Committee rules which don't recognize results of ``open
primaries'' allowing members of each party to cross over and vote
for another party's candidate.
   In Michigan, the 1976 primary marked the last time that both
major parties participated in the open primary. The Republicans had
a primary in 1980 but opted for a multi-tiered convention system in
the past two elections.
   Since 1980, the Democrats have held caucuses every four years.
   Leaders of both parties have supported the return to a primary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
