<DOCNO> AP880628-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Personnel     06-28 0130</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Personnel,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan To Nominate Twaddell To Mauritania Ambassadorship</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan intends to nominate William
H. Twaddell, a career Foreign Service officer, to be ambassador to
the Republic of Mauritania, the White House announced Tuesday.
   Twaddell, a member of the Peace Corps from 1963-65, would
succeed Robert L. Pugh.
   Twaddell, 47, entered the Foreign Service in 1969 after two
years as a reporter for the New York Daily News. In the Foreign
Service, he had assignments as a consular officer in Dhadran, Saudi
Arabia, the American Embassy in Caracas, Venezuela and, more
recently, in Maputo, Mozambique. He was the deputy chief of mission
for the U.S. Embassy in Bamako, Mali, from 1985-87, and since 1987
has been attending the Senior Seminar at the Foreign Service
Institute.
</TEXT>
