<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1710EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-NavyTrash     06-28 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Trash,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Could Help Pollution Fight by Limiting Plastic Packaging</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The most important step the Navy can take to
reduce plastic pollution of the ocean is to reduce the amount of
plastic going aboard its ships in food and other packaging, a panel
of Navy, environmentalist and animal welfare representatives said
Tuesday.
   The Navy already has begun to carry out some recommendations and
has canceled orders for 11 million small plastic bags for use in
carrying purchases away from ships' stores, the committee said.
   The committee was organized last year by the Keystone Center, a
group of environmental mediators based in Keystone, Colo., in
anticipation of legisation passed later to implement an
international agreement to end disposal of plastic trash at sea.
   Environmentalists increasingly are concerned over the killing of
birds, fish and marine mammals by long-lasting plastics such as
six-pack rings that are eaten by or entangle sea creatures.
   ``We are trying to reverse a tradition of millennia'' of trash
disposal at sea, said Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass., at the news
conference where the recommendations were presented.
   `The Navy's initial position was that it couldn't possibly
comply; that it would take at least 20 years,'' said Studds, who is
chairman of the fisheries, wildlife conservation and environment
subcommittee of the House Merchant Marine and Fisheries Committee.
   The Keystone committee said such skepticism was quickly turned
into enthusiastic cooperation, largely as a result of the work of
Nancy Stehle, deputy director for the environment in the office of
the assistant secretary of the Navy for shipbuilding and logistics.
   She ``set the example and established the tone we all needed for
frankness and openness. She focused our attention on helping the
Navy solve the problem,'' the committee said.
   Warships pose a particular problem because space aboard them is
very limited.
   The recommendations call for reducing the plastics carried
because that would ``greatly reduce the need for expensive
technologies intended to facilitate storage and disposal.''
   The committee said the Navy should review specifications for
food and other items to buy them in degradable, non-plastic
packaging whereever possible, support development of compactors and
degradable plastics, unload unnecessary plastics before leaving
port and separate plastics for carriage home before disposing of
other trash at sea.
   In addition to representatives of the Navy, congressional staffs
and the Keystone Center, the committee had members from the
American Cetacean Society, the Animal Protection Institute of
America, the Oceanic Society, Defenders of Wildlife, the Center for
Environmental Education, the Texas Environmental Coalition, the
National Fish and Wildlife Foundation, the Monitor Consoritum and
Greenpeace.
   The Navy must report to Congress in three years on its progress
in complying with the international agreement on plastic disposal
after five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
