<DOCNO> AP880628-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1538EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope-Cardinals Bjt   06-28 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Cardinals, Bjt,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Installs 24 Cardinals; Appeals to Rebel Archbishop's
Followers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos ROM2,3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II installed 24 cardinals
Tuesday, offered them as symbols of church unity and urged
followers of rebel French Archbishop Marcel Lefebvre not to break
with the papacy.
   Lefebvre plans to consecrate four traditionalist bishops
Thursday without papal permission, which the Vatican has said will
result in automatic excommunication of those involved. John Paul
says a schism in the Roman Catholic church, the first since 1870,
appears inevitable.
   The church crisis cast a shadow over the otherwise joyous
ceremony of conferring red hats on the new ``princes of the
church,'' who include two U.S. archbishops, James Hickey of
Washington, D.C., and Edmund Szoka of Detroit.
   Prelates from Lithuania and Hong Kong also were in the group,
indicating the pontiff's desire to expand church influence in the
Soviet Union and China.
   Without mentioning Lefebvre by name, John Paul said: ``We are
very saddened by the news ... that one of our brothers in the
episcopate, who for several years has withheld the required
obedience to the Holy See ... will soon proceed with the ordination
of bishops without the apostolic mandate, and will thus break the
unity of the church, drawing with him large numbers of his
followers into a dangerous situation of schism.''
   He said Lefebvre, who plans to consecrate the biships at his
seminary in Econe, Switzerland, had appeared ready for a
settlement, ``but now it seems that the decision of our brother can
no longer be reversed.''
   Referring to followers of the 82-year-old traditionalist, John
Paul said: ``We pray and exhort them with all our heart to remain
in the house of the Father and to understand that every truth of
faith and every correct way of living finds its place in the
church.''
   Lefebvre, who rejects many reforms of the 1962-65 Second Vatican
Council, was suspended from priestly duties in 1976 by Pope Paul VI
but has ordained more than 200 priests since then in defiance of
the Vatican.
   A compromise reached by the two sides last month fell through
and Lefebvre said he would go ahead with the consecration. He says
traditionalist bishops are necessary to ensure the continuity of
his movement after he dies.
   The last schism in the church occurred in 1870, when the Old
Catholics broke with Rome after the First Vatican Council
proclaimed papal infallibility.
   John Paul made his comments Tuesday to 58 cardinals, who held a
closed meeting in the frescoed Consistory Hall of the Apostolic
Palace to give formal approval to the new cardinals. The remarks,
in Latin, were released by the Vatican.
   After the private ceremony, Cardinal Agostino Casaroli, the
Vatican secretary of state, read the 24 names to an audience of
about 10,000 in the Paul VI auditorium. Each new cardinal wore a
crimson cassock and gold cross.
   The pope, wearing a gold-embroidered red cape over white robes,
entered and sat in a high-backed beige chair at the center of the
stage. One by one, the new cardinals climbed the steps and knelt
before John Paul, who placed on their heads the three-cornered hat
known as a biretta.
   Speaking in Italian, the pontiff said the hat ``signifies that
you should be ready to comport yourselves with strength, up to the
point of spilling blood, for the growth of the Christian faith, for
peace and tranquility of the people of God and for the freedom and
the spread of the Holy Roman Church.''
   He frequently stressed Christian unity both in the remarks to
the meeting of cardinals and his public address at the elevation.
   Noting the diversity of the 24 prelates, who represent 17
countries and five continents, he stressed the ``common roots of
the College of Cardinals, constituted by the unity of the seat of
the Roman church.''
   John Paul also announced long-awaited reforms in the Curia, the
Vatican administration. Changes include a special oversight panel
for the Vatican Bank, which was linked to Italy's worst postwar
banking scandal.
   Four new cardinals are from Italy and two each from the United
States, Brazil, Spain and India. The others are from Canada,
Mozambique, Colombia, Australia, Hungary, Cameroon, Austria,
France, West Germany, Mauritius, Hong Kong and Lithuania.
   The College of Cardinals, the most important governing body of
the church, now has 160 members, 121 of whom under age 80 and thus
eligible to elect a pope. John Paul had named 25 new cardinals, but
Hans Urs von Balthasar of Switzerland died Sunday at age 82.
</TEXT>
