<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GrawemeyerAward     06-28 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grawemeyer Award,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Harvard Professors Win $150,000 Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED M. NATT JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Harvard professors, Richard E.
Neustadt and Ernest R. May, were named Tuesday as the first
recipients of a $150,000 award for ideas that foster world order.
   Neustadt and May won the 1988 Grawemeyer Award for Ideas
Improving World Order for their proposal of how contemporary
political leaders should draw on past experience in tackling the
world's problems.
   The two said they would use the prize to follow up on their
winning entry.
   Neustadt said the award should bring attention to their winning
idea, which is set forth in ``Thinking in Time: The Uses of History
for Decision-Makers,'' a 329-page book published by The Free Press
in 1986.
   Neustadt, 69, is a professor of government; May, 59, is a
history professor.
   In the book, the two proposed that lessons from the past can be
useful in shaping modern public policy if they are used carefully
and early enough.
   They explain, for example, how the Kennedy administration's
analysis of Soviet history and Nikita Khrushchev's personal
background helped resolve the Cuban missile crisis in the early
1960s.
   May said their follow-up work will involve developing a more
efficient means of communication in times of crises between a
decision-maker such as the president and experts.
   ``When the president has to make a decision on a foreign
government ... he needs to communicate with an expert on that
country,'' May said in a telephone interview from Sunriver, Ore.
   Jurors chosen by the University of Louisville reviewed 60
nominations before deciding on Neustadt and May's entry.
   ``When policies fail because of mistaken decisions in major
issues affecting international relations, progress toward world
order is set back and confident expectations turn sour,'' the
jurors said.
   ``The authors show plainly when, where, how and why this happens
and develop prescriptions for avoiding it,'' they said.
   The jurors said statesmen, legislators, scholars and the public
could find useful lessons for the future in the work.
   The international relations prize is one of four $150,000 awards
established by Charles Grawemeyer, a 1934 graduate of the
University of Louisville, to stimulate the worldwide development of
new ideas.
   A Grawemeyer award in the field of music composition has been
awarded in three prior years. An award in education is supposed to
be made this year; an award in religion is supposed to be made next
spring.
   Grawemeyer, 74, operated a local plastics business, then retired
and became an investor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
