<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ABA-Chauvin     06-28 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ABA-Chauvin,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Louisville Lawyer Poised To Head Bar Association</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   L. Stanley Chauvin Jr., preparing to
become president-elect of the American Bar Association, doesn't
forget the worn, country paths that led him to the job.
   A new computer terminal sits in one corner of Chauvin's
Louisville office, electronically linking bar associations, lawyers
and others in the profession.
   If the fixture can be considered a symbol of the new issues
facing lawyers as Chauvin takes office, the picture above it of the
Class of '53 at Castle Heights Military Academy in Lebanon, Tenn.,
could represent the past Chauvin cherishes.
   When Chauvin, 53, assumes his elected office at the ABA's House
of Delegates meeting Aug. 10 in Toronto, he will bring to it the
experience of a lawyer who learned the ropes by watching his peers.
   ``When I came to the bar, if you heard someone was going to try
a case on a unique question of law, ... it was not unusual to go
over, sit down, listen to part of their case, look at the
instructions, talk to the lawyers about it. Lawyers are willing to
do it now, but it's a matter of time,'' he said in an interview
Monday.
   Nostalgic as Chauvin may be about days when time wasn't such a
luxury, he is eager to begin a more hectic pace, traveling and
speaking on behalf of the 350,000-member association in addition to
his practice with the firm of Barnett & Alagia, where he handles
both corporate and civil cases.
   He has been pursuing the ABA presidency for seven or eight
years. ``I pretty much decided (then) that it was a possibility or
something that if it were possible, I would like to do it.''
   Chauvin succeeds Robert D. Raven of San Francisco as
president-elect and Raven moves up to the post of president.
Chauvin will become president a year from now.
   Chauvin was chairman of the House of Delegates from 1982 to
1984, a post he believes prepared him for the chief job.
   ``You know, that's not one of your easier jobs, being locked in
a room with 400 lawyers. I thought, `Well, if I can handle this
job, then it might become a reality.''' The delegates decide policy
stands for the ABA.
   With Chauvin as chairman, the delegates took up such issues as
the code of professional conduct, gay rights, the insanity defense
and malpractice insurance, topics that allowed him to use his
folksy style to defuse controversy.
   The president of the ABA concerns himself primarily with current
matters, while the president-elect plans for the coming year,
Chauvin said.
   His agenda covers everything from lawyer advertising to
children's rights to toxic waste to alternative ways of resolving
disputes, but they all fall under the two obligations Chauvin
believes lawyers have: to protect citizens' rights and to make
society better.
   Chauvin is delighted with his upcoming position.
   ``I would not be any happier doing anything else that I know
of.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
