<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AmericanCardinals     06-28 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Cardinals,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archbishops of Detroit and Washington Become Cardinals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pope-Cardinals Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edmund Szoka whispered his thanks to the
pope in Polish and James A. Hickey felt ``filled with grace'' when
the archbishops of Detroit and Washington, D.C., became cardinals
on Tuesday.
   More than 500 Americans were among about 10,000 people who
watched Szoka, Hickey and 22 other churchmen kneel one by one
before Pope John Paul II to have the three-cornered red had placed
on their heads and become ``princes of the church.''
   Cardinals, who elect the pope, make up the highest governing
body of the Roman Catholic Church.
   ``It was a very emotional experience,'' Szoka said after the
ceremony. ``I was much more moved than I expected.'' His parents
were born in Poland, John Paul's native land.
   The cardinals first received certificates of their new office
from the Vatican secretary of state, Cardinal Agostino Casaroli.
   As the tall, ruddy-faced Hickey mounted the platform in the Paul
VI auditorium, friends and relatives jumped up and cheered.
Applause filled the hall when Szoka, a slight man with glasses,
received his certificate.
   In a later part of the ceremony, John Paul gave the churchmen
their red hats, called birettas, and made them titular heads of
different churches in Rome. Each wore a red cassock and gold cross.
   Hickey, 67, walked briskly up the 10 steps and knelt solemnly
before the pope.
   John Paul placed the biretta gently on his head, blessed him and
made him titular head of the Church of St. Maria Mother of the
Redemptor. Cardinals are appointed heads of Rome churches because
of a church tradition that only pastors of Rome can elect the pope.
   Hickey kissed the pope on both cheeks and walked over to embrace
other cardinals.
   ``It was an awesome moment,'' he said at a reception in the
Pontifical North American College, where he was rector in 1969-74.
``I felt very much filled with grace.''
   Szoka, 60, listened attentively as John Paul blessed him and
made him titular head of the Church of Saints Andrea and Gregorio.
   As he rose, Szoka whispered, ``I thank you most sincerely for
everything'' in Polish, and the pontiff smiled.
   ``He said something'' in response, Szoka told reporters later,
but ``I can't remember now what he said.''
   Both new American cardinals are considered conservatives on
doctrinal matters but have increased the efforts of their dioceses
in helping the poor, minorities and victims of AIDs, acquired
immunity deficiency syndrome.
   Tuesday's ceremony, known as a consistory, brought the number of
active Roman Catholic cardinals in the United States to five. Four
others are retired and three U.S. citizens who are cardinals work
outside the United States.
   Hickey, who previously served as bishop of Cleveland, said he
hoped as cardinal to focus more attention on Catholic education
because ``so many people know only snitches and snatches of their
faith.''
   Dozens of members of Detroit's large Polish-American community
came to Rome for the ceremony.
   ``A Polish bishop was becoming cardinal and we've got a Polish
pope,'' said Raymond Gientke, 65, of Northville, Mich. ``The time
was right.''
   Ethel Crawford of Detroit, 61, said: ``It was indescribable.''
   Szoka, a native of Grand Rapids, Mich., was ordained in 1954 and
became bishop of Gaylord, Mich. in 1971. He was made leader of the
Detroit archdiocese's 1.2 million Roman Catholics in 1981.
   Hickey was born in Midland, Mich., in 1920. He became archbishop
of Washington in 1980.
</TEXT>
