<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Irish     06-28 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Bomb Explodes on School Bus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An IRA bomb exploded Tuesday in
a school bus carrying 12 Protestant and Roman Catholic students,
seriously injuring one of them and the driver, a part-time soldier.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army said in a message to the
media it planted the bomb but would hold an investigation because a
civilian had been ``regrettably injured,'' a tacit acknowledgement
the attack went awry.
   The seriously injured girl, Gillian Latimer, 14, underwent
emergency surgery in Enniskillen, 10 miles from the blast, and was
then transferred to Royal Victoria Hospital in Belfast, 70 miles
away, police said.
   She was in the intensive care unit with chest injuries and a
broken arm, the hospital said.
   Four other children, the youngest being 12 years old, were
treated for minor cuts and bruises and shock. The driver, a member
of the Ulster Defense Regiment militia, who was not immediately
identified, was cut in the face and eyes by flying glass.
   The girls were members of both the province's Protestant
majority and Roman Catholic minority.
   ``The bus was coming up to a stop, but it hadn't slowed down,
when there was a big bang,'' said Madonna Murphy, 18, a Catholic
pupil on the bus.
   ``Glass was everywhere and some of the girls didn't know what
had happened. I went down to the back to comfort the wee ones, who
were frightened and crying. The I saw a girl behind me. Her arm was
just hanging there, and I could see blood coming through her
blouse.''
   Miss Murphy added: ``I hope this doesn't drive the Protestants
and Catholics apart in Enniskillen. That is the only aim this bomb
would have but we won't let it work.''
   An IRA bomb in Enniskillen killed 12 Protestants attending a war
memorial service in November.
   Dr. Brian Mawhinney, education minister of the province, said:
``There can be no excuse, no attempt to justify, no cynical apology
from the men of violence. Northern Ireland is a God-fearing
province and it's quite clear what the IRA means by `Suffer little
children.'''
   Police said the bomb apparently was put in the front of the bus
while parked overnight outside a school in Maguiresbridge in County
Fermanagh, near the border with the Irish Republic. They said it
was probably meant to explode before the driver began collecting
children to drive them to school in Enniskillen.
   The bomb, with 2-3 pounds of explosives, went off after the bus
had been en route for half an hour.
   Police said the driver, despite his injuries, carried the badly
injured girl to the rear of the bus and gave her mouth-to-mouth
resuscitation before ambulances arrived.
   The Ulster Defense Regiment is recruited in Northern Ireland to
assist the British army and 175 of its members have been killed
since the IRA launched its violent campaign in 1969 to force a
British withdrawal from the province. More than 2,650 civilians,
police and soldiers have been killed in the conflict.
   Police said the IRA unit that planted the Enniskillen bomb in
November was likely to have been the same which bombed the school
bus and it might be based across the border in the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
