<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Stingers     06-28 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stingers,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Disturbed Over Stinger Missiles in Hands of Small Gulf Country</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tiny Persian Gulf sheikdom of Qatar
illegally obtained Stinger missiles from unnamed ``third parties''
and the United States is demanding an explanation and return of the
weapons, the State Department said Tuesday.
   The incident could upset traditionally good relations between
Washington and the oil-rich Arab country. It is believed the
shoulder-fired Stingers, often called a terrorist's dream because
they are easy to handle, were intended for Afghan rebels, a U.S.
official said.
   The official, who spoke only on condition on anomymity, said
that might mean the U.S.-made missiles were turned over to Iran,
which then gave them to Qatar.
   Many of the guerrillas fighting the Soviet-backed Kabul
government with U.S. support are Moslem fundamentalists with at
least a theological and philosopohical kinship to the Iranians.
   The Middle East and Persian Gulf already were awash in a rising
tide of missiles when reports of Stingers in Qatar sent Assistant
Secretary of State Richard W. Murphy to Doha last week for an
explanation.
   The Soviet Union, ignoring U.S. appeals, has sold a variety of
missiles to Syria and Libya, while China has provided Saudi Arabia
with new rockets. This has alarmed both the United States and
Israel, which is seeking a new surface-to-air missile as a
counterbalance.
   Under U.S. law, Stingers can be transferred to a third party
only with American consent. The missiles have been used effectively
by Afghan rebels against Soviet helicopters and other targets, and
are credited with hastening a decision by Moscow to withdraw the
Red Army after more than eight years of occupation.
   Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, said Qatar
had refused to supply details of its acquisition of the Stingers.
``We have been intensively involved in discussions with the Qataris
on their acquisition of Stingers through unauthorized sources,''
the U.S. official said.
   ``These Stingers were not procured from the U.S. government, and
must have been obtained illegally from third parties,'' Redman
said. ``That they were procured improperly, and are in Qatar
without authorization are matters of great concern to us. We are
seeking the return of these missiles.''
   He said he did not know how many missiles were involved. ``We're
trying to determine how and from where Qatar obtained the
Stingers,'' he said. ``We still don't have any conclusions as to
where the Stingers came from. We still need answers from the
Qataris, and that's the reason we're having these discussions, to
see if we can get those answers.''
</TEXT>
