<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     06-28 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Pledges $3 Billion in Housing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis blasted Reagan
administration housing cuts on Tuesday and promised to spend $3
billion on housing if elected to help people achieve ``one piece of
the American dream.''
   Dukakis spoke to reporters at the site of a former Boston public
school that was razed to make way for more than a dozen homes sold
through a state program offering subsidized mortgages to low- and
moderate-income families buying their first home.
   He endorsed a Senate housing bill sponsored by California Sen.
Alan Cranston, who accompanied Dukakis to the event. Dukakis said
the bill provided for a ``a federal commitment, a re-commitment to
affordable housing'' and promised to provide $3 billion in funding
for the legislation within three years of taking office.
   He touted provisions of the bill calling for low-interest
mortgages for new homes and renovation of existing housing stock
and said similar programs he began in Massachusetts had proven
highly successful.
   ``I don't see how we can talk about a bright economic future for
America if it doesn't include decent and affordable housing for all
our citizens,'' Dukakis said in a speech at a housing forum before
visiting the neighborhood.
   Dukakis, the certain Democratic presidential nominee, dismissed
speculation about his search for a running mate by saying ``there's
only one guy who knows what's going on and that's the guy you're
looking at.''
   But he refused to rule out Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn for the No. 2
spot on the ticket despite Nunn's insistence that he is not
interested. He also said Florida Sen. Bob Graham remained in
contention.
   The Massachusetts governor planned to meet Wednesday in
Washington with about 30 Democratic senators, including Nunn and
Graham, before a Midwest campaign swing. ``Some of them may be
possibilities,'' for the vice presidential nomination,'' Dukakis
said.
   ``I don't know,'' he answered when asked when he would make a
decision. ``I'm enjoying the process and I hope you are too.''
   Cranston said the ``betting on Capitol Hill seems to be John
Glenn and Llyod Bentsen as the front-runners'' to share the ticket
with Dukakis, with Nunn running third in the speculation. Glenn and
Bentsen are senators from Ohio and Texas, respectively.
   Dukakis laughed when told of Cranston's assessment. ``I'm not a
betting man,'' he said.
   Dukakis blamed the lack of affordable housing on a 90 percent
cut in federal spending on housing by Reagan and said there were
2.5 million homeless people in the United States ``largely because
of the cuts in federal commitment to affordable housing.''
   ``I don't know that he has a policy,'' Dukakis said when asked
about the housing policies of Vice President George Bush, the
certain Republican nominee.
   At the housing forum, Dukakis said a national housing program
should include some goverment support, either through loans and
grants or through other incentives, such as donating land or
granting zoning variances.
   ``It takes partnership, it takes commitment, it takes an
understanding that we are one nation,'' Dukakis.
   ``One piece of the American dream is an affordable home or
apartment,'' Dukakis said. ``And anything less than that just won't
do.''
   Dukakis cited efforts by some unions to invest their pension
funds in housing developments that guarantee a percentage of the
units to low- and moderate-income families.
   ``It creates good jobs at union scale and does it in a way that
creates good housing,'' he said.
</TEXT>
