<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DCResidency     06-28 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DC Residency,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Removes Residency Requirement for District Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House killed a residency requirement for
District of Columbia police officers on Tuesday, reflecting
congressional concern that the rule was hurting recruiting while
the crime rate went up.
   In a rare instance in which Congress intervened in an issue
normally handled at the local level, an amendment that scuttled the
city's eight-year-old residency requirement was approved by a
246-163 vote.
   The measure, offered by Rep. Stan Parris, R-Va., came as the
House considered the city's $3.2 billion budget for fiscal 1989.
   Parris had intended to replace the residency rule with a system
giving hiring preference to city residents, but Democrats moved
that the vote be contested only on the residency issue. Parris'
amendment passed after the preferential hiring language was dropped.
   ``The message trying to be conveyed is that there are problems
in public safety,'' Parris said after the vote.
   D.C. Mayor Marion Barry, a steadfast supporter of the residency
rule, was not immediately available for comment.
   ``We look forward to seeing an improvement in the numbers and
quality of the people joining the police department,'' said Gary
Hankins, spokesman for the local chapter of the Fraternal Order of
Police. ``We remain convinced this will substantially improve
public safety in the District of Columbia.''
   Parris' amendment will apply to all city positions, including
police and firefighters.
   Supporters of the residency requirement accused Parris of
meddling in city affairs. But he and other opponents of the
residency rule claimed that a combination of increasing crime and
decreasing police applications equaled a looming public safety
problem in the nation's capital.
   Police statistics indicate crime has increased by 17 percent for
the first four months of 1988, compared with the same period a year
ago, and police blame an upsurge in drug-related violence for much
of the city's 146 homicides so far this year. There were 98
killings at this time last year, and 228 for all of 1987.
   Applications to the police department also are down. According
to police records, there were 3,100 applications in 1985, but just
591 last year. The city has 3,880 officers, but some members of
Congress long have favored expanding the police force to 5,100
members.
   Opponents of the residency rule argued that it severely
restricted the city's job applicant pool, particularly in crucial
public safety positions.
   Rep. Ron Dellums, D-Calif., who chairs the House District of
Columbia Committee, said the House would become ``a super city
council'' if it voted to repeal the act, and Rep. Julian Dixon,
D-Calif., suggested that the House wait for the District of
Columbia Council to act on the matter.
   The bill now moves to the Senate, where Parris said he expects
no opposition to the repeal of the residency requirement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
