<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Mexico     06-28 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mexico,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Angry with Mexico, Recalls Ambassador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An angry Reagan administration recalled its
ambassador from Mexico on Tuesday after Mexico released a Puerto
Rican separatist wanted by U.S. authorities for terrorist
activities.
   Mexican authorities freed William Morales, 37, from prison last
Friday and put him on a plane to Cuba, effectively erasing any
possibility of his extradition to the United States.
   The recall of Ambassador Charles Pilliod from Mexico City for
consultations was a sign of U.S. displeasure over the Mexican
action. State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman did not say
whether any retaliatory measures are planned. He described the
release as politically motivated.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said it was an outrage
for Mexico to release and deport to Cuba a man who had not yet
completed a prison sentence for the murder of a Mexican police
officer. Morales had been serving an eight-year prison term for the
1983 slaying.
   ``This decision is an inexplicable affront to otherwise
excellent U.S.-Mexican relations and a great blow to U.S. and
Mexican efforts to combat the scourge of international terrorism,''
Fitzwater said.
   He said the State Department had summoned the Mexican ambassador
to the United States, Jorge Espinosa de los Reyes, on Monday night
``and expressed our anger over the release of this convicted
terrorist.''
   Redman said Morales is an escaped U.S. prisoner who has been
sentenced to jail terms totaling more than 100 years. He was
implicated in over 50 bombings by a Puerto Rican separatist group
that from 1976 to 1978 resulted in the death and injury of many
individuals, the spokesman said.
   A U.S. Embassy official in Mexico City, insisting on anonymity,
said Mexico waited five days before informing the United States of
Morales' release.
   Mexico has described Morales as a political fighter who could
not be legally extradited to the United States because of a
bilateral treaty clause protecting political activists from
extradition.
   Redman said application of the provision to Morales was
``outrageous'' and undercuts the fight against terrorism by legal
means.
   ``It is inconceivable that an important friend such as Mexico
could find such violent acts to be a legitimate exercise of
political activity,'' he said.
   ``The decision is particularly offensive to us, because in
reversing the finding by the pertentent Mexican court that Morales
should be extradited, the action of the Mexican Foreign Ministry
could only have been taken for political reasons.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1636EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Rights     06-28 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Rights,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Drag Away Protesters After Gorbachev Calls for Free
Expression</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police Tuesday dragged off members of a
disgruntled ethnic group at one demonstration and herded away
political protesters at another, hours after Mikhail S. Gorbachev
called for greater freedom of expression.
   ``They took my husband!'' said a sobbing woman minutes after
police carried away about 200 fellow Crimean Tatars, who demand the
return of their historic homeland.
   The woman, in her 20s, said she came to Moscow from the city of
Krasnodar to demonstrate during the nationwide Communist Party
conference. She was arrested a few minutes later.
   A few blocks away in the Kremlin, Gorbachev had just endorsed
openness.
   ``I would like to dwell particularly on the political freedoms
that enable a person to express his opinion on any matter,'' the
Soviet leader told the conference in a keynote speech. ``The
implementation of these freedoms is a real guarantee that any
problem of public interest will be discussed from every angle.''
   But he also condemned ``attempts to use democratic rights for
undemocratic purposes,'' such as attempts to redraw borders and
establish political parties that would challenge the rule of the
Communists.
   Josef V. Stalin ordered the Crimean Tatars deported in May 1944
from their homes on the Crimean peninsula in the Ukrainian
republic. They were accused of betraying their country while the
Crimea was occupied by Nazi Germany.
   The government dropped the collective war crimes charges in 1967
but the Tatars were not allowed to return permanently to the Crimea.
   The Crimean Tatars, who number 250,000-350,000, are demanding
permission to resettle in their homeland.
   Police had put up steel barricades to prevent the Tatars from
demonstrating on a square on Gorky Street in Moscow's main shopping
district. The group gathered anyway, outside the barricades, during
an evening rush-hour rainstorm and unfurled banners demanding
return to the Crimea.
   Within seconds, plainclothes and uniformed police emerged from
nearby buses, grabbed the Crimean Tatars and dragged them onto the
vehicles. Some appeared to be injured.
   As the demonstrators were herded onto the crowded buses, they
shouted ``Homeland!'' Women screamed and clutched their children.
Then they, too, were taken away.
   A second group of Crimean Tatars arrived, but they also were
grabbed and hustled onto buses.
   Two officers told a reporter the protesters were not being
arrested or taken to a jail, but moved out of the area because they
were ``violating public order.''
   Some of the dozens of bystanders who watched the incident
shouted ``Gestapo!'' and ``Fascist idiots!'' at the police. Others
called the Tatars traitors.
   ``Take them all away!'' shouted one woman as police hunted down
and grabbed one of the demonstrators.
   About 15 minutes later a few blocks away, on Pushkin Square,
police rounded up seven members of the group called the Democratic
Union, witnesses said. Several remaining members of the group
addressed separate crowds of several dozen people to promote its
platform, which calls for a multiparty system.
   Bystanders argued about the merits of socialism and capitalism.
   In his speech, Gorbachev said the civil rights of Soviets need
to be preserved.
   ``The entire law-and-order structure of ours is called upon to
guarantee strict observance of the citizens' rights to the
inviolability of private life and the home, privacy of
correspondence, postal and telegraph messages,'' he said.
   The Soviet legal system must ensure that a person is innocent
until proven guilty and that all people get equal treatment before
the law, Gorbachev said.
   Those rights and the right to speak out on the issues before
Soviet society have been violated since the time of Stalin and must
be restored, he said.
   And in a reference to religious freedom, Gorbachev said, ``All
believers, irrespective of their faith, are equal citizens of the
Soviet Union,'' despite their differences with communism, which is
officially atheistic.
</TEXT>
