<HEAD>Ferret Owner Given Until July 14 To Produce Fuji</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANASSAS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of a ferret authorities want to
test for rabies has been given until July 14 to find the missing
animal or return to jail.
   Jennifer Au, 19, spent much of last week in Prince William
County jail on contempt of court charges after she claimed she did
not know where the ferret was. The teen-ager was given the weekend
to find the animal, but faced another jail term when she returned
to the courthouse Monday without it.
   She was, however, allowed to remain free on a $1,000 personal
recognizance bond as Circuit Judge Percy Thornton Jr. set the
mid-July deadline for the animal's return.
   Miss Au has argued that she does not know where to find the
ferret, which may have bitten a boy on June 3 in a pet shop where
she worked. A.J. Simpson, 5, will receive the last of six
precautionary rabies shots on July 9.
   ``I think she was making a substantially greater effort to find
it when she was in jail or when she had the threat of jail hanging
over her,'' said Wenda Travers, assistant commonwealth's attorney.
   Miss Au showed Thornton logs of the telephone calls she had made
in efforts to find the ferret since Friday, when she was freed
after five days in the Manassas-Prince William Adult Detention
Center on orders to bring the animal to court Monday.
   Miss Au has said the female ferret named Fuji was not the one
that bit the boy at Manassas Mall pet center. Two other ferrets
that were in the cage tested negative for rabies in a process that
requires the decapitation of the animals.
   Miss Au, a Virginia Tech student, took the animal from the pet
store and refused to give it up for testing. She said she left it
to be picked up by an unidentified animal rights activist before
Thornton ordered its surrender.
   The court became involved in the case after Prince William
Health Director Dr. Jared Florance filed a lawsuit to get the third
ferret for testing.
</TEXT>
