<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrawbridgeJump     06-28 0297</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drawbridge Jump,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police: Operator Opened Drawbridge Suddenly, Sends Driver Leaping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POMPANO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A motorist was forced to fly eight
feet across the Intracoastal Waterway to avoid falling through a
drawbridge that unexpectedly opened, police said.
   The 16-year-old bridge operator, William Sills, did not lower
warning gates before raising the bridge Saturday night, police
said. It was the second _ and last _ day on the job for the
operator who had listed his age as 19 on his application, a
supervisor at the company which operates the bridge said Tuesday.
   The gates are supposed to be lowered before the bridge is
opened, except in emergencies.
   ``I can't believe how close we were to getting killed,'' said
Gary Darras, 34, of Pompano Beach, whose car lept across the
yawning bridge and slammed down on the other side.
   Darras, who was returning from the grocery store, said he was
near the middle of the bridge when it began opening. ``There were
no bells and no whistles,'' he said.
   The frame of his 1978 Lincoln Town Car was twisted and the car
lost its oil pan and exhaust system when it crunched into the
grating on the other side, police said.
   Chuck Joyce, a spokesman for the Florida Department of
Transportation, said the department had asked for a report on the
incident from Global Contracts Services, a private company under
contract to operate the bridge.
   Joyce said the contract did not set a minimum age for a
bridgetender.
   ``When we hired them we said `you're responsible for the
bridge,''' Joyce said. ``We don't stipulate who can and can't work
there.''
   No charges have been filed.
   Sills had just completed a one-week training course, said the
supervisor, who spoke on the condition he not be identified.
</TEXT>
