<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EPADepartment 1stLd-Writethru a0685 06-28 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-EPA Department, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Would Elevate EPA To Cabinet Status</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs grafs 12-13 bgng: EPA Administrator ... with one graf to
UPDATE with Thomas quote endorsing bill.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several Republican senators filed a bill
Tuesday to elevate the Environmental Protection Agency to Cabinet
status, saying the legislation was meant as a signal to the next
administration that the environment should get more attention.
   ``We want environmental protection to receive a higher priority
than it has in the past,'' said the author of the bill, Sen. David
Durenberger, R-Minn.
   The bill would not change the duties or offices of the
government's largest regulatory agency, but would upgrade it to the
``Department of Environmental Protection'' headed by a secretary.
   The senators conceded that they had little hope of quick
passage, but said the bill was intended to prod presidential
candidates into dealing with environmental issues.
   ``I very much want George Bush and Michael Dukakis to address
environmental issues in their campaigns. Putting this issue before
them will very much encourage that debate,'' said Sen. John Heinz,
R-Pa., another sponsor.
   Heinz declined to criticize President Reagan's environmental
record, something Dukakis, the likely Democratic presidential
nominee, has done on occasion and many environmental groups do
frequently.
   ``Given where the United States was in 1980 and 1981 and
(Reagan's) experience, I think the president would agree concern
over the environment has sharply increased in the past six or eight
years. That's true for him and it's true for us,'' Heinz said.
   But Durenberger said, ``We want the next president of the United
States directly involved in making environmental policy,''
something Reagan has not generally been involved in.
   The agency needs the clout that Cabinet status can bring, both
against other departments of the government, in international
negotiations, in seeking larger budgets and in pressing its views
on Congress, the senators said.
   Though EPA led the development of the administration's position
to seek large worldwide cuts in emissions of chemicals that destroy
the earth's protective ozone layer and won a treaty last year
calling for a 50 percent reduction by 1998, ``it was more difficult
from the position of an agency than it would have been at the
Cabinet level,'' said Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I.
   In addition to Chafee, Heinz and Durenberger, the other initial
sponsors included Sen. Lowell Weicker, R-Conn. and Sen. Robert
Stafford, R-Vt. All but Stafford are seeking re-election in
November.
   EPA Administrator Lee M. Thomas, in a comment relayed by
spokesman David Cohen, said he had no complaints about his agency's
clout in the current administration but added: ``The role of this
agency has grown significantly and we should sit at the same table
with the rest of the major players. This proposal strikes me as an
excellent idea.''
   EPA has about 14,000 employees and spends $3.1 billion a year,
roughly half of that on the ``Superfund'' toxic waste cleanup
program. It distributes more than $2 billion a year more in grants
for sewage plants.
   The agency administers 13 major laws and through them is the
chief overseer of massive pollution control and abatement spending
by states, cities, businesses and consumers that by some estimates
totals as much as $70 billion per year.
   EPA was formed by President Nixon's executive order in 1970 out
of pieces of the Agriculture, Interior and Health, Education and
Welfare departments and the Atomic Energy Commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1658EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Political 1stLd-Writethru a0645 06-28 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Political, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Proposes Separation of Party, Government Powers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with comments by Politburo member,
tightens; changes byline.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Tuesday proposed a broad
but vague separation of powers between the Communist Party and
government legislatures that would be made stronger but remain
subordinate to the party.
   Gorbachev called for a new, full-time national legislature to be
headed by a president with power to oversee foreign and defense
policy and appoint the head of government.
   But the Communist Party chief said legislative bodies, or
soviets, still would be expected to implement party policies, and
he appeared to limit their independent development by recommending
that the positions of local party head and government leader be
held by the same person.
   ``The party's economic, social and ethnic policy should be
carried out above all via the Soviets of Peoples' Deputies as the
organs of popular government,'' Gorbachev told the opening session
of 5,000 delegates to the first Communist Party conference in 47
years.
   Neither Gorbachev nor Politburo member Alexander N. Yakovlev, a
leading theorist of Gorbachev's reforms who spoke later at a news
conference, made clear whether the party general secretary also
would be president.
   Currently, the head of the party is the most powerful person in
the Soviet Unionl.
   As described by Gorbachev, the new presidency would be more
powerful than that currently held by Andrei A. Gromyko. At times,
the Communist Party leader also has been president but the head of
state is traditionally a ceremonial post.
   ``Specifically, the president could exercise overall guidance in
the drafting of legislation and of major socio-economic programs,
decide on the key issues of foreign policy ..., chair the Defense
Council'' and nominate the premier, Gorbachev said.
   Outlining plans to strengthen the legislatures, Gorbachev
proposed election of a new 2,250-member Congress of Deputies that
would meet annually to review constitutional, economic and social
questions.
   Its members, elected from the same constituencies that now make
up the two house of parliament, plus new representatives of trade
unions, artistic, scientific, party and other special interest
organizations, would serve five-year terms.
   That could give intellectuals, the strongest supporters of
Gorbachev's reforms, a stronger voice in the chamber.
   Yakovlev said not all members of the new chamber need be party
members.
   The Congress of Deputies would choose a permanent legislature of
400-450 members, to be headed by a president chosen in a secret
ballot by the entire Congress of Deputies.
   Selection of the president is ``the prerogative of the peoples'
deputies, and they can elect anyone they choose,'' Yakovlev said.
   The new parliament would be known by the same name as the
current nominal parliament, the Supreme Soviet. However, ``it would
consider and decide all legislative, administrative and monitoring
questions,'' Gorbachev said.
   The Communist Party leader said legislation implementing the new
arrangement could be submitted to the existing parliament as early
as fall and elections held as soon as next spring.
   Yakovlev said it inevitably would lead to a redistribution of
power in the Soviet system.
   ``All legislative authority will be invested in the soviets. The
executive power would go to the government and its executive organs
locally. The party will reserve the right and the function as the
political vanguard,'' he said.
   The new, smaller Supreme Soviet would have the right to review
appointment of government ministers, he said.
   The new president and the members of the new Congress of
Deputies could be recalled after election, Gorbachev said, without
making clear how this might happen.
   Gorbachev recommended that the local party leader also head the
local governing council in order to enhance the council's prestige
and increase accountability. But that apparently contradicted
passages in his speech advocating that the party get out of
day-to-day administration.
   Councils could decide against electing the party leader, but in
most cases the proposal presumably would ensure party control of
the government councils.
   Gorbachev advocated a more open style of debate for the new
permanent legislature and also suggested its decisions need not be
unanimous, as those of the current 1,500-member Supreme Soviet
traditionally have been.
   Apparently mindful of recent ethnic strife in the Soviet Union,
Gorbachev urged the Council of Nationalities to become a watchdog
on ethnic issues, monitoring legislation and policies in the
nation's 15 republics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
