<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1719EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Veep     06-28 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Veep,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Asking Very Detailed Information From VP Prospects</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis' campaign has asked for an
exhaustive amount of information from potential Democratic vice
presidential contenders, including driving records and academic
transcripts in addition to financial material, sources said Tuesday.
   In the case of John Glenn, officials said, Dukakis' close friend
Paul Brountas is delving into the senator's 1984 presidential
campaign, seeking information about a lingering $2.4 million debt
and a staff upheaval that came just before the Iowa caucuses.
   Dukakis sought to dampen speculation about his search for a
running mate during the day, telling reporters, ``there's only one
guy who knows what's going on.''
   He wasn't saying much more about the subject.
   But other officials said Dukakis' campaign has requested
detailed financial and health information on several possible
running mates. In addition to income tax returns, the candidates
have been asked for academic records, driving records, military
records and health records, among other material.
   Presumably, Dukakis' aides have asked for the wealth of
information to minimize the prospects for an embarrassing
disclosure once the choice has been made and announced. Past
campaigns have been damaged by controversy over a running mate,
most recently in 1984, when questions were raised about the
finances of Geraldine Ferraro's husband, John Zacarro.
   Dukakis' reluctance to discuss the search didn't stop the
ceaseless speculation in advance of the governor's trip to
Washington on Wednesday in which he is expected to meet with
several potential running mates, as well as 30 or so other members
of the Senate.
   Dukakis' aides have solicited information from several
prospective candidates, including Jesse Jackson and Glenn, as well
as Sens. Bob Graham of Florida, Sam Nunn of Georgia and Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas and Reps. Thomas Foley of Washington, Richard
Gephardt of Washington and Lee Hamilton of Indiana. The names of
Sen. Dale Bumpers of Arkansas and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee
also have cropped up.
   Members of Congress have urged Dukakis to look beyond Jackson in
picking a running mate, sources have said, and campaign aides say
they doubt the spot will be offered to him. Foley has reportedly
declined to provide the requested information.
   The remainder of the list under consideration is comprised of
moderate to conservative lawmakers from the South or Midwest _
precisely the type of running mate that many members of Congress
have urged Dukakis to pick.
   Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey has taken himself out of the
running, and Dukakis said earlier in the week ``I respect that.''
   But Dukakis declined during the day to rule out Nunn even though
the senator has relayed word that he does not intend to return the
questionnaire sent out by the campaign. Nunn is one of several
senators expected to meet with Dukakis on Wednesday.
   Dukakis also told reporters that Graham remains under
consideration, although other sources have indicated in recent days
that the senator might have fallen slightly out of favor when he
publicly confirmed last week that he had been asked to provide
information about himself.
   Dukakis and his aides have tried to conduct their search in as
much privacy as possible, and aides have been ordered not to talk
to reporters about the subject.
   Thus Bob Farmer, Dukakis' fund-raiser, responded ``no comment''
when asked whether he had been asked about his role in Glenn's
abortive 1984 campaign.
   But sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said other
associates of Glenn had been asked detailed questions about the
1984 presidential campaign and the senator's involvement in a
campaign staff shake-up several weeks before the primary season
began.
   In addition, sources said Dukakis' aides want to know what they
can about the circumstances surrounding the $2.4 million debt
remaining from the campaign.
   The Federal Election Commission last year settled a lawsuit in
which it originally charged that $2 million in bank loans during
the Glenn campaign were illegal because there was no assurance they
would be repaid.
   Under the settlement, the FEC dismissed all claims against the
senator, while the campaign committee agreed to make a $4,000
paymenmt to the federal agency after the loans are repaid.
</TEXT>
