<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Arms Sale,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Planning to Sell Ship Guns to Brazil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon informed Congress on Tuesday it
had approved an arms sale of Phalanx ship-protection guns to Brazil.
   Assuming there are no congressional objections, Brazil will be
offered eight of the weapons for an estimated $63 million. Brazil
wants to install the guns on four frigates and four corvettes, the
Pentagon said.
   The Phalanx, also known as the Close-In Weapon System, is a
computer-controlled gatling gun that fires depleted uranium
ammunition to knock down low-flying missiles or aircraft.
   The Navy would be responsible for overseeing the transaction
with Brazil and General Dynamics Corp. would be the prime
contractor.
