<HEAD>Dukakis Takes Jab At New Hampshire Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis, who has had testy relations
with his Republican counterpart in neighboring New Hampshire, John
Sununu, took a light-hearted jab at Sununu while addressing a
housing conference Tuesday.
   Dukakis, whose opposition to the Seabrook nuclear power plant
just north of the Massachusetts border has prevented the New
Hampshire plant from going on line, told the gathering that if
elected president he would adopt a housing policy that involved the
nation's 50 governors, ``including the guy from New Hampshire.''
   He then joked that the troubled Seabrook plant, which Sununu
fervently supports, could be converted into housing.
   ``I figured we'd hang balconies off it and make it
condominiums,'' the likely Democratic presidential nominee said.
   But even if elected president Dukakis won't get an opportunity
to work with Sununu on national housing policy.
   Sununu, a top figure in the presidential campaign of Vice
President George Bush and one of the Bush campaign's top critics of
Dukakis, has announced he will not seek another term as governor
and will leave office after his current term expires in January.
