<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmStudy     06-28 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Study,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Leader Says Surpluses Vital In Drought</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If there's a good side to the drought it could
be that Americans are being given a quick, hard lesson about the
importance of maintaining adequate food supplies, a national farm
leader said Tuesday.
   DeVon Woodland, president of the National Farmers Organization,
said that the surpluses once referred to as ``an albatross over
agriculture'' are now looked at as being extremely vital.
   ``I think we must always maintain a strategic food reserve in
this country and treat it as such,'' Woodland said. ``I think that
message is probably coming through loud and clear in the last few
months.''
   He added: ``The consumer, I think, is understanding today as
never before how vital this (agricultural) industry is.''
   Woodland and Leland H. Swenson, president of the National
Farmers Union, briefed reporters about a new study of U.S.
agriculture's economic structure by two Oklahoma State University
economists, Daryll E. Ray and James S. Plaxico.
   The study was commissioned by the NFO and the NFU. Although not
making specific recommendations, the study said the 1985 farm law's
basic philosophy of lowering federal price supports and payments to
farmers has not worked as proponents have contended. The law will
expire in 1990.
   It was argued that the 1985 law would result in U.S. recapture
of large shares of the farm export market, thus draining away
surpluses and eventually resulting in higher commodity prices and
improved farm income.
   ``However, our competitors have matched our price reductions and
have reduced their total acreage from zero to inconsequential,''
the economists reported.
   Moreover, they said, there is little future in ``using U.S. farm
policy to bludgeon our competitors into surrendering their export
business as a means of shoring up our export volume.''
   Woodland said foreign countries ``simply are not going to allow
themselves to become dependent on other countries for their
stability in the food supply. And we must take a similar posture
for protecting our industry, agriculture, and treat it as a vital
industry.''
   The two farm leaders, whose organizations in the past have
strongly urged some type of ``supply management'' of farm
production _ as opposed to the so-called market-oriented policies
favored by the Reagan administration _ said the report would be
widely distributed to members of Congress and candidates running
for office this fall.
   Asked which of the two apparent presidential nominees _ Michael
Dukakis and George Bush _ fit the policy ideals sought by NFU and
NFO, the farm leaders declined to be pinned down.
   ``I think we will make that decision through debate and through
discussion, and, hopefully, members will be involved in the
political process,'' Swenson said. ``Our organization, the National
Farmers Union, does not endorse political candidates, and any
reference of that type would be an indication ... and I do not
choose to get into that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
