<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope-Plot     06-28 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Plot,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Austrians Say Two Turks Faked Plot to Kill Pope</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Pope-Cardinals Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Turks seeking notoriety faked a plot
to kill Pope John Paul II on the first day of his visit to Austria,
authorities said Tuesday.
   They said the 68-year-old pontiff was not in danger during his
five-day tour of this Alpine nation, which ended Monday. John Paul
has survived two assassination attempts in his decade as leader of
the world's Roman Catholics.
   Interior Minister Karl Blecha said the escape of 29 terrorist
inmates from a Turkish prison in March put Austria on alert because
of the possibility some might head for this country. He said
Interpol, the international police agency, advised Austrian
officials of the escape.
   Mehmet Ali Agca, now serving life in prison, shot and seriously
wounded the pope in May 1981 in St. Peter's Square in Rome. Agca
belonged to a right-wing Turkish terrorist group called the Gray
Wolves.
   One year after Agca's attempt, a man lunged at the pope with a
knife during a visit to Portugal, but John Paul was not hurt.
   The Austrian incident gained attention after an American
television network reported Monday that a plot to assassinate John
Paul had been discovered and foiled. International news media
carried the report for more than 10 hours before Austria responded
officially.
   Blecha told reporters at midday Tuesday, after a Cabinet
meeting: ``The two men staged the so-called assassination plot as a
means of gaining attention. ``No weapons were found, only a warning
pistol unable to shoot bullets. They were arrested and charged with
faking a criminal act, but were not kept in jail.''
   Austrian television said of the Turks: ``At first they were
prime suspects in a possible plot.''
   Officials said the men, whose names were not released, were
arrested two days before John Paul's arrival and had been freed by
the time the pontiff arrived last Thursday. The men face maximum
punishment of six months in jail or a fine.
   ``They are now free, in Austria,'' Blecha said. ``This
investigation is closed. We investigated, and we determined that
these two men were not members of the Gray Wolves. During the papal
visit, there was no attempted assassination.''
   He said the hoax resulted from the men ``craving attention'' but
offered no further explanation of their motives.
   The interior minister, who oversees many police and security
functions, said the plot was intended ``to grab the attention of
the world news media.''
   Interior Ministry spokesman Karl Newole said Tuesday afternoon:
``It was an attempt to become world-famous. The risk was small
because even the potential maximum penalty for faking such a plot
is small.''
   Authorities said one of the men told police on June 13 that the
other planned to assassinate John Paul outside St. Stephen's
Cathedral, where the pope said Mass. The man showed pictures of a
building under construction, from which he said the shots would be
fired.
   Investigation showed the men to be accomplices in a hoax, the
officials said.
</TEXT>
