<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-ForeignPolicy     06-28 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Foreign Policy,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Charges Errors in Past Soviet Foreign Policy Decisions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev made a rare public criticism
of Soviet foreign policy Tuesday, saying a ``narrow circle'' of
Kremlin leaders once made decisions without weighing the outcome
for the people or consulting with allies.
   Gorbachev made the remarks during a televised Kremlin speech
attended by, among others, President Andrei A. Gromyko, who served
as foreign minister for nearly three decades under Gorbachev's
predecessors. State-run television did not show Gromyko's reaction
to the remarks.
   Gorbachev, opening a nationwide Communist Party conference,
appeared to target the reign of President Leonid I. Brezhnev in his
criticism of past Soviet diplomatic moves, although he offered no
specifics.
   ``One cannot but admit that the command and administrative
methods did not bypass the foreign policy sphere,'' Gorbachev said,
referring to the bureaucracy, one of his favorite targets.
   Under Brezhnev, Soviet-led Warsaw Pact forces entered
Czechoslovakia in 1968 to put down that country's reform-minded
leadership. And the Kremlin sent troops and tanks into Afghanistan
in 1979, only to see them bog down in a protracted war with Moslem
guerrillas.
   ``It happened that even the most important decisions were
adopted by a narrow circle of persons, without a collective and
all-around study and analysis, and sometimes also without a proper
consultation with friends,'' Gorbachev said. ``This resulted in an
inadequate reaction to international events and the policy of other
states and sometimes in mistaken decisions.''
   ``Unfortunately,'' he added, ``the price for the people or the
possible outcome of some variant of action was not always weighed.''
</TEXT>
