<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh-Floods     06-28 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Floods,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>27 Die In Bangladesh Flooding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYLHET, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rains and flash floods in
Bangladesh in the past week have killed at least 27 people and
damaged homes, crops, roads and communications, officials and news
reports said Tuesday.
   Five people died Tuesday in flood-related accidents in this town
92 miles northeast of Dhaka, officials reported.
   Five other deaths were reported in southern Bangladesh. Earlier
in the week, 17 people died nationwide.
   Muzaffar Ali, his wife and five children were among the 500
people evacuated from Noapara, a hilly town east of Sylhet, to a
relief camp after flood waters damaged their house.
   ``I am leaving the camp since water is no more there,'' said
Ali, who is returning home after the floodwaters have receeded.
   But government officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the situation in other parts of the Sylhet district was
worsening because river waters were rushing in from the Indian
state of Assam.
   About 1.3 million people are reported stranded in the district,
they said.
   In neighbouring Sunamganj district, the flooding has trapped
800,000 people on the rooftops of their submerged homes, press
reports said Tuesday.
   Abdur Rahim, a businessman who reached Dhaka on Tuesday from
Sunamganj, said he saw thousands of people waiting on top of houses
to be rescued.
   A Railway Ministry official, who asked not to be identified,
said train services between Dhaka and the port city of Chittagong
have been disrupted since Sunday because of incessant rains. He
said service on the Dhaka-Sylhet rail line was also stopped because
the floods damaged two bridges.
   The government said at least 25 people were killed in floods and
rain last month, but unofficial reports claim at least 50 people
have died.
   Hundreds of rivers run through Bangladesh, an impoverished
nation of 105 million people, and flooding is common between June
and September.
</TEXT>
