<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JusticeAppointments     06-28 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice Appointments,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Names Two to Top Justice Department Posts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III on Tuesday
moved to fill two key slots in the Justice Department, recommending
that Douglas Kmiec be nominated to head the office of legal counsel
and that Thomas Boyd become chief of the office of legislative
affairs.
   Kmiec, currently a deputy in the legal counsel's office, would
replace Charles Cooper, who announced May 27 that he was resigning
effective July 8 to enter private law practice. Cooper said several
days ago he is still in the process of deciding what firm to join.
   Kmiec, 36, will become acting assistant attorney general in
charge of legal counsel's office when Cooper leaves, the Justice
Department said in a statement.
   Boyd, 41, has been the acting assistant attorney general in
charge of the legislative affairs office since the departure in
March of John Bolton, who is now the assistant attorney general for
the civil division. Boyd served as associate counsel to the House
Judiciary Committee from 1976 to 1986.
   Kmiec, currently on leave as a professor of law at the
University of Notre Dame, was a White House Fellow and special
assistant to the secretary of Housing and Urban Development in 1982
and 1983.
   The department has been hit by a series of departures in recent
months. Former Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns and criminal
division chief William Weld resigned March 29 to protest Meese's
continued tenure at the Justice Department in the face of an
ongoing criminal investigation of Meese.
   Burns has been replaced by acting deputy Harold Christensen,
while Weld has been replaced by Ed Dennis. Both men are serving in
an acting capacity pending completion of the Senate confirmation
process.
</TEXT>
