<HEAD>Three Convicted Terrorists Sentenced To Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STUTTGART, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German court Tuesday
sentenced three members of the Red Army Faction terrorist group to
prison in connection with two bombings, officials said.
   A court in Stuttgart found Eva Haule-Frimpong, 33, guilty of the
1984 attempted bombing of a North Atlantic Treaty Organization
training school in the southern state of Bavaria and sentenced her
to 15 years in prison.
   An accomplice, Christian Kluth, 29, was sentenced to 10 years in
prison after being convicted of planting a bomb that exploded
outside the offices of the Dornier aeronautics company in southern
West Germany in 1986.
   Luitgard Horstein, 25, who was arrested with the other two in
August 1986, was sentenced to four years in prison after being
convicted of belonging to the Red Army Faction, West Germany's most
notorious leftist terrorist group.
