<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Thailand-Strike,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Averts Public Service Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of employees called off a
planned strike Tuesday over the privatization of debt-ridden state
industries when the government said it would not take
across-the-board action.
   The employees agreed to reconsider their protest against the
government's plans to privatize 19 state enterprises, including
water supply, mass transit and electricity concerns.
   Union leaders, representing about 400,000 members, demanded that
at least some of the industries not be sold. In addition, they want
the reinstatement of laid-off employees, heavy fines for employers
violating labor laws and a restructuring of the social security
system.
   ``There will be no such across-the-board privatization of the
state enterprises,'' said government spokesman Mechai Viravaidya.
   About 100 policemen stood by as thousands of workers, supported
by labor unions, rallied in front of Government House, the seat of
power.
</TEXT>
