<HEAD>Reports Say Up to 40 Political Prisoners May be Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As many as 40 political prisoners may
be freed this week as part of government efforts to improve
relations with the opposition, news reports said Tuesday.
   The Korean news agency Yonhap and several leading newspapers
said the prisoners were expected to be released Thursday from a
number of prisons around the country.
   The Justice Ministry declined to comment on the reports, but
said an announcement on the matter might be made Wednesday.
   South Korea's two main opposition parties have been demanding
the release of all political prisoners. President Roh Tae-woo's
government, after recent talks, agreed to consider the matter.
   Opposition leaders contend there are more than 1,000 political
prisoners serving sentences or awaiting trial for anti-government
activity. Government officials say most of the prisoners were
sentenced for violent crimes or violating national security laws.
   Hundreds of political prisoners have been released since the
government of former President Chun Doo-hwan bowed to demands for
democratic reforms after nationwide unrest.
   Roh, who won presidential elections in December over divided
opposition candidates, promised to consider further releases as
part of his commitment to introduce full democracy after years of
authoritarian rule.
