<DOCNO> AP880628-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1827EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Nazis     06-28 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Nazis,0775</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nazi-Hunters Stumble On New List of British-Resident Suspects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nazi hunters on Tuesday handed the British
government a list of 13 alleged war criminals who fled to Britain,
saying it was new evidence the country harbored Nazi collaborators
to assist with anti-Soviet intelligence.
   Rabbi Marvin Hier of the Nazi-hunting Simon Wiesenthal Center
submitted the list of White Russians, now aged 63 to 89, to a
two-man legal panel appointed by the government. The list showed
all but three were policemen.
   The Home Office said it will try to trace the men on the list,
which brings to 31 the number of suspects submitted to the panel by
the Los Angeles-based Wiesenthal Center.
   The panel also has received from other sources the names of 84
other suspected Nazi collaborators, of which 18 have been traced to
British addresses.
   Hier said researchers stumbled on the new list last week while
sifting through British government records for traces of members of
Adolf Hitler's notorious SS who escaped to Canada via Britain after
World War II.
   Hier said some of the suspects' addresses in British prisoner of
war camps were first submitted by the Soviet ambassador in November
1947.
   The Soviet sheet of charges showed most of the 13 were accused
of taking part in mass murders and deportations in Nazi-occupied
Soviet territory in 1941 and 1942.
   But the researchers found a December 1947 reply from Ernest
Bevin, the foreign secretary in Britain's first post-war
government, telling the Soviet ambassador that none of the men
could be traced despite an ``exhaustive search.''
   ``This is incredible,'' said Hier, in London to hand over the
evidence.
   ``The Soviet Embassy provided specific details of what each and
every one of these men had done and where they were, down to post
box and street numbers, and the British _ in their own country _
couldn't find them,'' Hier said in an interview.
   Hier gave a photocopy of the list to The Associated Press with
the names blanked out. The center's usual policy is to release
names only to government investigators.
   The Wiesenthal Center, which has long accused Britain of
foot-dragging over fugitive Nazis and their collaborators, also
produced a 1983 letter from Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
government saying Britain has not felt obliged to deport suspected
war criminals since 1950.
   ``Now we know why inquiries made about Nazi war criminals from
the beginning were left hanging,'' said Hier. ``It was the Cold War
and they were interested in (countering) communism. They wanted to
play ball with the Nazi criminals.''
   A Foreign Office spokesman said he could not comment on the
letter, dated Dec. 21, 1983, from a foreign office minister,
Baroness Young, to a rank-and-file lawmaker, Patrick Ground.
   Ground had inquired about a native Estonian whose extradition
the Soviets sought in 1960, saying he perpetrated atrocities
against Jews and anti-German partisans as head of the Nazi-run
secret police in Estonia which now is now part of the Soviet Union.
   Baroness Young acknowledged the Estonian had lived in Britain
since 1947 and that Britain had refused to extradite him. He was
sentenced to death in his absence by a Soviet court in March 1961.
   Baroness Young added that in December 1950, Britain told the
United Nations War Crimes Commission ``we considered we had
discharged our obligations with regard to the surrender of alleged
war criminals. ... We no longer regarded ourselves under an
obligation to deport such persons.''
   A Foreign Office spokesman said he could not comment on the 1947
exchanges.
   ``I think it's a case that whatever Mr. Bevin said at the time
speaks for itself,'' said the spokesman, who in accordance with
British practice declined to be identified.
   The two-member British panel appointed by the British government
in February consists of Sir Thomas Heatherington, a former British
director of prosecutions, and William Chambers, a former Crown
agent (a senior government official) in Scotland.
   The inquiry, expected to last about a year, will recommend
whether Britain should pass laws to allow prosecutions in Britain
for crimes committed in another country.
   The most publicized British case submitted to the panel is that
of Lithuanian-born Antanas Gecas, whom the Wisenthal Center and the
Soviet authorities say was involved in the murders of thousands of
Jews. Gecas, who lives in Edinburgh, denies the allegations but
acknowledges he witnessed killings.
   The Wiesenthal center has identified 400 suspected war criminals
in eight Western countries, including the United States, Canada,
Australia and West Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
