<DOCNO> AP880628-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1815EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NuclearAlert 1stLd-Writethru a0686 06-28 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Alert, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0686,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illinois Incident Prompts Nationwide Alert By NRC</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to eliminate reference to meltdown; SUBS 5th-7th
grafs bgng: Although Commonwealth ... with 5 grafs to UPDATE with
engineer saying that scenario was unlikely, provide transition.
Picks up 8th graf pvs bgng: She said ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An incident at an Illinois nuclear plant that
could have jeopardized safety has prompted a nationwide alert
affecting 37 reactors, the Nuclear Regulatory Commission said
Tuesday.
   In the event March 9 at the LaSalle plant owned by Commonwealth
Edison Co. at Ottawa, Ill., two pumps that circulate water through
a reactor were shut off when the plant was operating at about 85
percent of full power, the NRC said.
   The incident produced an uncontrolled power fluctuation in which
power increased to 118 pecent of the reactor's rated capacity
before the system automatically shut down, the commission said.
   ``Since this kind of event had not occurred previously in a
licensed power reactor in this country, though it had been
calculated that it could occur, the generic safety implications
were not readily apparent,'' the NRC said.
   Although Commonwealth Edison was not at fault and handled the
situation properly, the problem could have been serious, NRC
spokesman Frank Ingram said.
   He originally speculated that, unchecked, the incident could
have resulted in a meltdown. However, an engineer on the commission
staff said the risk was not so great.
   ``We didn't know how much worse the situation could get, and
there was the potential _ not likely, but the potential _ of fuel
damage,'' said Ashok Thadani, the NRC's assistant director of
engineering and systems technology. ``But a whole lot of other
things have to go wrong before you worry about a (radiation)
release.''
   Edison spokeswoman Deborah Vestal dismissed either scenario as
speculation.
   ``Obviously, you want to look at all your possibilities,'' she
said. ``But there's always the possibility that nothing would have
happened. It could have subsided by itself.''
   She said both pumps inadvertently were shut down at the same
time during routine calibration of instruments and the mixture of
cold and hot water in the reactor system when the pumps started
again caused the power fluctuation.
   ``At the instant, we knew what was occurring and we knew what to
do to cease it. That's what was done,'' Ms. Vestal said. ``There
was no damage to the fuel. There was no release of radiation. There
was no suffering at the plant.''
   Ingram called the incident a fluke occurrence that could happen
without warning at any of the 37 U.S. reactors using boiling water
_ some use pressurized water _ to turn their turbines.
   He said the NRC has notified other plants using boiling-water
reactors about the LaSalle incident and asked them to make sure
their operators are briefed so they can recognize the conditions
leading up to uncontrolled power changes and know how to handle
them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
