<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Drought-Crops     06-28 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Crops,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High Temperatures Worsened Crop Picture</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The past week's triple-digit temperatures
blotted up soil moisture and severely stressed crops throughout
most of the eastern half of the nation, the government's Joint
Agricultural Weather Facility said Tuesday.
   ``Corn, cotton, soybeans, sorghum and spring wheat conditions
continued declining'' during the week of June 20-26, the facility
said. ``The lack of moisture may prevent some recently planted
soybeans and sorghum from emerging.''
   Pastures were rated poor to very poor, the report said. Farmers
culled herds as pasture and hay supplies declined.
   Meanwhile, the National Farmers Union and Feed the Children
scheduled a news conference for Wednesday to announce plans for
distributing hay to stricken livestock farmers, beginning next week
in South Dakota. The initial shipment, involving 15 rail cars, will
include hay from Texas, Oklahoma and Mississippi, she said.
   The Agriculture Department said federal and state officials have
agreed to establish a national hay information network, or HayNet,
to help locate available hay and identify drought-stricken areas
that need forage badly.
   A number of state hay hotlines are already in operation, said
LaVerne Ausman, deputy undersecretary for small community and rural
development. The USDA and the National Association of State
Departments of Agriculture will broaden these efforts.
   ``Each week, participating states will tell USDA how much hay
they have on hand and can spare, or how much they need,'' Ausman
said. ``This information will be put into a national data bank,
available to each state by electronic mail.''
   Ausman said individual farmers who have a supply of hay or who
need hay should contact their state department of agriculture.
   States with hotlines to date and the numbers were reported by
USDA as:
   Illinois, 1-800-541-9561.
   Iowa, 1-800-383-5079.
   Kansas, 1-800-228-5724.
   Kentucky, for in-state dialing only, 502-564-4696.
   Minnesota, 1-800-652-9747.
   Missouri, 1-800-877-4HAY.
   Ohio, 1-800-686-7246.
   South Carolina, for in-state dialing only, 803-734-2210.
   South Dakota, 1-800-228-5254.
   Wisconsin, 1-800-362-3020.
   Ausman said Indiana has targeted July 1 to start its hotline.
States with numbers to contact about hay include: Tennessee,
615-360-0117; Georgia, 404-656-3689; North Dakota, 701-224-2231;
Arkansas, 501-682-1038; and Nebraska, 402-471-4876.
</TEXT>
