<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Turkey     06-28 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Turkey,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Turkish President Seeks Military Aid, Complains of Armenian
Resolutions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turkish President Kenan Evren said Tuesday his
country needs more military aid and he complained that proposed
congressional resolutions on the killing of Armenians in Turkey
``distort history and encourage terrorism.''
   ``The risks shouldered by Turkey are much beyond her fair
share,'' Evren said in a National Press Club address, adding that
American awareness of Turkey ``falls short of what would reasonably
be expected regarding an ally of 40 years.''
   ``Situated in one of the most critical regions of the world,
Turkey shares the longest border with the Soviet Union, guards the
strategic Turkish straits and maintains the largest NATO army after
the U.S.,'' he said.
   Even though Turkey has the lowest income of the NATO countries,
its defense spending puts it among the top four nations in the
16-member alliance, Evren said.
   He also appealed for the removal of U.S. trade barriers to
Turkish exports of textiles, apparel and steel.
   Evren said he preferred ``less aid, more trade'' as a way of
enabling Turkey to obtain more income to pay for its military
modernization.
   He spoke in Turkish; his speech and answers to subsequent
questions were translated simultaneously by an interpreter.
   Evren's references were as specific as he has been in public
during his state visit about Turkish complaints over cutbacks in
U.S. aid. He didn't broach the subject during formal speeches at
the White House on Monday, when he met with President Reagan.
   In exchange for the use of Turkish bases, U.S. officials have
pledged to the Turkish goverment to make their ``best effort'' to
persuade Congress to provide sufficient aid to help the Turkish
military to modernize its forces.
   But Congress, at the urging of the Greek-American lobby, has
consistently trimmed the request to keep it in line with aid to
rival ally Greece.
   In recent years the administration sought about $800 million
annually in military aid, but Congress reduced that to about $600
million.
   This year Turkey said it needed $1.2 billion in U.S. military
aid, but because of budget constraints the Reagan administration
sought only $570 million, and Congress cut that to $520 million.
   Evren canceled plans for a state visit to the United States last
year in large part because of Turkish anger over the aid cuts. He
also was displeased by a proposed congressional resolution
condemning the alleged massacre of up to 2.5 million Armenians in
Turkish territory during World War II.
   ``The Turkish people are most sensitive to efforts to promote
passage by your Congress of resolutions that distort history and
encourage terrorism,'' Evren said in a National Press Club address.
   The resolutions, he said, encouraged Armenian terrorists, who
have killed 40 Turkish diplomats and injured about 400 people. He
added that Armenians, however, have rejected terrorism in ``the
past couple of years.''
   Evren disputed Armenian charges of genocide and said Armenians,
incited by the Russian army, had first massacred Turkish people.
</TEXT>
