<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildfires Rdp,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Montana Wildfire Nearly Contained; Calif. Blaze Destroys 4 Homes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A fast-moving range fire destroyed four homes in California on
Tuesday, while firefighters on the Montana-South Dakota border
worked to contain a timber and grass fire that has consumed 58,300
acres.
   About 1,000 firefighters made headway against the fire Ekalaka,
Mont., which was considered 95 percent contained, fire information
officer Judy Schutza said.
   ``They're looking really good right now,'' Ms. Schutza said.
``We're looking for containment tonight.''
   By late Monday night, firefighters were mopping up and checking
for hot spots on the perimeter of the blaze, which burned a large
section of the Custer National Forest.
   Winds that had been fanning the blaze dropped Monday and changed
direction, she said. Thundershowers Monday night helped.
   ``The fire lines held,'' she said. ``The rain didn't amount to a
whole lot, but it made us feel better.''
   No new fires were reported Tuesday from the lightning, she said,
but equipment was on standby.
   Temperatures were expected to be in the mid-90s Tuesday, down
from highs in the high 90s to above 100 in recent days. Winds
slowed to 15-25 mph from as high as 45 mph.
   In Northern California, a fire started about 4 a.m., burning 100
acres one mile outside Cloverdale and about 70 miles north of San
Francisco.
   The blaze, whipped by winds up to 20 mph, was nearly contained
by mid-morning, said Marie Mappus, spokeswoman for the forestry
department.
   One firefighter sustained minor injuries but no one was was
hurt, she said.
