<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 2111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SelectiveService     06-28 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Selective Service,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Director Calls Registration Program a Success</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Selective Service System entered its
ninth year of peacetime registration of draft-eligible young men
Tuesday with a roll call of 13.7 million and a compliance rate of
97 percent, its director said.
   Samuel K. Lessey, attending a training conference Tuesday in
Orlando, said the federal agency was proud of its success in the
eight years since Congress re-instituted registration for ``every
male citizen ... between the ages of 18 and 26.''
   Peacetime registration ``ensures that untrained manpower can be
delivered to the armed forces quickly in a time of national
emergency,'' Lessey told a news conference. It also ensures ``a
fair and equitable system to establish a priority of call,'' he
said.
   Lessey said Florida and 15 other states were helping the
compliance rate by passing legislation denying student financial
aid to those who do not sign up. The 1988 Florida Legislature also
passed a bill requiring registration for anyone seeking state
employment, or promotion if already employed.
   Procrastination, lack of information and ignorance are the main
reasons for failing to register, Lessey said, adding, ``We don't
notice any particular opposition to registration.''
   Youths failing to register within 30 days of their 18th birthday
face a felony charge punishable by five years in prison and a fine
of $250,000.
   ``Our biggest task is to assure that the 5,000 men who turn 18
every day are aware of the registration requirement,'' Lessey said.
</TEXT>
