<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Reunion,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Man's Arrival Ends 10-Year Emigration Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida neurologist was reunited with her
Soviet Lithuanian husband Tuesday when he arrived in the United
States following a 10-year fight to emigrate from the Soviet Union.
   ``Today is the happiest day of my life,'' Dr. Galina Vileshina
of Boca Raton, Fla., declared after her husband, Pyatras Pakenas,
arrived at Washington Dulles International Airport.
   Pakenas had been among a group of Soviet refuseniks with whom
President Reagan met on May 30 during his summit visit to Moscow.
   Ms. Vileshina's efforts on behalf of her husband included
meetings with Reagan and Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   She also enlisted the aid of members of Congress, human rights
activists, journalists and other ``divided couples.''
   Pakenas, 55, also was greeted at the airport by his daughter,
Laura Abovich, and 8-year-old grandson Eric, as well as Rep. E.
Clay Shaw, Jr., R-Fla.
   Ms. Vileshina expressed her thanks to Reagan, Shultz and other
officials and supporters who had helped her. ``Because of you all I
have my husband today,'' she said.
   Pakenas told reporters that ``all of the good things that are
happening in the Soviet Union are only happening because of the
meetings at the highest level between our governments. ... I want
to thank all of the American people who were very good and kind to
my wife and my family while I was back in the Soviet Union.''
   ``This is the climax of a beautiful, beautiful love story,''
Shaw said.
   Ms. Vileshina, 52, her daughter and son, Alex, were able to
leave the Soviet Union in 1980. Since then she had only been able
to see her husband during a 10-day visit to the Soviet Union last
year.
   Altogether Pakenas filed 18 emigration requests until he was
able to obtain an exit visa last month.
   Pakenas, who arrived on a from West Germany, had left the Soviet
Union late last week.
</TEXT>
