<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua     06-28 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista High Command Meets As Truce Runs Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, NICARAGUA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The high command is meeting with
hundreds of officers to analyze the military situation in Nicaragua
as a truce with U.S.-backed rebels runs out, the Defense Department
said Tuesday.
   The government-declared truce ends Thursday night, a day after
U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz is scheduled to arrive in
the region for a round of consultations with four Central American
presidents.
   The department called the meetings between Defense Minister
Humberto Ortega and his commanders ``extremely important.'' It said
such meetings are held only in extraordinary circumstances.
   It gave no details. Ortega is the brother of President Daniel
Ortega.
   The rebels, known as Contras, rejected the leftist Sandinista
government's offer for more peace talks, but offered to extend the
truce indefinitely.
   The government who said this week that 3,000 Contra fighters had
started filtering across the border from Honduras, has not said if
it will prolong the fragile truce.
   Both sides have accused the other of violating the agreement.
   Nicaragua has been at relative peace since March 23, when the
Contras and Sandinistas agreed to the first in a series of
cease-fires and peace talks.
   The talks fell apart on June 9 with the two sides unable to
agree on rebel disarmament and Sandinista democratic reforms.
   Since then, the Sandinistas proposed a formal round of talks in
Managua on a lasting peace or informal discussions on the
cease-fire in Miami. The Contras rejected both offers.
   The high-level military meetings came as President Ortega was on
his first official visit to Cuba.
   The Sandinista newspaper Barricada said Ortega's visit will
``deepen Latin America unity against the traditionally aggressive
policies of the United States.''
   In a clandestine broadcast monitored in Managua Tuesday, the
Contras' Radio Liberacion accused Ortega and Cuban President Fidel
Castro of holding ``secret talks about crushing'' Sandinista
opponents.
   The Nicaraguan opposition newspaper La Prensa called Ortega's
visit to Havana ``inopportune'' and said it might encourage the
United States to resume military aid to the Contras.
   Cuba gave Ortega its highest award Monday night, the Order of
Jose Marti.
   In his acceptance speech, Ortega said the Sandinistas ``will
never sacrifice our revolutionary democratic process, even if (the
United States) orders new terrorist actions against Nicaragua.''
   He said that while the Sandinistas intend to continue ``fighting
and confronting Yankee aggression energetically,'' they still want
to find a ``negotiated end to the conflict imposed on us by the
United States.''
   The United States has been funding the Contras since 1981, two
years after the Sandinistas took power. The war has killed more
than 26,000 people and has wrecked the Nicaraguan economy.
   Shultz is leaving Wednesday afternoon for Guatemala City. He
ends his Central American visit Friday, after consulting with
officials from Guatemala, Costa Rica, Honduras and El Salvador.
</TEXT>
