<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ArmsControl 1stLd-Writethru a0723 06-28 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arms Control, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0723,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Arms Control Aides Fail to Agree on Soviet Radar Facility</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 2 grafs new, picking up at pvs 2nd graf, ``The
administration;'' inserts 4 grafs of detail after 5th graf,
``Soviet leaders;'' edits references to Nitze and Rowny below</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's top arms control advisers
debated but failed to reach agreement Tuesday on how to respond to
a Soviet radar installation they say violates the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty, sources said.
   ``We don't know what approach we want to take,'' said one
administration official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The administration has been complaining since 1983 that the
radar violates ABM treaty provisions that such devices be located
near the Soviet border and aim outward _ conditions designed to
prevent deployment of a nationwide ballistic missile defense.
   At the recent summit in Moscow, U.S. officials said that until
the issue was resolved they would not sign a proposed Strategic
Arms Reduction Treaty to slash long-range nuclear arsenals by up to
50 percent.
   Soviet leaders repeated their claim that the radar was intended
to track objects in space. But last October, in apparent response
to U.S. complaints, they suspended construction of the incomplete
radar facility at Krasnoyarsk.
   Before the meeting on Tuesday, State Department officials,
including arms control negotiator Paul Nitze, advocated a formula
designed to leave the Soviets a graceful exit from the impasse: the
Russians would complete no further work on the radar and the
Americans would determine that it was not a ``significant
violation'' of the treaty, according to administration sources.
   Defense Department officials and some hardliners in the State
Department, including arms control adviser Edward Rowny, want
Reagan to declare the radar a ``material breach'' of the pact, and
to announce a tough response.
   Neither position prevailed at the session Tuesday, and the issue
will be considered at a future meeting or decided by the president,
sources said.
   A White House spokesman, Roman Popadiuk, said details of the
meeting would not be made public.
   Sometime before Oct. 2, the joint U.S.-Soviet Standing
Consultative Commission created under the ABM treaty, is due to
meet to review the pact, said William F. Burns, head of the U.S.
Arms Control and Disarmament Agency.
   ``I believe the review process will deal primarily with the
issues as we see them, under the ABM treaty, and the primary issues
are those issues of Soviet violation, primarily the Krasnoyarsk
radar,'' Burns told an American Bar Association conference on arms
control verification issues.
   Other administration sources, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Burns met Tuesday with other arms control aides,
including presidential assistants Nitze, Rowny and Max Kampelman,
and Assistant Defense Secretary Ronald Lehman.
   Burns declined to discuss the issue in detail, saying, ``I
really can't say anything more about that right now.''
   Some administration officials want the U.S. government to
declare that the Soviets have violated the ABM pact and on that
basis conduct more extensive tests of sensors designed as part of
the Strategic Defense Initiative, or Star Wars, sources said.
   Administration critics have argued that such tests would violate
the ABM pact, and Reagan so far has refrained from implementing a
so-called ``broad interpretation'' of the treaty, which would allow
more extensive testing.
   The Soviets have said they will not sign a strategic arms
reduction treaty unless the United States agrees to abide by the
ABM pact for another 10 years.
   For the past two years, Congress has barred the executive branch
from spending any money on SDI tests that would violate the
traditional, or narrow, interpretation of the ABM pact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
