<DOCNO> AP880628-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1913EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-IndependentFAA     06-28 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Independent FAA,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Approves Bill For Independent FAA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Commerce Committee approved a bill
Tuesday making the Federal Aviation Administration an independent
agency, a change designed to make the government more responsive to
aviation industry problems.
   The measure, sponsored by Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., chairman of
the Senate aviation subcommittee, was sent to the full chamber by a
14-4 vote.
   Its chances of passage by the Senate appear strong because Ford
gathered 57 co-sponsors. But prospects of passage in the House seem
weaker because some leading members, including Rep. Norman Mineta,
D-Calif., chairman of the House aviation subcommittee, have
questioned the bill's premise.
   The legislation would pull the FAA out of the Department of
Transportation, where it has been since the department was created
in 1966. Ford has argued that the Transportation Department,
heeding the Reagan administration's efforts to cut federal
spending, has restrained the FAA from aggressively embarking on
various programs.
   In a prepared statement after the bill was approved, Ford said
the legislation ``would end a situation in which the FAA is being
strangled, in the name of politics, by the secretary of
transportation and the ever-meddling departmental staff.''
   Opponents have said the measure actually would weaken the FAA by
removing the Cabinet-level clout it now has as a part of the
Transportation Department.
   In addition, they have said an independent FAA would be too
sympathetic to aviation industry groups _ such as airlines and
small plane owners _ which would no longer have to contend with
Transportation Department officials. Industry officials have long
called for an independent FAA.
   The legislation would give the chief of the FAA a seven-year
term. The administrator currently serves at the pleasure of the
president.
   It would allow the FAA to increase by 10 percent or more the
salaries of its air traffic controllers and other employees who
work in sections of the country with high costs of living. The
agency has complained that it has difficulty finding workers
willing to transfer to those parts of the country.
   In addition, it would allow the agency to streamline its
procedures for purchasing equipment. FAA officials have said their
efforts to acquire modern equipment are slowed by federal
procurement rules.
   In a report completed in April, the president's Aviation Safety
Commission recommended that the FAA be removed from the
transportation department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
