<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0833</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Shot in Nablus Clashes; General Strike Observed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 9 grafs to include shooting in refugee camp,
report on military costs of uprising; brings up 15th graf pvs `The
leaflet' on total casualties; PICKS up 5th pvs `In Nablus' with
minor editing below to TRIM.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and
wounded two young Palestinians in the narrow streets of the Nablus
market Tuesday, and a general strike virtually closed Arab east
Jerusalem and the occupied lands.
   Army radio said a third Arab youth was shot during a
stone-throwing protest in the nearby Balata refugee camp, but an
army spokesman could not confirm the report.
   The army kept curfews on parts of eight cities and refugee camps
in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. Underground leaflets
called for a strike and protests on the 21st anniversary of
Israel's annexation of Arab east Jersualem, which Israel captured
in the 1967 Middle East war along with the West Bank and Gaza.
   Soldiers used roadblocks in the West Bank to stop Palestinians
from entering Jerusalem. At one checkpoint on the road from
Bethlehem a large sign said in pink Arabic letters: ``It is
forbidden to go to Jerusalem.''
   Several members of the anti-Arab Kach movement opened fire in
the Arrub refugee camp near Hebron after residents stoned a passing
Israeli bus, the domestic news agency Itim said. It quoted Arab
sources as saying no one was injured. Kach was founded by
American-born Rabbi Meir Kahane.
   Army spokesmen said they had reports of the incident.
   The latest leaflet was the 20th issued since a rebellion against
Israeli occupation began Dec. 8 among the 1.5 million Palestinians
in the occupied territories. At least 211 Palestinians and four
Israelis have been killed.
   Brig. Gen. Dan Shomron, the chief of staff, said the first six
months of the uprising cost the army $200 million, Israel radio
reported without elaborating.
   Officials said in May the violence had cost the Israeli economy
$500 million in lost tourist income, uncollected taxes and military
expenses.
   In Nablus, soldiers shot the two youths in the legs in the
market area of the old city, officials at Al Ittihad hospital said.
   The army said they were shot during protests by stone-throwing
Arabs, but one victim and witnesses to the other shooting denied
the shots were fired during protests.
   Samer Wawi said he was confronted by about a dozen troopers
leaving an alley and and was shot when he turned to go the other
way.
   ``The didn't speak to me. They only fired at me,'' Wawi, 17,
said from his hospital bed.
   A young man who said he saw the shooting of Subhi Munib Saayeh,
12, said the boy was shot when he ignored soldiers who summoned him.
   Doctors said Saayeh was shot in the right leg, just above the
ankle, and the bone was fractured.
   Before the shootings, groups of boys and teen-agers stood around
the market area cradling stones and building fires of debris.
   New graffiti reflected underground leafets' instructions to
protest Israel's annexation of east Jerusalem, declared shortly
after the sector was captured from Jordan 21 years ago.
   ``Palestine without Jerusalem is like a body without a soul,''
said one slogan.
   The PLO-backed underground leadership of the uprising called
Tuesday's strike to affirm Jerusalem's ``Arab identity.''
   Authorities brought in 350 extra policemen to patrol Jerusalem,
raising the total to 1,500, Israel radio said.
   Shops were closed throughout east Jerusalem but there were no
large Arab protests. Ten Palestinian youths were arrested in
stone-throwing attacks the day before.
   Police Minister Chaim Bar Lev, speaking on Israel radio,
attributed the quiet Tuesday to the large police presence and
efforts to explain to people that Palestinian protests ``in the end
hurt the Arab residents.''
   Members of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's right-wing Herut
Party held a counter-demonstration with the theme ``Jerusalem is
ours.'' About 20 cars drove through the city, Israeli flags flying
from the windows.
   ``We are going to show the Arabs the only flag allowed in Israel
is the Israeli flag,'' said Reuven Rivlen, head of Herut's
Jerusalem branch.
   Police stopped the convoy from entering the Arab village of
Jabal Mukaber in east Jerusalem, radio reports said.
   Outlawed Palestinian flags were seen flying in several cities in
the West Bank and Gaza, which also were closed down by the strike.
   Youths set tires ablaze at the entrance to Gaza City. In
Bethlehem, soldiers stood guard on the roofs of the municipal
building and the Church of the Nativity.
   Some Arabs who tried to go to their jobs in Israel on Israeli
buses were halted by stone-throwing youths. Three firebombs were
thrown at a bus in Bethlehem and a woman passenger was slightly
injured as she ran from the bus, Israel radio said.
</TEXT>
