<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-ANZUS     06-28 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-ANZUS,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Australian Policymakers Confer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top U.S. and Australian officials met Tuesday
in the annual ministerial session of the U.S.-Southwest Pacific
military alliance that formerly included New Zealand.
   New Zealand was absent for the third straight year as a result
of its ban against visits by nuclear-armed or nuclear-powered
warships and the U.S. refusal to confirm or deny which vessels are
atomic.
   Secretary of State George Shultz and Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci represented the United States at the two-day meeting with
the Australian delegation, led by Foreign Minister Bill Hayden and
Defense Minister Kim Beazley.
   The meetings were held at Blair House, the restored U.S.
presidential guest residence facing the White House across
Pennsylvania Avenue.
   Beazley told reporters after his arrival in Washington he
considers it ``very important to hold open the possibility'' of
bringing New Zealand back nto the alliance. But he said he saw no
development ``in either New Zealand or U.S. policy pointing to
compromise'' of the port visit dispute.
   Australia had criticized U.S. farm supports at previous annual
meetings and was expected to do it again this year. Prime Minister
Bob Hawke, visiting Washington last week, said despite being ``a
first class ally,'' Australia gets second class treatment from the
United States on trade matters.
   Subsidized U.S. wheat exports have reduced the Australian share
of the world wheat market from 20 percent to 12 percent during the
last three years, Hawke said. He warned that any further impact
could ``corrode'' Australian public opinion against America.
</TEXT>
