<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hungary-Romania 1stLd-Writethru a0722 06-28 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Romania, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0722,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Romania Orders Hungarian Consulate Closed in Widening Rift</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania ordered the immediate closure of
a Hungarian consulate on Tuesday and expelled the consular staff,
the Hungarian state news agency MTI reported, in a widening rift
between the two communist neighbors.
   The action was unprecedented in recent Soviet bloc diplomatic
history. Romania and Hungary are military allies in the Soviet-led
Warsaw Pact.
   The decision to close the Hungarian general consulate in
Cluj-Napoca was apparently prompted by a demonstration of about
50,000 Hungarians in Budapest Monday night to protest a project
calling for demolition of 7,000 Romanian villages, including ethnic
Hungarian communities, by the year 2000.
   Cluj-Napoca is a city in Transylvania in northwestern Romania
where most of the 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians live. Hungarians
know it as Kolozsvar.
   Ethnic Hungarians have long complained about alleged
discrimination and denial of ethnic rights. They form the largest
minority group in East Europe outside the Soviet Union.
   MTI said Foreign Minister Ioan Totu called in Hungarian
Ambassador Pal Szucs on Tuesday and told him Romania considers
operation of the consulate as ``terminated with immediate effect.''
   According to MTI, Romania demanded that the staff ``leave the
territory of Romania within 48 hours.''
   Romanian President Nicolae Ceausescu on Tuesday rejected all
criticism of his village demolition program and accused Hungarian
authorities of actively supporting the unofficial protest.
   In a speech to the Romanian Communist Party's Central Committee
in Bucharest, Ceausescu hinted that he may direct the Hungarian
Embassy in Budapest to scale down operations following the protest
rally.
   The resettlement plan calls for 7,000 of Romania's 13,000
villages to be torn down and replaced with agricultural-industrial
centers. Romanian state-run media said the goal is to gain more
farmland for use by the country's collectivized agriculture, which
is plagued by lack of incentives for farmers and livestock fodder
shortages.
   The protesters Monday night filed quietly past the Romanian
Embassy in the biggest unofficial rally in Hungary since the 1956
Hungarian uprising. Police did not interfere.
   The Hungarian government newspaper Magyar Hirlap on Tuesday
praised the marchers' discipline.
   But Ceausescu denounced ``new actions of a chauvinistic,
nationalistic, anti-Romanian, anti-socialist nature'' in Hungary.
   He told the party meeting: ``Yesterday a new manifestation was
organized with the agreement and _ as stated even by news coming
from Hungary _ under the aegis of the official party and state
bodies of Hungary,'' the state news agency Agerpres reported.
   As reported by Agerpres, Ceausescu also sought to depict the
growing chorus of Hungarian protests as means to make people forget
about Hungary's serious economic problems.
   The MTI agency said ``responsibility for violating the consular
agreement'' lies with Romania. It added that ``this severe Romanian
measure'' will not divert Hungary from ``its principled policy
aimed at deepening friendship between the Hungarian and Romanian
peoples, strengthening the connecting role of the nationalities
living in their countries.''
   Both the Hungarian government and speakers at Monday's rally
made it clear that a change of existing borders is out of the
question. Under the 1920 Trianon Treaty, predominantly Hungarian
Transylvania became part of Romania.
   Hungary's premier and Communist Party chief, Karoly Grosz, is
scheduled to visit Romania, probably in late summer.
   Ceausescu said issues between the two parties and countries must
be solved ``exclusively by way of talks, in a spirit of equality,
respect and non-interference in the domestic affairs of either
country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Baker     06-28 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Baker,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan, Baker Exchange Goodbye Letters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan bid farewell Tuesday to chief
of staff Howard H. Baker Jr., thanking him for piloting the White
House staff through the difficult days of the Iran-Contra
investigation.
   ``A tone of cooperation and conciliation in those early months
of 1987 was communicated to the public and to those in Congress,''
Reagan told Baker in a letter released by the White House.
   ``At the same time, the White House functioned efficiently and
effectively in setting out and pursuing my policy goals. I clearly
appreciate the challenges you faced,'' Reagan said.
   Baker, in his letter to Reagan, said he'd been called upon to
``navigate the troubled waters of the Iran-Contra affair. I believe
that task is now behind us, and I think your representations have
been fully supported by the record.''
   He also cited the completion of the U.S.-Soviet treaty banning
intermediate-range nuclear weapons, calling the past 16 months
``among the most energetic and successful of your administration.''
   Baker, whose wife Joy has been in ill health recently, cited
personal reasons when he resigned earlier this month. The former
senator from Tennessee and Senate majority leader assumed the chief
of staff position after the departure of Donald T. Regan in the
wake of the Iran-Contra affair.
   ``No one understands better than Nancy and I the personal
reasons that lead you to relinquish your responsibilities at this
time. That too, is a tribute to your character and your
integrity,'' Reagan wrote.
   ``With all the years you and I have been associated, this truly
is no farewell, but rather a note of enduring and heartfelt thanks
for a job well done.''
   Baker's deputy, Kenneth Duberstein, is succeeding as him chief
of staff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
