<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Justice-DrugTesting     06-28 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Justice-Drug Testing,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Employees File Suit Against Random Drug Testing Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawsuit challenging Attorney General Edwin
Meese III's plan to conduct random drug testing of Justice
Department officials was filed Tuesday by 42 employees, mostly
trial attorneys and several supervisors.
   The lawsuit contends that random drug testing of employees in
sensitive jobs is an unconstitutional invasion of privacy that
violates the Fourth Amendment's ban on unreasonable searches.
   The suit, filed a day after the Justice Department announced
plans to begin random testing in two months, also contends that the
program is being implemented ``without any factual showing of a
problem of drug use in the department.''
   The plan is ``arbitrary, capricious and abuse of discretion''
because it ``would not require any suspicion that a particular
individual has used drugs prior to testing, and would subject
employees to urinalysis tests for drug use even though such tests
do not indicate whether employees are impaired in their job
performance by drug use,'' said the lawsuit filed by former
Maryland attorney general Stephen H. Sachs, who has also served as
a U.S. attorney in the state.
   The 42 plaintiffs named in the suit were mostly Justice
Department trial attorneys plus several supervisors, including
three deputy chiefs of the civil rights division's criminal
section: Barry Kowalski, Daniel L. Bell and Norajean M. Flanagan.
   Arthur Spitzer, an American Civil Liberties Union attorney
involved in the case, said he had spoken to a number of other
Justice Department officials who privately supported the lawsuit
but didn't want to join it for fear of hurting their careers.
   The drug testing plan is part of the Reagan administration's
program for a ``drug-free workplace'' in the federal government.
Random drug testing has been challenged by a number of federal
employee groups.
   Several federal appellate courts have upheld various kinds of
drug testing programs. But these courts have yet to rule
definitively on challenges to widespread random drug testing of
federal workers under the ``drug-free workplace'' program.
   The U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington is scheduled to
hear arguments next fall on challenges to drug testing of
Transportation Department and civilian Army employees.
   The same court ruled last year that the invasion of privacy
entailed by testing could not be justified if the test didn't
produce evidence that employees were impaired by drug use while on
the job.
</TEXT>
