<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChainSawMurder     06-28 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chain Saw Murder,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Professor Guilty In Chain Saw Murder Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Fresno State University professor
was found guilty of first-degree murder Tuesday in the slaying of a
teen-age male prostitute whose body was found cut into pieces that
were scattered as far as 200 miles apart.
   Max Bernard Franc stood calmly beside his attorney, Mark
Kaiserman, as the verdict was read in a silent courtroom. He showed
no immediate reaction to the verdict but leaned forward to listen
closely as the jury's decision was announced.
   Jurors deliberated 2{ days before returning their verdict.
   The victim, Tracy Leroy Nute, was an 18-year-old runaway from
Kansas City, Mo., who came to California to be a movie star and
wound up working as a prostitute.
   Franc, 58, a public administration professor at Fresno until his
arrest in August, was charged with shooting Nute last August, then
dismembering his body and disposing of it between Fresno and
Valencia.
   His arrest came after a chain saw he had rented was returned
with bits of flesh and blood in its inner workings.
   Franc said he didn't commit the murder and blamed a transient
named Terry Adams. ``Adams'' never was found, and the prosecutor
claimed he was ``a phantom'' invented by Franc.
   Forensic experts found traces of blood throughout Franc's West
Hollywood apartment as well as in his car. The murder weapon was
found in Franc's university office. And a motorist identified Franc
as the man he saw sitting in a car near a freeway offramp where
body parts were found.
   During the four-week trial, witnesses described the bespectacled
defendant as ``a sissy.'' His lawyer argued that Franc had neither
the physical strength nor the personality necessary to commit the
killing.
   Testimony about Franc's lifestyle disclosed the double life he
had lived for years. In Fresno,he was a conservative public
administration professor. But in West Hollywood he was a homosexual
voyeur who paid young men to be photographed in sexual poses.
   During their deliberations, jurors played tapes of Franc's
interviews with police after his arrest.
   At first, he claimed he used the chain saw to cut up a dog he
had killed with his car. Later, he claimed the dog belonged to
underworld figures and Adams used the saw to cut up the ``Mafia
dog.'' Ultimately he said Adams shot Nute in his apartment and used
the saw to dismember the body.
   The former professor did not testify at his trial.
</TEXT>
