<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CaptiveWomen     06-28 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Captive Women,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heidnik Jury Hears Closing Arguments In Torture-Murder Case
^Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gary Michael Heidnik committed ``horrible''
acts by chaining women and torturing them, two until they died, but
he is insane, not guilty of first-degree murder, his lawyer said
Tuesday in closing arguments.
   The prosecutor, however, argued Heidnik ``knew what he was doing
and he knew it was wrong.''
   ``This man conducted repeated sadistic acts on six defenseless
persons,'' Assistant District Attorney Charles Gallagher said.
``What he did was premeditated, deliberate murder.''
   Following Tuesday's closing arguments, the jury will be given
instructions Wednesday before beginning deliberations. The jury was
selected in Pittsburgh because of intense publicity about the case
in eastern Pennsylvania.
   Gallagher pressed for a first-degree murder conviction, for
which Heidnik could face a death sentence. The prosecutor also
sought convictions on six counts of kidnapping, five counts of
rape, four of aggravated assault and one of abuse of a corpse.
   Heidnik, 44, was arrested in March 1987, after one captive
escaped from Heidnik's car and alerted police. He is accused of
luring women to his basement torture chamber, where he chained them
and raped them repeatedly in hopes of breeding a ``superior race,''
between November 1986 and his arrest.
   He used a chain saw to cut up the remains of one woman and then
fed the remains mixed with dog food to the other women, according
to police and trial testimony. The body of the second woman was
found in the woods in New Jersey.
   All four survivors testified about their experiences during the
seven-day trial in Common Pleas Court.
   The bearded Heidnik, wearing the black, flowered Hawaiian-style
sport shirt he has worn most days, ignored the lawyers Tuesday.
   ``A person who holds women captive in chains, and kills two of
them, and feeds them dog food and human flesh, is insane,'' argued
Heidnik's lawyer, A. Charles Peruto Jr. ``What was his purpose? To
raise 10 babies from 10 different women in his basement. Does that
make sense?''
   ``Even though we have conceded he committed those horrible acts,
we have not conceded first-degree murder,'' Peruto argued.
   ``The commonwealth says the defendant fooled all the doctors,
that he faked schizophrenia for 25 years. If you don't believe that
you have to say he was insane. Certainly he knew he was hiding the
bodies, certainly he knew what he was doing, but he thought it was
right.''
   Gallagher challenged the reliability of medical experts who said
Heidnik was mentally ill. Two experts testified for the defense,
saying that Heidnik was schizophrenic and had been in and out of
mental institutions over 20 years.
   ``If you rely on the evidence, you will realize that this man is
not legally insane (and that he) is guilty beyond a reasonable
doubt,'' Gallagher said.
   ``He repeatedly raped these `girls' for his own sadistic sexual
pleasure. How was he described when Sandra Lindsay died. He was
obsessed, but not sorry. And when Debbie Dudley was electrocuted he
wasn't unhappy.
   ``Does this show he was psychotic? I say it does not,''
Gallagher said. ``What he did was premeditated, deliberate murder.
Reject the very idea that this man is legally insane.''
   Peruto said the actions Gallagher outlined proved Heidnik was
out of touch with reality:
   ``When he cut up that woman with a hacksaw, what kind of person
is that? And then eating some of the flesh, and wrapping up the
rest and putting it into his freezer. Who was trying to impress
when he did that? Was he faking a mental illness?
   ``This case is about mental capability. Was the defendant able
to plan killings? Did he intend to kill? I say that he didn't. He
is insane and you can't get around it.''
</TEXT>
