<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Bolivia-Cocaine     06-28 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia-Cocaine,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coca Farmers Threaten Violence if U.S. Agents, Troops Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers who grow the raw material for
cocaine demanded Tuesday that 40 U.S. soldiers and drug agents
leave the Chapare coca leaf-growing region, where six farmers were
killed the day before.
   James Danbridge, spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in La Paz, said
there are ``no plans to remove U.S. personnel from the Chapare.''
The 40 Americans operate in the region in conjunction with Bolivian
authorities.
   A spokesman for the Chapare federation of coca growers, who
spoke on condition of anonymity, said farmers will respond with
violence and road blocks if the Americans remain. The coca farmers
oppose U.S.-backed legislation that would declare most coca
plantations in the Chapare illegal.
   Several thousand farmers and workers gathered in Cochabamba, a
city 90 southwest of the Chapare, on Tuesday to protest the six
deaths and the anti-narcotics law Bolivian legislators are
considering.
   On Monday, at least 5,000 coca farmers briefly overran a
Bolivian police and U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency base in Villa
Tunari, a Chapare village, said Jorge Alderrete, undersecretary in
the Interior Ministry.
   Dandridge said five DEA agents on the base at the time were not
hurt.
   Police fired shots and tear gas at the mob to regain control of
the base, killing two farmers, Bolivian authorities reported. A
police spokesman said officers arrested several farmers carrying
dynamite and weapons.
   Four farmers were reported killed and scores injured Monday when
Bolivian anti-drug police attacked a blockade erected on the main
road through the Chapare, a lush tropical region 240 miles east of
La Paz.
   Another confrontation occurred north of the roadblock, at
Ivirgarzama village, when officers dispersed a group of farmers.
Police said at least four farmers were injured, one seriously.
   President Victor Paz Estenssoro's government said Tuesday that
trouble was being fomented by cocaine traffickers opposed to the
anti-narcotics legislation, which would impose stiff penalties on
them in addition to declaring plantations illegal.
   Military and police units were sent into the Chapare on Tuesday
to protect the anti-narcotics police and U.S. military and DEA
camps. Security teams patrolled in helicopters and armored
vehicles, officials said.
   At least 350,000 farmers live in the Chapare, which is about the
size of New Jersey. Coca growing or cocaine processing provides the
livelihood of most.
   Coca farmers have held protest marches in recent weeks against
the legislation. Part of the U.S. aid program is contingent on the
Bolivian Congress passing the law, and it is expected to do so this
week.
   More than 100,000 acres of Bolivian farmland are planted in
coca, which produces 90 metric tons of cocaine when refined _ about
one-third of world production, according to a U.S. Embassy report.
   Authorities have increased interdiction efforts in the Chapare
this year with the aid of U.S. military, DEA and Border Patrol
personnel, and the police say five tons of cocaine paste has been
captured.
   ``Bolivia has made more progress in combating the cocaine trade
than any other South American country,'' U.S. Attorney General
Edwin Meese III said during a recent visit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
