<HEAD>Teamster Leaders Deny Mafia Controls Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Teamsters, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters, hit by a federal racketeering suit Tuesday, denied that
their union was controlled by the Mafia and said the suit was
un-American.
   ``It's pure myth that this organization is in any way influenced
or controlled by organized crime,'' Teamsters lawyer John Climaco
told a news conference at the Ritz Carlton Hotel, where the union
general executive is holding its quarterly meeting.
   ``It's totally un-American and it's wrong.''
   The suit was filed in federal court in New York by U.S. Attorney
Rudolph Giuliani.
   The union's acting president, Weldon Mathis, called it ``a
vicious anti-labor attack'' and ``a shameful attempt to destroy a
democratic union. It will not be tolerated.''
   The leaders declined to outline how they will fight the suit.
``We're not going to litigate this in front of the media,'' Climaco
said.
   ``I'm shocked and surprised that anyone who had reviewed this
case, not in the Soviet Union, not in Poland, but in the United
States of America, would take such action,'' Climaco said.
