<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IndustrialAccident     06-28 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Industrial Accident,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Dead, 20 Injured From Cyanide Fumes in Plant Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers using an acid to clean a 5-foot-tall
tank created a deadly gas that killed four people and injured 20
others at a metal platings plant Tuesday.
   One worker was in critical condition. Fifteen of the injured
were rescuers wearing self-contained breathing units who were
affected by the gas because it can be absorbed through the skin,
said Robert Corkwell, a hazardous materials officer with the
Indiana State Police.
   Workers at Bastian Plating Co. who were cleaning a tank with an
acid solution caused the toxic gas hydrogen cyanide to form,
officials said. It had not been determined how that happened.
   Three to 4 inches of chemical residue and sludge were inside the
tank at the time of the cleaning, said Corkwell. An independent lab
later determined that cyanides, which could have come from the
cleaning solution, were present in the tank, he said.
   ``The one guy who's in ... Fort Wayne, he might be able to tell
us (what happened) when he comes around,'' said police Detective
David Bundy. He referred to Craig Fogel, 19, of Auburn, who was
listed in critical condition at Parkview Hospital in Fort Wayne.
   Bastian Vice President Dennis Fry said he did not know how many
workers were in the plant when the accident occurred. The plant,
which employs about 30 people, makes dyes and chromate dip used to
color electroplated products.
   Corkwell said one of the workers was inside the vat, which was 5
feet high and 5 feet in diameter.
   Killed were plant workers Barron W. Sweet, 21, of Garrett; Larry
D. Hensinger, 29, of Waterloo; William M. Freeze, 29, of Garrett;
and Jeffery Link of Auburn, said Dr. William Hathaway, DeKalb
County coroner. Link's age was not immediately available.
   Of the 20 people injured, five were plant workers, three were
Auburn police officers and 12 were city firefighters. Sixteen were
treated and released.
   In addition to Fogel, two other workers were hospitalized at
Parkview, one in fair condition and one admitted for observation. A
police officer was in satisfactory condition at DeKalb Memorial
Hospital.
   Sharon Cramer said her son, Patrick, one of the workers
hospitalized, had told her he had tried to pull one of his
co-workers out of the fumes but lost consciousness himself.
   She said her son had worked at the plant as a stacker since
January.
   ``The first thing he said to me was, `I won't work there
anymore,' '' Mrs. Cramer told The Fort Wayne News-Sentinel.
</TEXT>
