<DOCNO> AP880628-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1959EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-TelemarketingFraud     06-28 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Telemarketing Fraud,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves Bill To Crack Down on Telemarketing Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday approved a bill designed
to crack down on telemarketing fraud, which is estimated to cost
American consumers at least $1 billion a year.
   By a voice vote, the House passed the measure which directs the
Federal Trade Commission to draft rules governing sales by
telephone and would make it easier to sue telemarketing companies.
   The bill does not specify the content of the rules, but says the
agency should consider including provisions that establish refund
rights for customers and a period during which consumers can
withdraw their order and set a time of day when unsolicited calls
can be made.
   ``No piece of legislation is going to end fraud,'' Rep. Thomas
A. Luken, D-Ohio, said during debate on the bill Monday. ``But I
think this bill will significantly reduce the losses now being
suffered by American consumers.''
   The FTC estimates that telemarketing sales in 1986 amounted to
more than $100 billion. The agency, however, has been able to get
back only about $25 million for defrauded consumers over the past
four years, he said.
   Under the bill, states and private individuals would be able to
sue telemarketing companies in federal court. Currently, suits must
be brought in state courts, making it difficult to prosecute
telemarketers that conduct interstate business, which most
companies do.
   The measure will help legitimate telemarketing companies ``by
removing the bad actors from the scene and restoring the confidence
of the American consumer in the products they buy over the
telephone,'' said Rep. Michael G. Oxley, R-Ohio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
