<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Spy     06-28 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Spy,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canadian Charged With Spying for the Soviets Appears in Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Newfoundland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 25-year-old Canadian charged
with spying for the Soviet Union appeared in provincial court
Tuesday and opted for a trial by judge and jury on three counts of
espionage.
   Stephen Ratkai, wearing plaid pants and a T-shirt, entered the
courtroom in handcuffs under police escort. Spectators and
reporters were searched at the door.
   He was ordered held without bail until a preliminary hearing
Aug. 29.
   Ratkai was arrested June 11 at a St. John's hotel and charged
under the Official Secrets Act with trying to obtain U.S. military
secrets for the Soviets.
   Born in Nova Scotia of a Hungarian father and a Canadian mother,
Ratkai moved to Hungary at an early age to live with his
grandmother. He returned to Canada a few years later and has
traveled to Hungary several times since.
   The Canadian Security Intelligence Service investigation focused
on the U.S. naval base at Argentia, Newfoundland, which monitors
the movement of Soviet submarines in the Atlantic.
   Four days later, Prime Minister Brian Mulroney expelled eight
Soviet diplomats and officials and barred nine others from
returning to Canada because of alleged espionage activities.
   That led to a series of retaliatory expulsions and barrings by
the two sides involving 32 of their representatives. The exchange
finally cooled off Monday, when Foreign Minister Joe Clark met
Soviet Ambassador Alexei Rodionov in Ottawa to begin to rebuild
relations.
   Security sources linked the expulsions to the purported Soviet
attempt to infiltrate Argentia and to parallel operations at
Paramax Electronics in Montreal, a U.S. subsidiary making guidance
and communications systems for a new generation of Canadian
frigates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
