<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Haiti-Children     06-28 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Children,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Haitian Police Detain 45 School-Age Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Haitian police have rounded up at
least 45 school-age children in a wealthy suburb of the capital on
grounds they are beggars who must be taken off the streets, Radio
Haiti-Inter reported Tuesday.
   Between 2,000 and 3,000 homeless children are believed to live
on the streets of Port-au-Prince, sleeping on the sidewalks.
   Capt. Irving Mehu, head of the police barracks in Petionville in
the southern part of the city, acknowledged in the radio report
that 45 youngsters were detained.
   He said they were waifs and beggars and were taken temporarily
to a children's home in Carrefour, a slum in the northern part of
the capital.
   According to the radio report, however, members of a delegation
of children that went to the station said not all of those detained
were street urchins. They said some were students on school
vacations who were detained while playing in the square outside the
police barracks.
   They said the arrests started last Thursday with 28 detentions.
Members of the delegation said most of those detained had been
released to their parents but some still were being held.
   A reporter for the station said the children were believed to
range in age from 7 to 14.
   A witness, speaking on condition of anonymity, said she saw
seven or eight boys aged 12 to 14 sweeping the sidewalks and
driveway of the police barracks Monday and their parents brought
them food.
   Another resident of the area said he saw five children arrested
near the square Sunday.
</TEXT>
