<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Raid     06-28 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Raid,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report of Cuban-Angolan Attack On South African-Guarded Dam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military said Tuesday a
combined force of Cuban and Angolan troops suffered 200 dead in
attacks on a dam South African forces were guarding inside Angola
and that 12 South Africans also were killed.
   The South African Defense Force said the Calueque dam, which
supplies water to the South African-controlled territory of
northern Namibia, was attacked by land and air on Monday and that
South African troops destroyed many tanks and armored personnel.
One South African was killed in ground fighting, it said.
   It said 11 South Africans were killed later Monday in an air
raid which damaged the dam wall, its electricity supply and the
pipelines which carry water to northern Namibia, also known as
South-West Africa.
   South Africa refuses to say how many of its troops are in
Angola. Thousands entered last year and engaged in battles with
Cubans and Angolan government troops. South Africa supports UNITA,
the anti-Marxist National Union for the Total Independence of
Angola, which has been fighting for 13 years for a power-sharing
agreement.
   South Africa, Cuba, Angola and the United States, which also
supports the UNITA guerrillas, finished a third round of peace
talks in Cairo, Egypt last weekend. The talks were aimed at
achieving withdrawal of all foreign troops from Angola and bringing
independence to Namibia, formally known as South-West Africa.
</TEXT>
