<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Carwash 1stLd-Writethru a0726 06-28 0610</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Carwash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0726,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carwash Convention Comes To Nation's Driest City</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 14-16th grafs, bgng `We have...', with 2 grafs to
CORRECT wording of quotation, fix garble. Picks up 17th graf pvs,
`See, rain...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARGARET HABERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What could be better than a rain dance
for the nation's driest city? How about a convention of the
International Carwash Association?
   ``A lot of people have the opinion that `If I wash my car, it's
going to rain.' So we'd love to have everybody go out and wash
their car and have it rain. That'd be wonderful,'' association
President Thomas J. Hoffman said with a laugh Monday.
   Last week, the National Weather Service said Nashville had
received only about 12 inches of rain so far this year, about 13.5
inches below normal. The agency rated the city the nation's driest
based on the difference between normal rainfall and the actual
level.
   ``There's a lot of joking about that with the customers at
home,'' said Jim Russell of Cincinnati, who owns Rainbow Car Wash.
``They'll say they want to be a hero today and get their car washed
so it'll rain.''
   The three-day convention was expected to draw up to 8,500 people
by the time it ends Wednesday. About 175 exhibitors set up aisles
and aisles of carwash equipment, ranging from huge car-scrubbing
brushes to newfangled wax treatments.
   Willard Scott, the jovial weatherman on NBC's ``Today Show,''
won enthusiastic applause during his keynote address when he
recounted a story of once doing commercials for a Washington, D.C.,
carwash.
   ``You never say partly cloudy and I always guaranteed ...
whoever paid the bills for the sponsorship that we'd always give
him a good shot and we'd never forecast rain when I did the
weather,'' Scott said.
   Jokes aside, Scott said he was concerned about the drought.
   ``My heart does go out to the farmers,'' said Scott, who has a
farm of his own in Virginia.
   Hoffman said the carwash industry, which lives and dies by the
weather, recognizes the problems arising from the extended drought
throughout much of the country and has taken measures to conserve
water.
   ``We have that question put to us continuously about the
drought. As far as water consumption, we are very, very visible to
the public,'' he said. ``But we use much, much less water than
someone washing their car at home.''
   Many carwashes filter and reuse water to conserve, Hoffman said.
   ``One of the things that we talk about here is how to conserve
water through high pressure pumps,'' he added. ``We conserve water
with what we call programmers to program the amount of water when
the water goes on the car.
   ``We have solenoids and control valves that put the proper
amount of water and the proper amount of solutions on so that we do
not waste, because this is definitely something we're as concerned
about as everybody else is,'' he said.
   And contrary to the popular belief that carwash owners usually
don't want rain, they really do like rain, said Hoffman, who owns
Hoffman Car Washes with 13 locations in Albany, N.Y.
   ``See, rain dirties cars. So a certain amount of rain is good,''
he said.
   ``But we realize, too, that other people have to live and we're
sure not praying for no rain,'' Hoffman said.
   ``We need rain just like everybody else. We have landscaping
around our places and it's all burning up,'' he said. ``And several
of our car washes are in communities where there's bans on
watering. Our lawns are messed up just the same as everybody
else's.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 2023EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0701 06-28 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0701,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Loyalists Leave Beirut Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Four grafs SUB for grafs 11-14 pvs, The harshly ... south
Lebanon. UPDATING with further PLO deputy quotes. Picks up 15th
graf pvs, Syria, the ... with minor editing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 150 guerrillas loyal to PLO
Chairman Yasser Arafat were evacuated Tuesday from a devastated
refugee camp captured by Syrian-backed rivals in a bloody power
struggle.
   Palestine Liberation Organization leaders accused Damascus of
aiding and encouraging the dissident Fatah-Uprising faction to
crush Arafat's forces in Lebanon.
   They said that endangered a reconcilation effort between Arafat
and Syrian President Hafez Assad to end a 5-year-old feud over who
controls the Palestinian movement.
   The last group of Arafat loyalists emerged from Chatilla refugee
camp before dawn Tuesday, escorted by 30 Libyan soldiers.
   They were put in three trucks bound for Sidon, 25 miles south of
Beirut, but were stopped on the way by a leftist Lebanese militia
that controls the city. The militia later allowed the guerrillas to
be driven in ambulances to the Ein el-Hilweh Palestinian camp on
the city's outskirts.
   A police spokesman said 13 guerrillas were hospitalized.
   The bodies of two Palestinians, a man and his fiancee, also were
carried from Chatilla on stretchers.
   Arafat's mainstream Fatah had battled the Syrian-backed
dissident Fatah-Uprising faction since May 1 for control of
Chatilla and a nearby shantytown, Bourj el-Barajneh. In all, 127
people were killed and 527 wounded.
   Fatah-Uprising guerrillas, led by Col. Saeed Mousa, overran
Chatilla in a fierce 13-hour battle Monday that leveled what was
left of the camp. Most of Arafat's 200 fighters then surrendered to
Syrian and Libyan officers.
   The PLO's executive committee on Monday blamed Assad for the
fighting.
   The London-based Mideast Mirror newsletter on Tuesday quoted
Salah Khalaf, Arafat's deputy, as saying the Beirut fighting
``constitutes a big setback for Syrian-Palestinian relations.'' He
said the Syrians were driving the PLO from Beirut under a plan
drawn up with U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz, the
publication said.
   ``The plan on which Shultz and the Syrians agreed provides for
ridding west Beirut of weapons and fighters,'' the newsletter
quoted Khalaf as saying in a telephone interview from Tunis, where
the PLO has its headquarters.
   Khalaf claimed the plan was aimed at establishing a pro-Syrian
government in Lebanon, it reported.
   He also was quoted as accusing Damascus of seeking to undermine
Arafat and eliminate the PLO as a force under his leadership and of
predicting that inter-Palestinian feuding is likely to erupt in
south Lebanon.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, has thousands of troops
enforcing security in west and south Beirut, but none made any
attempt to stop the fighting for Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh.
   Syrian soldiers on Tuesday confiscated weapons from Arafat
loyalists as they left Chatilla and searched them before allowing
them to board trucks for Sidon.
   The weapons were returned after they crossed the Syrians'
southern checkpoint on the Awali River just north of Sidon. The
Syrian escort returned to Beirut.
   The Popular Liberation Army, the leftist militia that controls
Sidon, refused to allow the five-vehicle Chatilla convoy into the
city.
   They blocked the highway north of Sidon with burning tires. The
PLA's leader, Mustafa Saad, said in a statement he feared if he let
the convoy through, Sidon would be flooded with other Palestinians
fleeing the Beirut fighting.
   Libyan officers met PLA officials to try to get the evacuees
into Sidon, where there are refugee camps. Police said the PLA
later allowed the guerrillas to be driven in ambulances to the Ein
el-Hilweh Palestinian camp.
</TEXT>
