<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-28 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0474</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Rain Covers Parts of Minnesota, Wisconsin
^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms brought welcome rain to widespread
areas of Minnesota and Wisconsin on Tuesday and also scattered rain
in portions of the Plateau region, the Rockies and the Southern
Plains.
   Cooler weather prevailed from the Great Lakes to the Northern
and Middle Atlantic Coast states, but it was hot and humid along
the Central Gulf Coast and temperatures got up to around 100
degrees from South Dakota to eastern Kansas.
   Much of the area from northern Minnesota to northern and central
Wisconsin received at least a few tenths of an inch of rain.
   Park Falls, Wis., received three-quarters of an inch of rain in
the six hours ending at 1 p.m. CDT, while Wausau got 0.65 of an
inch and Duluth, Minn., recorded 0.57 of an inch in the same period.
   Severe thunderstorms east-central Minnesota with one-inch hail
and lightning set three structures on fire, while marble-sized hail
fell in west-central Wisconsin.
   Thunderstorms over the mountains west of Colorado Springs,
Colo., dropped four-tenths of an inch of rain in 15 minutes on
North French Creek late Tuesday morning. Winds gusted to 50 mph and
small hail was reported at Grandbury in north-central Texas.
   A flash flood watch was posted in parts of Texas.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed over northeastern
Florida.
   It was mild in most of the West, but unseasonably cool weather
covered the Pacific Northwest. Snow was forecast in the Cascades of
Washington and Oregon at elevations as low as 4,000 to 6,000 feet.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures around the nation ranged from 49
degrees at Fairchild Air Force Base in Spokane, Wash., to 105
degrees at Gila Bend, Ariz.
   Wednesday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
the southern Plateau to portions of West Virginia, Virginia and
North Carolina. Rain is expected in the Rockies, the Great Plains,
the middle Mississippi Valley and lower Ohio Valley, with showers
and thunderstorms most numerous in eastern Colorado and along the
Missouri Valley from Missouri to Montana.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms also were forecast for
Florida, the central Gulf Coast, the Pacific Northwest and the
North Atlantic coastal states, with showers most numerous in
central Florida and New England.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 80s or 90s in most of the
nation. Highs were expected to be in the 60s and 70s from Minnesota
across the Great Lakes and upper Ohio Valley to the Northern and
Middle Atlantic coastal states, and from western Montana to the
Pacific Northwest and along the Pacific Coast. Highs were forecast
to climb to around 100 degrees in portions of the lower Mississippi
Valley and up to 110 degrees in the central valleys of California
and across the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
