<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Government 1stLd-Writethru a0712 06-28 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Government, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0712,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Names New Cabinet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with details on new Cabinet. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Michel Rocard named a new, expanded Cabinet
on Tuesday with Socialists in all the key posts, similar to the
government that resigned two weeks ago.
   Rocard named four new ministers from centrist opposition
parties, bringing the total number to eight. It was unclear,
however, whether the appointments signaled a larger movement toward
cooperation between Socialists and centrists _something President
Francois Mitterrand, a Socialist, had promised.
   Among the nine other new Cabinet members were a leading cancer
surgeon (Leon Schwarzenberg, deputy health minister); a well-known
historian (Alain Decaux, deputy overseas territories and
departments minister for French-speaking countries), and the leader
of an organization of the handicapped (Michel Gillibert, deputy
health minister for the handicapped).
   As expected, Rocard reappointed Finance Minister Pierre
Beregovoy, Foreign Minister Roland Dumas, Defense Minister
Jean-Pierre Chevenement and Interior Minister Pierre Joxe _ all
leading Socialists.
   Other top Socialist leaders reappointed from the first Cabinet
included Education Minister Lionel Jospin and Culture Minister Jack
Lang.
   The Socialist premier on Wednesday was to make his first major
policy address to the National Assembly since his appointment by
Mitterrand.
   Mitterrand was re-elected to a seven-year term on May 8,
defeating his conservative opponent, former Premier Jacques Chirac.
   Rocard's first Cabinet, named May 12, resigned after the
Socialists failed to win an absolute majority in the 577-seat
assembly in legislative elections on June 12.
   The Socialists won 276 seats, 13 short of a majority, leading to
speculation that Mitterand might try to form a coalition with some
members of the center-right grouping that holds 269 assembly seats.
   The new Cabinet included Labor Minister Jean-Pierre Soisson,
Foreign Trade Minister Jean-Marie Rausch, Family Affairs Minister
Helene Dorlhac and deputy Health Minister Theo Braun, all centrists.
   But statements from opposition leaders indicated the four were
acting on their own. No prominent centrist joined the new
government.
   Pierre Mehaignerie, leader of the Social Democratic Center, said
party member Rausch was ``acting on his own initiative'' and that
his actions ``put him on the margins of the party.''
   Mehaignerie said earlier his party was forming an
semi-autonomous group in the National Assembly that would support
or reject Socialist initiatives as it saw fit. He and other leaders
have been unwilling to participate as junior members in a coalition
with the Socialists.
   The Socialists have said they expect to pass their programs by
using tactical alliances with the centrists and the Communists, who
control 25 seats.
   The new Cabinet was expanded in size from 41 to 48 ministers and
included 24 non-Socialists. The previous Cabinet had 16
non-Socialists.
   There are six women in the new Cabinet, compared to four in the
previous one.
   As part of their overtures to the opposition, Socialist leaders
in the assembly on Tuesday allowed former President Valery Giscard
d'Estaing of the center-right Union for French Democracy to win
re-election as head of the foreign affairs committee, one of the
six standing committee chairmanships.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
