<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Deficit     06-28 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Deficit,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China's Annual Budget Deficit 8 Billion Yuan In 1987</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China had a state budget deficit of 7.959 billion
yuan, or $2.15 billion, in 1987, according to a report made at the
National People's Congress Standing Committee Tuesday.
   That figure was up slightly from the 1986 deficit of 7 billion
yuan, or $1.89 billion.
   Chi Haibin, vice minister of finance, said state revenues were
236.89 billion yuan ($64.02 billion) and expenditures totaled
244.849 billion yuan ($66.17 billion) last year, the official
Xinhua News Agency reported.
   Ye Lin, vice chairman of the National People's Congress
Financial and Economic Committee, told the parliamentary body that
the deficit will remain about the same in 1988.
   He urged greater efforts to restructure the economy, raise
efficiency, adhere to the budget, avoid overspending and strengthen
administration of finance and tax incomes.
   About one-third of China's budget goes to subsidize prices and
finance state-run enterprises. Western economic experts say the
deficit figure would be at least twice that quoted by the Chinese
if China excluded from revenues those funds it receives from
foreign borrowing and treasury bond sales.
</TEXT>
