<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FishingSafety     06-28 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fishing Safety,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves Fishing Vessel Safety Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to fix category code</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation requiring that fishing vessels
carry such safety equipment as life rafts and survival suits was
approved Tuesday by the House, capping a three-year effort by
Northwest lawmakers who called the measure a memorial to those who
have died at sea.
   ``This was an important first-step in making the industry
safer,'' said Robert Barry, whose son died when the fishing vessel
Western Sea sank off the Alaska coast in 1985.
   Barry, who lives in Washington, D.C., said the 70-year-old
Western Sea, which was registered out of Seattle, did not contain
life rafts, survival suits or an emergency locator when it went
down with six crewmen aboard.
   ``The crew of the Western Sea would have had a chance of
surviving if they had had such things as life rafts,'' said Barry.
``Without them, they didn't have a chance.''
   Barry and his wife, Peggy, lobbied hard for passage of the bill,
but added that more needs to be done including mandatory training
of fishing boat crews and mandatory Coast Guard inspections. The
bill now goes to the Senate.
   ``It seems strange to me that men and women have died because
they literally did not know how to open a pressurized life raft,''
said Mrs. Barry.
   The bill specifically requires that fishing boats carry radio
communications equipment including an emergency position-indicating
radio beacon. In addition, boats must carry life rafts or lifeboats
for each crew member and passenger and enough survival suits to
enable them to survive for at least four hours in the water.
   Rep. John Miller, R-Wash., a co-sponsor of the bill, said the
measure should ``assure the families who have lost their loved ones
that we have heard their anguish and listened to their plea that
others be spared.''
   ``The bill will not return loved ones lost at sea,'' Miller said
in a floor statement. ``But it is a lasting and fitting memorial to
the men and women, young and old, who did not return home from
fishing.''
   About 250 U.S. fishing boats sink each year, according to Coast
Guard statistics.
   Rep. Mike Lowry, D-Wash., another bill co-sponsor, said the
death rate for fishermen is seven times the national average and
twice that among miners, the next most hazardous profession.
   ``An alarming number of people have been killed in accidents on
commercial fishing boats,'' said Lowry. ``We can't allow this
dangerous situation to continue.''
   Saying that about 80 fishermen die every year in accidents
involving commercial fishing boats, Lowry added the legislation
will ``go a long way toward preventing these tragic accidents.''
   Stripped from the bill was a provision that would have limited
the liability of boat owners in the case of accidents.
   The insurance provision, strongly opposed by the trial lawyers'
lobby and some consumer groups, had led to the defeat of the bill
on the House floor during the previous session of Congress. Miller
also said lawmakers had to overcome considerable skepticism from
the fishing industry over the need for the measure.
   ``The fishing industry has this macho aura and are very
skeptical of regulations,'' Miller said in an interview. ``They
feel they are masters of the sea.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 2218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Letterman     06-28 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Letterman,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>``Late Night'' Show Resumes Without Writers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Funny man David Letterman left his writers at
home but brought along his humor Tuesday as production of his show
resumed for the first time since a writers strike began four months
ago.
   The host of ``Late Night With David Letterman'' kept his
audience laughing through the hour-long show with repeated
references to the strike by the Writers Guild of America.
   ``We've got nothing but time to kill tonight,'' the chuckling,
gap-toothed comedian said at one point as the show was taped
Tuesday for broadcast early Wednesday morning.
   Last week, scriptwriters voted to continue their strike by a 75
percent to 25 percent margin.
   Normally, the show has 13 writers, including Letterman. The show
resumed with only Letterman, who wrote his own material, said Peter
Spivey, a spokesman for NBC.
   The show's head writer, Steve O'Donnell, had said the other
writers thought it was all right for the show to halt reruns and
resume production.
   And Letterman let his sympathies be known on the show as he
blamed the strike on producers, whom he repeatedly called
``money-grubbing scum'' and ``jerks.''
   ``I certainly have a bright future, don't I?'' he asked his
audience, which responded with laughter.
   Then he filled time talking about his $1,500 ringside seat at
Monday night's heavyweight bout in Atlantic City between Mike Tyson
and Michael Spinks and about his failure to impress friends at the
Indianapolis 500 when he said hello to actor Paul Newman, who all
but ignored him.
   ``And this strike may go on until Christmas, so I'm going to ask
every member of the staff, all of you in the band, if you can come
up with stories. As this unfolds, we'll call on you to help kill a
little time,'' he said.
   On Tuesday, he called on an associate producer in the show's
control room to play his accordion for the audience.
   ``Anything to kill a little time,'' he said as Pete Fatovich
performed ``Lady of Spain.''
   ``That's all we're really trying to accomplish is to eat up
valuable network time,'' Letterman said.
   He acted surprised when members of his staff cued him to stop
for commercials or let him know that the show had to move along.
   ``You're giving me time cues. Our biggest goal tonight is to
kill time,'' he quipped.
   His guests included comedian and Writers Guild member Billy
Crystal, actress Susan Sarandon and an inventor of odds and ends.
And although he announced at the start of the show that musician
Graham Parker would appear, he didn't.
   ``We ran out of time,'' Letterman said to applause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
