06-28 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-Amerasians, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0707,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Meets His Vietnamese-Born Son</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTING summary line, lead graf view father, son meet for
first time and so not reunited. Picks up 5th graf pvs, On June .. .</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BK3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American has been united with an
18-year-old Amerasian son he fathered during the Vietnam War and
whom he had never seen, the father said Tuesday.
   Joseph Crotty said he planned to take his son, Khuc Thua Si, to
the United States, where they would live together.
   ``We have air tickets confirmed for Friday,'' said Crotty, 62,
of Redding, Calif. ``It's quite emotional.''
   Crotty, a retired U.S. Navy officer, and his son arrived Monday
in Bangkok, where Si was to spend a few days doing necessary
paperwork before traveling to the United States.
   On June 20, Crotty and three other parents flew to Ho Chi Minh
City, formerly known as Saigon, hoping to return with their
Amerasian offspring.
   The three others parents are West Anderson of Poulsbo, Wash.;
Verdun Andrus of San Diego, Calif., and Nam Small, the Vietnamese
wife of John Small of Westbrook, Maine.
   Anderson and Mrs. Small returned to the United States Tuesday,
apparently unable to complete necessary formalities to take their
children out of Vietnam.
   Mrs. Small's son, Nguyen Ngoc Linh, 16, lives in Can Tho, south
of Ho Chi Minh City.
   Anderson, 38, took his Vietnamese wife to the United States when
he left Vietnam during the war years, but left behind their
daughter, Nguyen Thi Lang, now 16, in Qui Nhon, north of Ho Chi
Minh City.
   Andrus has extended his stay in Ho Chi Minh City to try to leave
with his 14-year-old son, Vo Thi Tham.
   The Vietnamese government has said that all of the country's
Amerasians should be resettled in the United States and has
organized a departure program for them. It has also allowed smaller
groups of Amerasians to leave on an informal basis.
   Crotty left Vietnam in August 1969, leaving behind his pregnant
housekeeper, Pham Thi Tam. He said Si was very concerned about his
mother, a street sweeper who recently suffered a heart attack.
   `It's going to be more difficult as we get along without the
interpreters,'' Crotty said, noting that his son speaks little
English.
   Immediate plans for Si include an American education, Crotty
added. In Vietnam, Si attended nine years of school and took on
various manual labor jobs in Danang, where he lived.
</TEXT>
