<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0714 06-28 0999</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0714,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says AIDS Victims Deserve Federal Discrimination Protection</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 13th graf pvs, bgng: Bush said, with
Bush comment on poll</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said
Tuesday that AIDS victims should have federal protection from
discrimination on the job, in schools and elsewhere.
   ``I think it is needed,'' Bush said, embracing the key _ and
most controversial _ recommendation of President Reagan's AIDS
commission before Reagan himself had taken a position.
   ``I think it is important to do a lot to lay to rest some of the
fears. There is a lot of misunderstanding,'' Bush said.
   The commission delivered its final report to the White House on
Monday, calling for an executive order or new federal laws to
prevent AIDS discrimination.
   Reagan has not taken a stand on the issue, which has polarized
some communities, particularly as parents grapple with whether to
send their children to classes attended by AIDS victims.
   Bush said Reagan ``did the right thing'' by withholding
judgment. ``How can the White House be asked to take an instant
position?'' he asked.
   When it was pointed out that Bush, himself, was doing just that,
the vice president said Reagan ``just saw this thing yesterday.
He's not running for president. Maybe he wasn't asked the question,
either.''
   Bush, certain to be the Republican presidential nominee, said
``I've got a different role here. I want to say what I think.''
   The vice president endorsed the anti-discrimination proposal on
a trip to San Francisco, a city whose homosexual population has
been ravaged by AIDS.
   Bush spent part of the flight westward reading the AIDS
commission's report and then went to the rear cabin to outline his
views to reporters.
   He said protection from discrimination against carriers of the
AIDS virus should not be seen as a gay rights issue, although
homosexuals are the group hardest hit.
   ``This is a national health problem. We're talking about
children, innocent victims,'' he said.
   Bush said anti-discrimination policy should apply to everyone
carrying the AIDS virus and should not be left to the states
because ``there's some national federal responsibility.''
   The vice president said during his California trip on Tuesday
that he was not worried about a Gallup Poll for the Times Mirror
Corp., released Monday, that shows him running 13 points behind
Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis.
   ``I don't make too much of it,'' Bush said, adding that polls
had shown him trailing before the New Hampshire primary, which he
won handily. ``I look at it as something that can be taken care of.
   ``I like to come back. I think I'm going to win,'' he said.
   The vice president flew to northern California to tour NASA's
Ames Research Center and see its supercomputer, which can perform
250 million calculations a second.
   During a news conference in a cavernous wind tunnel, Bush
acknowledged that ``there will be some that differ with _ argue
with one part or another'' of the commission's report. ``I might be
(opposed). I haven't read the entire report ... There will be
different voices.'' He said he had no idea of penalties for people
guilty of discrimination.
   On a related subject Bush voiced strong opposition to the
distribution of free needles to drug addicts, a step taken in some
instances to curb the spread of AIDS. ``It just offends me, that
concept of encouraging people to take shots of heroin or whatever
kind of shots,'' Bush said.
   On another subject Bush clarified that he was not opposed to
prison furloughs for all drug dealers. ``I'm against particularly
those who kill policemen and are kingpin narcotics types,'' he said.
   After a luncheon at the estate of industrialist David Packard,
Bush was attending a fund-raising dinner in San Francisco.
   Bush said he was moved by what he heard from James D. Watkins, a
retired admiral who is the AIDS commission's chairman, ``about the
need for people in the workplace to be able to come forward,
especially if the commission report endorses testing (for AIDS) and
I think it does.
   ``They're not going to come forward if they think they're going
to be thrown out of their jobs,'' Bush said.
   He repeatedly couched his discussion of AIDS discrimination in
terms of its effect on children.
   ``I would hate if a kid of mine got a blood transfusion, (if) my
grandson had AIDS, and the community discriminated against that
child, innocent child, particularly when the report concludes and
(Surgeon General C. Everett) Koop, I'm sure would agree, that AIDS
is not _ can't be transmitted in ways that some had feared.''
   Asked if an executive order or law would strip parents of
healthy children of their right to protect their young, Bush said,
``I think the parents of an innocent child (with AIDS) have the
right, too, and that is that that child is not the victim of
invidious discrimination.''
   He said he would change his views if it can be shown that AIDS
can be communicated ``in casual ways.''
   He said the AIDS commission's report ``will do a lot to lay to
rest some of the fears about this disease, a lot of
misunderstanding.''
   ``They've concluded there is a danger of discrimination against
little kids that can't go to a school, and the reason they can't go
there is people think that they can communicate the disease, and
the facts show that that doesn't happen,'' the vice president said.
   He said that based on advice from the National Institutes of
Health, the federal government does not need to increase spending
on AIDS research.
   ``We have about the proper level of funding,'' he said. ``It's
close to $1 billion.''
   Before returning to Washington on Wednesday, Bush is to deliver
a foreign policy address before the World Affairs Council. He also
is to stop in Appleton, Wis., on Wednesday afternoon to view
drought damage affecting the nation's farmlands.
</TEXT>
