<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 2237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DroughtRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0725 06-28 1078</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0725,1099</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wells Dry Up, As Do Trout Streams and Blood Donors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `Wisconsin Gov...,' to UPDATE with Thompson
signing fireworks ban. INSERTS 4 grafs after 8th graf pvs,
`Branstad, a...', to add soybean association campaign, tighter
restrictions on Mississippi barge traffic; picks up 9th graf pvs,
`Wisconsin's Department...'. ADDS 2 grafs at end with drought
driving up marijuana prices in Kentucky.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENEVA COLLINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought has drained wells in Nebraska and sizzling
temperatures in Minnesota were blamed for a shortage of blood
donors, but rumors of rain sent corn and soybean futures plummeting
Tuesday in a frenzied session on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The plunge was based on concerns that rain may fall across the
Midwest and bring at least some relief to drought-stricken crops.
   ``That dirty word was being heard on the floor today, r-a-i-n.
Not a lot, just a little bit, but that's all it takes to scare
anybody,'' said Victor Lespinasse, an analyst with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   Corn prices dropped the limit set by the Board of Trade, 15
cents a bushel from Monday, when they closed up the limit. Soybeans
also fell the 45-cents-a-bushel limit.
   Officials in parched communities in the Midwest and Southeast,
the regions hit hardest, fretted over weekend forecasts and debated
canceling Fourth of July fireworks for fear that sparks could start
timber and brush fires. Independence, Mo., opted for a laser light
show instead.
   Wisconsin Gov. Tommy G. Thompson signed an executive order
banning private fireworks displays, open fires and even sparklers.
Under the ban, local governments and the state may make exceptions
where conditions allow. Also exempted will be community fireworks
displays, but only where adequate fire prevention measures are
taken.
   Meanwhile, the federal government froze grain inventories in
three hard-hit counties in North Dakota. And Iowa Gov. Terry
Branstad and Agriculture Secretary Dale Cochran announced a joint
effort to get up to $7 billion in drought relief.
   Branstad, a Republican, and Cochran, a Democrat, said they'll go
to Washington to seek changes in federal legislation allowing
farmers to keep deficiency payments they've already gotten. No date
has been set for the trip, aides said.
   The American Soybean Association began a campaign for federal
help, saying soybean farmers should get whatever relief is approved
for other commodity producers and should have more flexibility in
planting and marketing soybeans.
   First vice president James Lee Adams said in a telephone news
conference from St. Louis that the nation's crop could be as small
as 1.2 billion bushels if there is no significant rain until
August, down from more than 1.9 billion bushels last year.
   The Coast Guard tightened restrictions on barge traffic on the
Lower Mississippi because of the continued grounding of towboats.
Northbound towboats will be limited to 20 barges, only 12 of which
can be loaded, said Cmdr. Michael Donohoe of the Memphis district.
Last week, the Guard imposed a limit of 25 barges per tow, of which
16 could be loaded.
   Limits for southbound towboats remained unchanged at 20 barges,
all of which can be loaded.
   Wisconsin's Department of Natural Resources has refused to let
farmers withdraw water from some highly stressed trout streams
until water levels rise, said Max Johnson, a fish manager at Antigo.
   ``It puts us in a very difficult position,'' he said. ``On the
one hand, the governor is saying give them water. On the other
hand, we can't. It's an impossible position.''
   Johnson estimated that 40 percent to 60 percent of the trout in
streams in his area have died because of the drought. He said the
estimate probably applies to much of Wisconsin.
   Nebraska officials say water supplies are marginal in 30 to 50
towns in the eastern part of the state. The towns of Dawson and
Table Rock began rationing water last week, said Jack Daniel of
Nebraska's Department of Health.
   In normally temperate Minneapolis and St. Paul, two weeks of
temperatures in the mid-90s have kept donors away from Red Cross
centers and bloodmobiles, said Robert Bowman, medical director of
the St. Paul Regional Red Cross Blood Services.
   ``It's clearly the worst I've seen this early,'' Bowman said.
``The part that worries me is that we're already in the shape we
didn't expect to be in until midsummer.''
   In addition to the unusually high number of no-shows, those who
do come in are being rejected for physical reasons that may be
weather-related, such as red blood cell concentrations diluted by
drinking excess fluids, said Bowman.
   The grain inventory freeze in three North Dakota counties was an
effort to ensure there will be feed for livestock farmers, said
Collyn Peterson, a deputy director for the Agricultural
Stabilization and Conservation Service field office in Kansas City,
Mo.
   In Logan County in south-central North Dakota, row crops are 90
percent wiped out, by county agriculture agent Roger Martin's
estimate. He also predicted cattlemen would continue to sell off
livestock as feed grain becomes increasingly scarce.
   ``People are waiting till after the Fourth,'' he said. ``After
the Fourth they're going to admit defeat.''
   Several years of below-average rainfall in North Carolina's
mountains are beginning to take their toll, and older trees could
die by summer's end as they draw off their reserves, forestry
experts said.
   ``The younger trees are the most stressed,'' said Tim Boone, a
Christmas tree grower in Mitchell County. ``We usually can count on
snow in the winter and rain in the spring before we transplant. But
we've had no spring rainfall.''
   Arizona's baking temperatures have caused pollen monitors in the
Pima County Health Department to note that marijuana illegally
grown in the area has matured about three weeks early.
   Marijuana plants shed up to 500 million pollen grains in a
season, and could be the leading type of pollen in the area for
several weeks, said Mark Sneller, director of the office of pollen
and mold. ``It will raise our overall pollen count and when we get
some rain, our Bermuda grass pollen will kick in. We could have a
rough August.''
   Law enforcement officers in Kentucky say the drought appears to
affecting marijuana plants, the state's No. 1 cash crop, and
driving up prices. The plants require a lot of water, officials
said.
   Detective Charles Forshee of the Warren County Sheriff's Office
said deputies paid $1,600 for a pound of marijuana in a recent
undercover operation, double the normal price, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
