<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp     06-28 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saddam Hussein Says Iran On Ropes, Iran Claims Iraqi Attack
Repulsed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran on Tuesday claimed its forces killed
or wounded thousands of Iraqi troops who tried to recapture
strategic peaks in northern Iraq, and both sides reported air
strikes against each other's positions.
   Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, speaking in Baghdad, boasted his
army has 50 divisions totaling nearly 1 million men, and that after
three battlefield defeats the Iranians are on the ropes.
   In Kuwait, Richard Murphy, a U.S. assistant secretary of state,
said Washington will not resume normal relations with Iran until it
agrees to end the Persian Gulf war with Iraq and quits terrorism.
   Murphy, on an eight-nation tour of the gulf, held talks with
Kuwait's crown prince and prime minister, Sheik Saad Abdullah
Al-Sabah.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted a
Revolutionary Guards communique as saying the Iranians mauled three
special forces and commando brigades in heavy fighting in Kurdistan
on Monday.
   IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, said the fighting centered around
the Iranian-held Shakh-Shemiran range near Lake Darbandikhan, Iraqi
territory seized months ago.
   The news agency also claimed the Iranians shot down an Iraqi
fighter-bomber.
   Baghdad denied losing any planes in heavy air activity Monday.
It reported its warplanes and helicopter gunships flew 219 combat
missions Tuesday, most of them apparently in the northern sector of
the 730-mile battlefront.
   IRNA said Iranian fighter-bombers attacked Iraqi positions in
the northern warfront around Sulaimaniyeh and Darbandikhan Tuesday.
   The Iraqis, bolstered by three victories over Iran in nine weeks
in a dramatic turnaround in the nearly 8-year-old war, have been
pressing the Iranians in the north in recent weeks.
   After driving the Iranians out of three of their bridgeheads on
Iraqi soil in the south in Majnoon, Salamcheh and the Faw
Peninsula, the Iraqis have been trying hard to push the Iranians
out of Kurdistan.
   They claim to have retaken in recent fighting several key peaks
that dominate the region.
   In Baghdad, Hussein told a ceremony awarding medals for valor to
air force pilots: ``The day will come when the rulers of Iran will
find no one to fight for them, and that day is not far away.
   ``Iraq hopes that the eighth year of the war will be the last
and that the Iranian rulers will come to their senses,'' the
official Iraqi News Agency, also monitored in Nicosia, quoted
Hussein as saying.
   INA said the president disclosed that in the Iraqis' latest
offensive to recapture the oil-rich Majnoon islands in the Howeizah
marshes north of Basra last Sunday, his forces thrust 19 miles into
western Iran before withdrawing.
   Western military analysts believe Iran is regrouping its forces
after its defeats and plans to strike back.
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, named commander-in-chief
by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini in a military shakeup, has declared
his forces will ``respond at the appropriate time'' for the
setbacks.
   Independent verification of battle claims by the opposing sides
is rarely possible, since neither as a rule allows foreign
correspondents into war zones.
</TEXT>
