<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     06-28 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leader Vows to Defy Government Crackdowns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-apartheid church
leader vowed Tuesday that religious organizations would disobey
government laws and regulations that they consider unjust.
   The Rev. Frank Chikane said the South African Council of
Churches, which he heads, already has defied government orders to
submit copies of church publications for review.
   ``On the basis of the practice and constitution of this
government, we are compelled to regard it as illegitimate and are
thus not obliged to obey its unjust laws,'' Chikane said.
   During a speech at the group's national conference, Chikane
called on Western nations to impose additional economic sanctions
against South Africa. He said sanctions were ``one of the most
effective non-violent ways to force the government to the
negotiating table.''
   It is illegal under emergency regulations to advocate sanctions.
   The church council, which began its five-day conference at St.
Barnabas College on Monday, represents all major Protestant sects
in South Africa except the white branch of the Dutch Reformed
Church, the denomination of most government officials.
   Chikane and other church leaders have vowed to take the lead in
anti-apartheid activities following government crackdowns against
most opposition groups.
   ``The government has confirmed its commitment to violence as the
way of continuing to govern the majority of people against their
will,'' he said. ``Attacks have been particularly directed against
the SACC, some church leaders ... and other ecumenical
organizations.''
   In the recent crackdowns, the government has not placed
restrictions on anti-apartheid church leaders such as Chikane and
Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu. But President P.W. Botha has
harshly criticized the men and warned them to refrain from
political activities.
   Chikane said the government has shown little interest in
improving the standard of living among blacks and that the council
of churches and its members have been providing services he
believed should be government responsibilities.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   In other developments Tuesday, police said they arrested 66
blacks from two opposing groups that were fighting in a township
outside the southeastern city of Pietermaritzburg. Police did not
identify the two factions or the nature of the conflict, saying
only that three men were injured.
   But local residents said the battle, which lasted from Saturday
until Monday, involved the United Democratic Front, the nation's
largest anti-apartheid coalition, and Inkatha, a political
organization. More than 500 blacks have been killed in fighting
between the two groups in the past 18 months.
</TEXT>
