<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites SUB a0748 06-28 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites, SUB, a0748,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS first item datelined San Francisco in AM-Brites to
CORRECT that it was driver's 3rd day on job sted first and that
route was from Fresno to San Francisco sted Stockton-San Francisco;
ADD driver and company saying she became lost only once. No pickup.
Lita is cq in lead.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rookie Greyhound bus driver Lita Martin got
lost on a trip from Fresno to San Francisco Monday and at one point
had to ask passengers for directions.
   It was her third day on the job and her first on the 20-stop
route from Fresno. A Greyhound official in Dallas said she only
``graduated from driving school last week.''
   Although one passenger insisted Martin got lost four times, the
bus driver and Greyhound officials said it only happened once.
   Greyhound's slogan, ``Take the bus and leave the driving to
us,'' took on new meaning when Martin asked passengers how to find
the depot in Livermore, a stop along the route, said passenger
Susan Parker, a 24-year-old waitress.
   Later, Parker said, the driver ``got lost finding the bus
station in Hayward, San Leandro and Oakland. Most of the passengers
didn't seem to mind. They enjoyed giving her directions. But I was
ready to scream.''
   In Dallas, Greyhound spokesman George Gravley said Martin became
lost only in Merced, 50 miles northwest of Fresno. He said
passengers gladly gave her directions to the terminal there.
   Martin also spent some time in Modesto clarifying route stops
with an agent there, Gravley said. She arrived in San Francisco 65
minutes late, he said.
   ``Maybe she doesn't have as much confidence as an old-timer, but
we think she's a good driver,'' he said. ``Anybody can make a
mistake their first day on the job.''
