<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 2353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AfghanFighting     06-28 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan Fighting,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Increased Fighting Around Capital, Guerrillas Breach Defenses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting has increased around the
Afghan capital of Kabul, where Soviet airpower last week suffered
its worst single blow of the war, Western diplomatic sources said
Tuesday.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said communist
forces pulled back from Kabul's outermost security ring to
consolidate defenses against Islamic guerrillas who have been
penetrating in small units.
   Sources quoted other diplomats in Kabul as saying nine rockets,
presumably fired by guerrillas, slammed into the city in a
seven-day span ending Monday.
   They said various reports indicate that hundreds of dead or
wounded Afghan and Soviet troops arrived in the city from battles
around the country.
   Kabul radio, monitored in London, said Tuesday that 18 men,
women and children were killed on Monday when their vehicle hit a
land mine planted by ``extremists'' along the Tokham-Jalalabad road
in eastern Afghanistan.
   It said the vehicle was taking the 18 from Jalalabad to villages
in Sorkhdewar region.
   One rebel rocket on Friday may have touched off an explosion
that destroyed an ammunition dump and eight Soviet SU-25
fighter-bombers at Kabul airport, the sources said.
   Western diplomats estimated the aircraft cost about $70 million,
making it the worst single-day air loss since the Soviets
intervened in Afghanistan in December 1979.
   Diplomats said the scale of fighting around Kabul is increasing,
especially to the east and west.
   The Soviets and the Marxist Afghan government are said to be
increasingly nervous over the situation in Wardak province, just
west of the capital, where insurgents claim to have taken the
capital of Maidan Shahr.
   The fall of Wardak province would open the free flow of
guerrillas and their equipment to the Paghman heights overlooking
western Kabul.
   The guerrillas also claimed to have taken Kalat, provincial
capital of southeastern Zabul province, on June 16. But diplomatic
sources said Tuesday that local citizens asked the guerrillas to
leave to spare Kalat from retaliatory bombardments by troops.
   In neighboring Kandahar province, guerrillas have cornered
Afghan and remaining Soviet troops at the airport of the provincial
capital, according to combined sources.
   The guerrillas asked civilians to evacuate the area in
preparation for increased attacks on garrisons there, the sources
said.
   Despite guerrilla advances, diplomats said the Soviet pullout
under terms of a U.N.-sponsored Geneva agreement appears to moving
on or ahead of schedule.
   Soviet officials claim about 25 percent of their 100,000-strong
contingent have crossed the Oxus River into home territory in the
first six weeks of the pullout that began in May. They promised to
remove 50 percent of their troops by Aug. 15.
   Undersecretary-General Diego Cordovez, the mediator of the U.N.
accords, said Tuesday he will review alleged violations of the
10-week-old agreement during official talks in the area.
   The accords are being implemented ``as satisfactorily as one can
expect under the circumstances,'' Cordovez told reporters on the
eve of a trip to Iran, Afghanistan and Pakistan.
   Afghanistan and Pakistan have lodged nearly 100 complaints with
his office, including Afghan charges that Pakistan is continuing to
supply the guerrillas, Cordovez said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
