<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-InfantMortality     06-28 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Infant Mortality,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Population Study Sees High Rate of African Infant Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every other person who dies in Africa is a
child less than five years old, and early in the 21st century
nearly half of all the children who die worldwide will be African,
according to U.N. figures.
   New data from the U.N. Population Division indicate that a
child's chance of surviving to adulthood often depends on where the
child is born.
   About 15 million children died each year from 1980-85, and 98
percent of those deaths were in underdeveloped countries. Most were
in South Asia, but by 2025, most will be in Africa, the study says.
   A child born in a developing country is, on the average, seven
times more likely to die before reaching five than a child in the
industrialized nations.
   In the countries with the worst infant and child mortality
rates, such as Afghanistan, Mali or Sierra Leone, a child is 40
times more likely to die than in a northern European country.
   The U.N. data, published this month in ``Mortality of Children
Under Age 5 _World Estimates and Projections, 1950-2025,'' do
contain signs of hope:
   _The mortality rate under age 5 declined by more than half
worldwide in the last 30 years, from 240 per thousand in 1950-55 to
118 per thousand in 1980-85.
   _East Asia has experienced the most rapid child mortality
decline of any region, about 80 percent since 1950 from 248 per
thousand to 50 per thousand.
   _China reduced child mortality from 266 per thousand to 55 per
thousand in the last 30 years.
   _The Soviet Union lowered child mortality from 102 per thousand
to 31 per thousand in 30 years, a reduction of almost 70 percent.
   _North America lowered its child mortality rates over 30 years
from 34 per thousand to 13 per thousand, a reduction of 61 percent.
   Mortality figures vary widely among underdeveloped regions.
   Africa has the highest death rate, at 182 per thousand in
1980-85, followed by South Asia at 157 per thousand; Latin America
at 88 per thousand; the developing countries of Oceania at 81 per
thousand, and the developing countries of East Asia at 53 per
thousand.
   Fertility and mortality rates are expected to decline in all
regions and the number of deaths are expected to decline everywhere
except in Africa.
   In Africa, the high fertility rate and the fact that a large
part of the population is of child-bearing age are expected to
offset declining mortality rates, causing increasing numbers of
deaths among children.
   By the years 2020 to 2025, nearly half of all infant and child
deaths worldwide are expected to be in Africa, the study concluded.
   The mortality study was conducted by the Population Division of
the U.N. Department of International Economic and Social Affairs,
with the support of the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
