<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 2356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Breastfeeding     06-28 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Breastfeeding,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Revival of Boycott Against Nestle Threatened</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. consumer activists Tuesday accused the
Nestle food conglomerate of breaking promises to stop promoting
infant formula in the Third World and threatened to revive a
seven-year boycott of the company's products that ended in 1984.
   Douglas A. Johnson, chairman for Action for Corporate
Accountability said the group objects to distribution of free
formula through maternity hospitals as a promotional tactic that
``effectively undermines breastfeeding ... (and) creates the
impression that health professionals recommend it.''
   ``Once bottle feeding starts, breastmilk begins to dry up,'' he
added. ``When mother and baby leave the hospital there is a
physical need to buy more formula - both mother and baby are hooked
(addicted).''
   But ``Nestle has refused to abide by these unequivocal
statements to end its supplies program, breaking the promise it
made in 1984,'' Johnson said.
   ACA, based in Minneapolis, Minnesota, is the successor of groups
that organized boycott activities against Nestle, the Swiss-based
global food distributor, from 1977-84 in the United States and nine
other countries.
   The groups halted the boycott after Nestle agreed to comply with
the World Health Organization Code and promised a clarification
covering donation of formula to institutions.
   Johnson estimated that the 10-nation boycott had cost the
multinational company $3 billion.
   ACA also warned a second firm, American Home Products Co.,
against alleged promotion of formula for newborns, on grounds it
undermines the traditional _ and healthier _ practice of
breastfeeding.
   ``AHP and other U.S., Japanese and European formula
manufacturers have hidden in the shadow of Nestle, but are no less
guilty of marketing practices which endanger infant health,''
Janice Mantell, executive director of ACA told a news conference.
   ``We call upon Nestle to produce a plan, detailing how and when
it will stop its practice of pushing free supplies in maternity
wards and hospitals,'' Ms. Mantell said. ``If this plan is not
available by Oct. 4, the fourth anniversary date of the end of the
first boycott, the Nestle boycott will be renewed at that time.''
   She added a warning to American Home Products ``to develop a
detailed and reasonable code implementation plan by the same date''
or it ``will also be the target of a public pressure campaign.''
   Spokespeople for both Nestle and AHP rejected the accusations
and said they were complying with the World Health Organization and
individual national codes.
   Dr. Thad Jackson, Washington spokesman for the Nestle parent
firm in Switzerland, said ``We totally reject either that we're in
violation of the WHO code or of our agreement. We are industry
leaders in supporting the code, which is the standard by which we
market our products in the Third World.''
   The code permits donations or concessionary sales of formula for
distribution to infants needing breast milk substitutes and says it
may not be used for sales promotion. Jackson said Nestle sends free
supplies only to hospitals requesting it in writing and closely
monitors against excessive requests.
   AHP spokeswoman Carol Emerling, reached by telephone at her New
York office, called the accusation against her firm ``not
well-grounded'' since ``we comply with the WHO code in all
countries when full compliance is relevant, or 100 percent with the
codes of countries that have their own.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
