<DOCNO> AP880628-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0722EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Czechoslovakia Adv03-2Takes   06-28 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Czechoslovakia, Adv 03-2 Takes,0856</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Czechoslovakia _ Wary of Reform</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: The main story of a three-story package.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the reforms now emanating from Moscow
were put forth 20 years ago in Czechoslovakia, only to be swept
away by a Soviet-led invasion. Their rebirth with the Kremlin's
imprimatur, however, is met with skepticism in today's
Czechoslovakia. Here's why.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty years after Soviet tanks
crushed Alexander Dubcek's ``Prague Spring'' of reform,
Czechoslovaks are deeply leery of the changes now proclaimed in
Moscow and echoed by their own leaders.
   A key reason is that Dubcek was crushed and disgraced for trying
them, or at least letting them go too far.
   Czechoslovaks today wonder if the same will happen to Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and his Soviet reforms _ perestroika (restructuring) and
glasnost (openness) _ leaving them worse off than they are now.
   They are aware that old-time, conservative Communists are still
around and a fear of their traditional hard line remains.
   The skepticism of reform surfaces in countless jokes:
   _What is the difference between Mikhail Gorbachev and Alexander
Dubcek? None, but Gorbachev doesn't know it yet.
   _What is the difference between perestroika and chess? In chess,
you think before you move.
   _``Think in a new way?'' a cartoon character asks his boss,
echoing a new Communist slogan. ``But for years you've been telling
me not to think at all.''
   In the years after the Prague Spring, Czechs and Slovaks still
seemed stunned by the Soviet-led invasion on the night of Aug.
20-21, 1968, that erased Dubcek's movement to bring a new face to
Czechoslovak communism _ multiparty politics, freedom of the press,
speech and religion, a liberalized economy.
   When it was over Dubcek was expelled from the Communist Party
and went off to his native Slovakia to work as a clerk in a
forestry office.
   At the same time, the chanting, singing, joyous people of the
Prague Spring vanished from the streets and squares. Most retreated
morosely back to their private lives to pursue a material wealth
that was the party's reward for their political silence.
   In 1988, that post-invasion reward is running low.
   Czechoslovakia's outmoded industry is performing poorly, forcing
planners to scale down production targets and to slash coveted wage
bonuses.
   Shortages are again apparent in shops.
   On the political front, while Prague's leaders tinker with
reform, the winds of change blowing from Gorbachev's Kremlin are
prompting more citizens to challenge the Communists on issues
ranging from ecology to cultural and religious freedom.
   But the memory of 1968 makes Czechoslovaks wary of placing too
much faith in Gorbachev and in turn their own leaders, as well as
reforms.
   As one Prague man put it, Soviet reforms sound to Czechoslovaks
like ``the right ideas from the wrong side.''
   Even deeper skepticism is reserved for the cautious reforms
adopted so far by the Communist leaders installed by Moscow 20
years ago to make sure Dubcek's experiments would not be repeated.
   After spending 18 years assailing change, Czechoslovakia's
Communists have now fallen in step behind Gorbachev, endorsing
perestroika and adopting the rhetoric of reform. But the sense
among many in Prague is that there is no guarantee of any
meaningful or lasting effect.
   This past December, the party even changed its leader,
substituting a 65-year-old apparatchik, Milos Jakes (pronouned
Ya-kesh), for an increasingly frail Gustav Husak, 75.
   Jakes immediately set about trying to revamp the image of the
party leader, emulating Gorbachev by taking well-publicized trips
to factories and farms to chat with workers.
   Borrowing many phrases from Gorbachev, Jakes spoke of the need
for economic and social reform at a key party meeting in April that
brought some new, younger faces into the party elite.
   But Jakes lacks Gorbachev's touch. At February's snow-dampened
celebrations of the 40th anniversary of Communist power, crowds
streamed away from the square when Jakes got up to speak.
   Few Czechoslovaks can forget that it was Jakes who oversaw the
expulsion of almost 500,000 party members in a post-Dubcek purge.
   They also know that Husak, who took over from Dubcek in March
1969, is still on the ruling Politburo.
   When Jakes talks of reform, however, he pointedly omits mention
of glasnost, which has brought startling frankness to the Soviet
media. Jakes stresses that Czechoslovakia's 1.7 million Communists
must dictate the pace and shape of any change.
   An unspoken fear is that reform will spin outside the party's
control, as the Communists say it did in Dubcek's days.
   Even economic change is treated with extreme caution,
particularly by managers who report that overhasty reforms in the
Soviet Union are making it difficult for them to deal with Soviet
enterprises.
   Planned decentralization of management is not likely to go as
far here as it has in the Soviet Union and won't be in full force
until 1991.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0723EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Czechoslovakia Adv03-1stadd   06-28 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Czechoslovakia, Adv 03-1st add,0784</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>PRAGUE: until 1991.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Restructuring cannot be too hasty,'' said Svatopluk Smutny, an
economics editor at the Communist Party newspaper Rude Pravo. ``It
is far too important a change and needs to be thought out in detail
and consequences.''
   Communists like Smutny reluctantly admit to some parallels
between the current situation and 1968, when Dubcek at the age of
46 became party leader with a mandate to implement market-oriented
reforms designed to boost the economy.
   But Dubcek opted for political reform as well, advocating
changes Gorbachev now wants 20 years later.
   It was a heady spell wistfully remembered by many.
   ``It was, quite simply, the best time of my life,'' recalled one
man who was then a teen-ager in Prague.
   For Communists, 1968 carries a different message. They remember
how Dubcek promised that his reforms were irreversible, and look
anxiously now toward Moscow for signs of a conservative backlash
that could crunch Gorbachev.
   If Gorbachev strengthens his hold on power, both Moscow and
Prague may eventually re-evaluate the 1968 invasion _ in effect, a
Kremlin acknowledgment that it was the wrong thing to do and won't
happen again.
   Such a reappraisal would be popular with those who remember
1968, and create space for change that would be welcomed by those
who have grown up since.
   Both these groups increasingly have turned outside the system
for spiritual fulfillment, opening up what the banned playwright
Vaclav Havel recently termed ``a yawning chasm between two
virtually unrelated worlds _ the world of official ideology and the
world of the authentic attitudes and beliefs of society.''
   The rigid controls on Czechoslovakia's active state-run culture
have loosened a little with the advent of glasnost in Moscow.
   The first political satire in 20 years has been staged, a few
unofficial art shows mounted and a handful of previously banned
movies screened.
   The immense popularity of officially tolerated and underground
rock-music groups has forced authorities to issue more good rock
music on the sole, state-owned record label, as well as to relax
bans on some groups and to promote the occasional rock concert.
   Anxious perhaps to follow the example of Soviet television
programs beamed daily to Czechoslovakia's 15.5 million people, the
state-run media have become a mite more lively and provocative.
   But, while the name of Franz Kafka has made a rare appearance in
a literary journal, his full works are still unpublished in his
native Prague.
   Orthodox Communists visiting Moscow return genuinely appalled by
the outspoken new plays, books and films in the Soviet Union.
   Plays by Havel, performed to high acclaim in the West, remain
banned in Czechoslovakia, and dissidents forced to take manual jobs
are unlikely to return to their professions any time soon.
   Secret police no longer block the doors of dissidents' homes.
But three seminars called by the human rights group Charter 77 have
been broken up by police, who expelled 33 foreigners who attended
meetings in Prague June 17-18.
   In Bratislava in March, authorities sharply dampened the growing
activism of religious believers when police broke up a peaceful
demonstration by about 2,000 Roman Catholics.
   Religion has proved an increasingly attractive spiritual refuge
over the past five years, and some 600,000 believers recently
signed a 31-point petition for religious freedom, the largest such
action in Soviet bloc history.
   Another issue on which Czechoslovaks are increasingly outspoken
is the environment, which has been severely damaged by crash
industrialization.
   Opinions vary about whether these specific challenges to or
retreats from official doctrine will one day spill over into revolt.
   ``The moral situation is each year worse,'' said a pessimistic
Ivan Klima, a writer and Charter 77 signatory. ``The people are
cautious _ that is the mildest word. They don't find any reason for
engagement in political activity.''
   ``Fear rules our society,'' said the Rev. Vaclav Maly, a Roman
Catholic priest stripped of his license to preach. ``People are
generally well informed, but fear prevents them from doing
anything.''
   Very slowly, he said, this attitude is changing as people
realize ``it is not enough'' to preserve the perks of a relatively
high standard of living.
   Havel, too, sees change coming.
   ``Between the society and the leadership there is a bigger and
bigger gap,'' he said. ``You don't find anybody anywhere who says,
`This excellent government.' ... I don't know if something will
happen, but I think that something must happen.''
   If political change comes, he added, ``society is well prepared.
People know what to do.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0723EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Czechoslovakia-Dubcek Adv03   06-28 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Czechoslovakia-Dubcek, Adv 03,0323</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Czechoslovakia _ Dubcek Now a Retired Clerk</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: With BC-Czechoslovakia, b0677-b0678. One of a three-story
package</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Dubcek, ousted by the Soviets after they crushed his
Prague Spring liberalization movement in 1968, lives today in the
seclusion of a villa overlooking Bratislava, capital of his native
Slovakia.
   Officially, he is a retired forestry clerk.
   Dubcek was arrested after the Soviet-led invasion of August 1968
but released and allowed to remain on in his post as
Czechoslovakia's Communist Party leader.
   From then on it was an escalator ride to oblivion:
   _April, 1969: He is removed as party leader and named president
of Parliament, a largely ceremonial post.
   _September: In a purge of the party Central Committee, he is
fired as Parliament president.
   _December: Dubcek is named ambassador to Turkey.
   _March, 1970: He is suspended from the Communist Party.
   _June: He is formally expelled from the Communist Party and
called home from Turkey.
   _July: Dubcek is recalled as a deputy in Parliament's House of
the People, his last remaining official post. He and his wife,
Anna, move into political exile in Slovakia, where he is given a
job as a clerk in a forestry office.
   From then on, little is known, except that Dubcek, now 66 years
old, is retired from his forestry job.
   He and his family are said to have been kept under close
surveillance until Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the reformist Soviet
leader, visited Czechoslovakia in April, 1987.
   He made a few trips to Prague this year and on one occasion was
loudly applauded when he attended a theater performance.
   However, an attempt earlier this year by Dubcek and some other
Communist leaders from the Prague Spring to found an alternative
political grouping was repressed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
