<1ST_LINE>s i BC-Czechoslovakia-Religion Adv03   06-28 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Czechoslovakia-Religion, Adv 03,0346</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, July 3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Czechoslovakia _ A Challenging Church</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: With BC-Czechoslovakia, b0677-b0678, and
BC-Czechoslovakia-Dubcek, b0679. One of a three-story package.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRATISLAVA, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major force the
Czechoslovakia's Communist leaders face is growing religious faith,
in defiance of the government's atheistic teachings.
   Every Sunday, people of all ages cram Bratislava's Roman
Catholic churches.
   More and more young Czechoslovaks are turning to the Roman
Catholic and other churches.
   No official statistics are available on the number of believers.
The Vatican estimates that 60 percent of the country's 15.5 million
people are Roman Catholics, but state television says believers
make up just 25 to 30 percent of the population.
   The Roman Catholic Church has recently become a newly powerful
force, with some 600,000 believers signing a lay petition for more
religious freedom.
   The petition had the unprecedented backing of 89-year-old
Cardinal Frantisek Tomasek, who took the mass support as a signal
for a strong attack on the Communists' refusal to appoint bishops
in nine of the country's 13 sees or to allow more religious
education.
   Believers' frustrations over church policy have spilled over
into regular demonstrations outside the cardinal's residence in
Prague with calls for religious freedom and a visit from Pope John
Paul II.
   Perhaps influenced by the Kremlin's new tolerance of the Russian
Orthodox Church and growing Western condemnation of its church
policy, the Prague government sanctioned the consecration of three
new bishops in June.
   But, a Slovak believer recently warned, ``Religion is not free
here. Don't be deceived.''
   It is not clear where the new militancy of the Roman Catholic
Church could lead. As the only organized body outside Communist
control, it has always attracted party ire.
   The church's situation in Czechoslovakia is much worse than
elsewhere in the Soviet bloc, something believers attribute in part
to the ideological crackdown that followed the failed attempts at
Communist reforms in 1968.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, July 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
