<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Video View: Home Video News and Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mike Tyson fight is almost as hot as Muhammad
Ali's ``Thrilla in Manila'' and ``Rumble in the Jungle'' were a
decade or so ago when ``the Greatest'' took on Joe Frazier and
George Forman.
   And for those who couldn't afford tickets to Tyson's June 27
clash with Michael Spinks in Atlantic City, HBO Video will release
the home videocassette on July 13.
   Meanwhile, HBO has already put out ``Mike Tyson's Greatest
Hits,'' an hour-long montage of the heavyweight boxer's best
fights, including his World Boxing Congress, World Boxing
Association and International Boxing Federation championship
triumphs.
   The video opens with the late legendary trainer Cus D'Amato
taking Tyson from the angry sidewalks of Brownsville and
Bedford-Stuyvesant and molding him into a precision-run diesel.
   ``Remember,'' D'Amato counsels the young kid of iron, ``it's
always good to throw the punch where you can hit him and he can't
hit you. That's what the science of boxing is all about.''
   The tape shows Tyson fine-tuning his awesome knock-out punch
against such early opponents as Trent Singleton, Donald Halpin,
Rick Spain, Michael Johnson and Hector Mercades. The video also
includes footage of Tyson's defeat of long-time champ Larry Holmes.
   ``Mike Tyson's Greatest Hits'' is the first video in a series of
boxing programs planned by HBO. It retails in VHS for $19.99.
   Videos reviewed this week: ``Housekeeping'' and ``Benji the
Hunted.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Housekeeping'' (RCA-Columbia Home Video; VHS-Beta, $79.95;
Rated PG)
   
   This entertaining, offbeat comedy centers around an eccentric
aunt and the two orphaned nieces left in her care. One is a
conformist; the other opts to be a free spirit.
   The two luckless orphans are in need of a parent when Aunt
Sylvie, played by Christine Lahti, returns to her tiny hometown in
the Pacific Northwest to care for them. She isn't much on
housekeeping, and the children seem to be taking care of her.
   Sylvie stockpiles old newspapers in the home, collects and
stacks tin cans, naps on park benches, keeps crumbs in her pockets
for imaginary children, grows fungus in flower pots and never cuts
the lawn.
   The two girls, Lucille and Ruthie, played by Canadians Sara
Walker and Andrea Burchill in their first roles, don't have much of
a choice when it comes to parents. They never knew their father.
   As for their mother, after leaving her two young daughters at
their grandmother's house in the mountain community of Fingerbone,
she drives her car off a cliff and into a deep lake, killing
herself. Years later, when the grandmother dies, Aunt Sylvie comes
to live with them.
   Eventually, Lucille is repulsed by Sylvie's eccentricities, and
figures out their lifestyle is weird. She starts dressing up and
makes new friends while plotting to leave town to see the world.
She finally leaves and moves in with a teacher.
   Ruthie, however, embraces her aunt's carefree lifestyle. But the
townspeople decide Sylvie must clean up her place and Ruthie must
be removed from such influence.
   But Sylvie and Ruthie stage a disappearance, cover their tracks
and wander off.
   Bill Forsyth (``Gregory's Girl,'' ``Local Hero'') directed this
film, which won raves for Lahti when it had its theatrical run.
   _ By Robert Dvorchak, AP National Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``Benji The Hunted'' (Walt Disney Home Video; VHS-Beta, $89.95;
Rated G)
   
   ``Benji The Hunted'' provides fresh evidence that the soulful
canine star may be the most accomplished actor in movies today.
   In his latest outing, Benji survives a shipwreck off the Oregon
coast and is on his way to a reunion with owner Frank Innes when he
stumbles upon a litter of orphaned cougar cubs. For the rest of the
film's 89 minutes, Benji struggles against rugged terrain and an
assortment of human and animal villains to find the cubs shelter
and a new mother.
   Director Joe Camp elicits a truly amazing performance from
Benji, his expressive eyes registering whatever emotion the plot
calls for, whether it be fear or slyness or tenderness. In one
startling scene, he brilliantly portrays a canine in conflict, as
Benji must decide whether to reveal himself to a search-and-rescue
helicopter or hide so he can remain in the wilderness to help the
cubs.
   The other actors can't match Benji, although the cubs are
awfully cute and a particularly vicious wolf has a grand death
scene. The human participants are few and there is virtually no
dialogue.
   Children over 4 should enjoy ``Benji the Hunted,'' although the
pace is slow and the story line is occasionally confusing.
   _ By Mike Silverman, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
