<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   06-28 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0547</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Out of Order'' (Warner Bros.) _ Rod Stewart
   
   Spin the first side of ``Out of Order,'' and you not only wonder
why Rod Stewart still has a recording contract, but why he earned
one in the first place.
   Fortunately, most records still have two sides. And side 2 of
this album is as impressive as the first side is depressing.
   That Rod Stewart's been a shallow trend mongerer for most of the
last decade is hardly news. Word that he'd recruited ex-Duran Duran
Andy Taylor and much of the Power Station crew for his new record
seemed to promise an album about two years behind the time.
   Instead, this crew seems to have loosened up Stewart, as his
howl on ``Crazy About Her'' suggests. If this isn't the real Rod
Stewart _ who knows what is anymore? _ at least it's a Stewart that
wears well.
   The two ballads that close this record, a cover of ``Try a
Little Tenderness'' and ``When I Was Your Man'' are both stellar,
as Stewart turns his distinctive growl into something soulful.
   ``Dynamite'' is a raunchy rocker that's more fun than some of
Stewart's more studied efforts. You can almost pity the mod one on
``Nobody Knows When You're Down and Out,'' although his complaint
of opening his door and finding a woman he doesn't know saying
she's having his baby is one of those problems only Rod seems to
have.
   So what happened to side 1? It's packed with clunkers, made all
the more sinful because most are stretched two or three minutes
beyond what a listener can endure.
   One side good, one side bad. The way's Stewart's been going
lately, he should take that batting average.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Evening Star'' (Contemporary Records) _ Joshua Breakstone
   
   Guitarist Joshua Breakstone plays textbook jazz with a few notes
scrawled in the margins.
   If ever a label name fit a musician's style, Contemporary suits
Breakstone perfectly. Yet, he delivers enough of himself in this
recording, his second for the label, to keep the record from being
merely a send up from ghosts of guitarists past, such as Wes
Montgomery or Grant Green. Note, for example, the opening bars of
the album closer, ``Just Open Your Heart.'' A reference to the
atonal mastery of Thelonious Monk, they quickly leave Monk's world
of surprises for more familiar ground, traditional straight-ahead
jazz.
   If you're looking for developing young guitarists to preserve
the traditions of jazz, the New Jersey-born Breakstone is a
candidate. His choice of sidemen for this session proves it. Tommy
Flanagan is on piano and Jimmy Knepper plays trombone. Their styles
polished by years of playing, Flanagan and Knepper make Breakstone
sound refined beyond his 32 years.
   ``Evening Star'' mixes Breakstone's own compositions with
standards. It's an album of nearly seamless playing on which two
masters of the craft _ Flanagan and Knepper _ are bringing along
the next generation.
   _ By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
