<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GM-Johnson     06-28 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM-Johnson,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Once Chairmanship Contender, Johnson Returns to Private Law
Practice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A General Motors Corp. executive vice president
and director who joined the company only five years ago and once
was considered a potential successor to the chairman has left the
automaker, GM says.
   Elmer W. Johnson, 56, resigned Monday from the board of
directors and retired as executive vice president in charge of GM's
legal, public affairs and operating staffs to return to the Chicago
law firm of Kirkland and Ellis.
   His departure was expected following several published reports
last week.
   One of the few outsiders to enter GM so near the top, Johnson
came to be known as a frustrated critic of the world's largest
manufacturer and its vast bureacracy because of its resistance to
change.
   Johnson engineered the departure of another well-known outsider,
Texas billionaire H. Ross Perot. Perot, founder of Electronic Data
Systems Corp., joined GM's board when he sold EDS to GM.
   Perot was GM's largest individual shareholder. He also become
one of its most vocal critics, and in late 1986, GM bought him out
for $750 million. Johnson was never as loud nor as public a critic
as Perot.
   Johnson, who became GM's general counsel, was elected an
executive vice president and director on May 22, 1987. GM Chairman
Roger Smith had indicated last year that Johnson was among
contenders for the chairmanship when Smith retires in 1990.
   ``Elmer Johnson has made significant and lasting contributions
to General Motors over the past five years,'' GM Chairman Roger
Smith said in a statement after Johnson resigned Monday at a board
meeting in New York.
   ``We will all miss our daily association with him and his
abilities,'' Smith said.
   In the same statement, Johnson said: ``My decision to retire
from General Motors was based on a number of considerations,'' but
didn't list any.
   ``Over the last five years GM has undergone a number of
extraordinary transactions. I'm glad that I had an opportunity to
contribute to the process,'' he said.
   William Hoglund, vice president in charge of GM's
Buick-Oldsmobile-Cadillac Group, is considered most likely to
replace Johnson.
   But GM spokesman Bill Winters said no decisions had been made
and he did not know when any executive changes resulting from
Johnson's departure would be made. The next scheduled board meeting
is Aug. 1 in Detroit.
   Johnson's retirement benefits will consist of an annuity
beginning at age 65 based on his contributions to GM's salaried
retirement plan and any interest, Winters said.
   Johnson hadn't been with GM long enough to be eligible for the
full range of GM retiree benefits, Winters said.
   Analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko Securities International in New
York said Johnson never had a clear shot at the chairmanship
because he was an outsider and he lacked automaking experience.
   ``Usually everybody at GM has been there since right out of
college. It's like a lifetime career,'' she said.
   In addition, Johnson was ``a little bit critical, said the
company wasn't moving fast enough. For him to have gotten Roger
Smith's job in 1990 would have been a real long shot,'' Heaney said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
