<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0851EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BreweryClosing     06-28 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brewery Closing,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last Major Brewery In Illinois Closing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stag Brewery, the last remaining
full-sized brewery in Illinois and one of the oldest in the
Midwest, will close by fall, putting more than 200 people out of
work, company officials said.
   An official with G. Heileman Brewing Co., which owns Stag, said
Monday the plant was closing because of ``certain financial and
operational considerations.''
   The brewery dates back to the 1850s.
   ``This decision to end operations here is difficult in view of
the cooperation and support extended to us by the employees, the
labor unions, Mayor (Richard) Brauer's administration and the
community,'' said Charles Nicks, administrative manager at the
parent company.
   While company officials refused to discuss specific reasons, one
observer linked it to the location of Heileman's other Midwestern
breweries, the age of the plant and an enormous excess capacity.
   Robert F. Weinberg, an industry research specialist in St.
Louis, said Heileman used only 64 percent of the capacity of its
plants last year.
   ``The company has the capacity to brew 25.3 million barrels of
beer,'' Weinberg said. ``They shipped 16.25 million barrels last
year. Obviously, they decided they didn't need the Belleville
brewery's 1.1 million barrel capacity.''
   Nicks said about 230 employees will lose their jobs. Between 200
and 300 employees are employed by the brewery, depending on the
season.
   The remaining beer manufacturers in Illinois are classified as
``micro-breweries'' because they produce only limited amounts of
brew and serve it only on their own premises, rather than bottling
or canning it.
</TEXT>
