<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Union-DrugTesting     06-28 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Union-Drug Testing,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rail Union Signs Agreement On Drug And Alcohol Testing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agreement between the Southeastern
Pennsylvania Transportation Authoritity and the Brotherhood of
Railroad Signalmen allowing random drug testing of rail workers is
being hailed as the first of its kind in the country.
   Dave Murdoch, a SEPTA spokesman, said the agreement signed
Monday is the first in the country in which a rail union has agreed
to random drug testing. He stressed that the testing would ``not be
used as a dragnet.''
   The agreement also includes an employee assistance program with
educational components and Red Block, a nationally recognized
program in the rail industry which allows employees to refer other
employees for assistance.
   In January, a federal judge ruled railroad employees would not
be subject to random testing unless the individual rail labor
organizations agreed.
   ``With the support of my members, the signalmen initiated this
type of agreement for the safety of fellow employees and the safety
of the riding public,'' said BRS General Chairman Roland E.
McKenzie in a news release.
   ``My members have no fear of such tests and in the event a
member has a drug or alcohol related problem the agreement goes
further and addresses those needs providing rehabilitation help in
an accessible manner,'' McKenzie said.
   The program should be in operation by the fall.
   ``We would like to give credit and applaud the BRS for their
efforts and willingness to take a stand, which was obviously a
difficult one,'' James Kilcur, acting general manager of SEPTA said
in a press release.
</TEXT>
