<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     06-28 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0322</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was little changed today amid
continuing worries about the outlook for interest rates and
inflation.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped .17 to 2,108.29
in the first half hour.
   Losers held a narrow lead over gainers in the overall tally of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 419 up, 463 down and
516 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 19.39 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   As the day began, traders were faced with news of an increase in
British interest rates and an overnight decline in the dollar.
   Rates rose slightly in the U.S. credit markets. The dollar,
however, showed signs of steadying in foreign exchange.
   Analysts said investors remained concerned over the drought in
the Midwest after futures contracts for several basic farm
commodities jumped by their allowable daily limits on Monday.
   Strong upward pressure on food prices is seen as an inflationary
threat. But some observers say increased food costs will dampen
consumer demand for other, discretionary goods, thus mitigating the
overall impact on prices.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines rose ] to 125]; General Electric [ to 42}, and Exxon \ to
45.
   L.A. Gear gained 1\ to 32[ in the over-the-counter market. The
footwear producer reported sharply higher quarterly earnings.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.13 to 152.35. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .08 at 306.70.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 34.50 to
2,108.46.
   Declining issues outpaced advances by more than 5 to 2 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 411 up, 1,088 down and 438 unchanged.
Big Board volume came to 264.41 million shares, against 179.88
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
