<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-Stocks     06-28 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Off</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: will be led with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London Stock Exchange turned
slightly lower at midday Tuesday as the market ignored news of a
rise in British interest rates.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was off 1.8
points, or 0.1 percent, at 1,839.7 at 1 p.m. local time, little
changed from its level before the rate hikes.
   Trading volume was a low 220.6 million shares, compared with
203.6 million shares at the same time Monday.
   Dealers said the market was little affected by the news at
midday that the Bank of England, by raising a money-market
intervention rate of its own, signaled a rise in the commercial
banks' base lending rate to 9.5 percent from 9 percent. The banks
quickly responded.
   ``We moved a tickle easier but I don't think anyone changed a
single price,'' said one equity salesman.
   Dealers said the increase had been widely expected following the
release of trade data on Monday showing that Britain's merchandise
trade balance had widened sharply to a record 1.705 billion pounds,
or $2.9 billion dollars. Its current account trade gap also widened
to a record 1.205 billion pounds, or $2.05 billion.
   The trade figures drove equities sharply lower Monday, when the
100-share index fell 29.8 points, and led to a sharp decline in the
pound.
   ``There is a feeling in the market that a half-point rate hike
isn't enough to combat inflation problems,'' said one dealer.
   ``There's still pressure in the market for another rate hike to
10 percent,'' said another dealer.
</TEXT>
