<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Citicorp-FirstRepublic     06-28 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Citicorp-First Republic,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Citicorp Team Studying First RepublicBank Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First RepublicBank Corp. says that a team of
officers from Citicorp, the nation's largest bank holding company,
is in Dallas studying a possible acquisition of the troubled bank.
   A First RepublicBank internal memo distributed Monday indicates
that about 20 Citicorp officials are examining First RepublicBank's
books and financial condition. Citicorp officials, though, have
declined to comment.
   First RepublicBank, the largest bank-holding company in Texas,
received a $1-billion bailout earlier this year from the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corp. The bank has been plagued by sour real
estate loans.
   The Citicorp visit was arranged by the FDIC, which says it is
negotiating with a number of parties interested in acquiring First
RepublicBank with federal assistance.
   First RepublicBank Chairman Albert Casey told company employees
in the memo that several banks have ``expressed interest in First
RepublicBank to the FDIC. One of those organizations is New
York-based Citicorp.''
   But the Dallas Morning News reported Monday that one bank has
maintained a serious interest in acquiring First RepublicBank, and
some First Republic insiders told the Dallas Times-Herald that to
their knowledge Citicorp is the first bank to take an in-depth look
at the bank holding company.
   Along with the Citicorp team, 80 examiners from the FDIC
division of liquidation also are looking at First RepublicBank's
books.
   The FDIC says it expects to act shortly on the First
RepublicBank rescue and has set a June 30 deadline for potential
acquirers to submit their bids.
   Citicorp and First RepublicBank, if combined, would form one of
the 10 largest bank holding companies in the world.
</TEXT>
