<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board of Trade, Open</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened
sharply lower today at the Chicago Board of Trade in a nervous
market concerned about possible rain in the Midwest.
   The possibility of rain in the major growing regions over the
next few days led to profit-taking after the market's recent
drought-driven rallies.
   ``There's a little bit of rain in the forecast and that makes
the bulls nervous,'' said Victor Lespinasse, an analyst with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc.
   But after dipping slightly at the opening, corn and soybean
futures strengthened on the underlying feeling that rainfall
amounts won't be enough to offer much relief to drought-stricken
crops.
   In early trading, wheat was 4{ cents to 14 cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.86{ a bushel; corn was 4{ cents
to 12{ cents lower, with July at $3.40 a bushel; oats were 15 cents
higher across the board with December at $3.89\ a bushel; and
soybeans were 3{ cents to 18{ cents lower, with July at $10.41 a
bushel.
   Cattle and hog futures prices opened mixed at the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, live cattle were .30 cent lower to .68 cent
higher, with the contract for delivery in August at 64.77 cents a
pound; feeder cattle were .5 cent to .80 cent higher with August at
72.35 cents a pound; live hogs were .32 cent lower to .65 cent
higher with July at 45.95 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies
were .55 cent lower to 1.20 cents higher with July at 38.50 cents a
pound.
   Cattle and hog futures closed sharply higher in trading Monday.
</TEXT>
