<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions July 2-3 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Toy Manufacturers Hoping for Hot Weather Hits</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: spelling of Pogo Bal, Jamball, Dip Stix, Skipstik and Lazer
Tag are cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The arrival of summer has made stars of
Crocodile Mile, Jamball and Groove Tube.
   They are among the hottest toys of the season, entertaining
children and _ crucial for the recovering toy industry _ bringing
in sales for manufacturers.
   Summer toys are ``viewed as an area where the companies can
potentially get a stable base of revenues,'' said Paul Valentine,
who tracks the toy industry for Standard & Poor's Corp.
   Stability is exactly what toymakers want after the industry's
1987 washout, when manufacturers committed too much cash to
overambitious product lines that failed. Many big companies ended
up losing money.
   One bright spot last year _ last summer, in fact _ was Hasbro
Inc.'s Pogo Bal.
   The spherical toy, used like a pogo stick, was the hottest toy
of the season. For all of 1987, Hasbro sold 3 million Pogo Bals,
raking in an estimated $35 million in sales. And it's doing well
again in 1988.
   This has not been lost on other toymakers.
   ``The huge success of Pogo Bal last spring and summer led to
increased emphasis by the industry on these toys,'' said Valentine.
``Everyone jumped into the segment.''
   Analysts say there is no one single blockbuster summer toy in
1988. But ``summer toys and sports look quite strong,'' said Barry
Rothberg of the investment firm Mabon, Nugent & Co.
   The most popular summer toy this year, according to the
best-seller list compiled by the trade publication Toy & Hobby
World, is Coleco Industries Inc.'s Jamball, a game in which players
throw and catch a large orange ball without touching it.
   Toys R Us Inc., the nationwide toy store chain, reports
Crocodile Mile, a backyard water slide by Marchon, is selling well,
as is Groove Tube, a game involving a ball and a long plastic tube
produced by Hasbro's Milton Bradley division.
   Bubbles are big this year, so Dip Stix by Lewis Galoob Toys Inc.
and Fisher-Price's Bubble Mower are selling well, said Angela
Bourdon, a Toys R Us spokeswoman.
   But bicycles, which did well in 1988, have slipped. Huffy Corp.,
the Ohio-based manufacturer of Raleigh and Huffy bicycles, said it
has suffered a slowdown in sales in the second quarter.
   Barry Ryan, Huffy's vice president for finance, attributed the
slump in part to a possible saturation of the market after several
years of strong sales.
   In addition, Ryan said, ``Retailers just overbought and created
a logjam in the pipeline.''
   Kites, another summer standard, are again popular, including
Milton Bradley's Air America, Valentine said.
   So are jump ropes. At Worlds of Wonder Inc., which is undergoing
reorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code, the
summer has been brightened by the success of Skipstik, a variation
on the jump rope.
   Struggling companies like Worlds of Wonder and Coleco, which is
trying to stay out of bankruptcy court, desperately need the
profits from their seasonal offerings. But the sad fact is, no
matter how successful such toys are, they're unlikely to turn the
companies around.
   The problem with summer toys is their lifespan is brief _ just a
few months _ and while they can help a company, they don't have the
kind of bottom-line impact of more timeless products.
   Even Pogo Bal's exceptional 1987 sales were ``far below what a
successful year-round toy would have done,'' Valentine said. In
contrast to Pogo Bal's $35 million in sales, the video game
Nintendo, the biggest toy of 1987, took in $750 million.
   It should also be noted that even with the popularity of
seasonal items, the top-selling toys are still the same ones that
occupied children during the winter.
   Nintendo took the No. 1 spot on Toy & Hobby World's list of
best-selling toys in May, the most recent month for which figures
are available. No. 2 was Mattel Inc.'s ever-popular Barbie doll,
followed in third place by the board game Pictionary, manufactured
by Games Gang Ltd.
   As was the case last year, there are no ``megahit'' toys on the
market like the Cabbage Patch Kids, Teddy Ruxpin or Lazer Tag that
had consumers jamming into stores in the past. But video games and
what are called basic toys _ such as board games, Barbie and
preschool toys _ are bringing the industry back.
   The third quarter, when Christmas toys are shipped, is the
biggest for the industry, and the one that will ultimately
determine how well the manufacturers do. But so far, the analysts
said, the business has a better tone than it did a year ago.
   ``The environment is getting better,'' said Rothberg, the Mabon,
Nugent analyst. ``(Product) movement is pretty good.''
   Steven Eisenberg, who tracks the industry for Bear Stearns &
Co., gave an industry forecast of ``reasonably healthy to possibly
very healthy for some of the larger companies.''
   In the meantime, the summer is proceeding ``right on
expectations,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions July 2-3</NOTE>
