<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0307</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned upward today, recovering
some of Monday's losses.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down 34.50 on Monday,
climbed 13.16 to 2,121.62 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 3 to 2 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 770 up, 515 down and
514 unchanged.
   As the day began, traders were faced with news of an increase in
British interest rates and an overnight decline in the dollar.
   The dollar, however, showed signs of steadying in foreign
exchange as the day passed. Interest rates in the U.S. credit
markets headed lower after an initial rise.
   Analysts said investors remained concerned over the drought in
the Midwest after futures contracts for several basic farm
commodities jumped by their allowable daily limits on Monday.
   Strong upward pressure on food prices is seen as an inflationary
threat. But some observers say increased food costs will dampen
consumer demand for other, discretionary goods, thus mitigating the
overall impact on prices.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines rose 1{ to 126{; Exxon | to 45], and American Telephone &
Telegraph [ to 26|.
   Data General, buffeted by takeover speculation, gained 1{ to 24[.
   L.A. Gear gained 2[ to 33 in the over-the-counter market. The
footwear producer reported sharply higher quarterly earnings.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.85 to 153.07. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .67 at 307.29.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 66.81 million shares at
noontime, down from 184.25 million at the same point Monday, when
the total was inflated by dividend-related activity in a few
high-yielding stocks.
