<1ST_LINE>u f PM-PlantClosings 2ndLd-Writethru f0066 06-28 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Plant Closings, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0066,0534</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 4 grafs recast for clarity, picking up 5th graf
pvs, The same; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<HEAD>Leaders Push for Quick Vote on Plant-Closings Notice Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, moving to vote on the
controversial plant-closure bill this week, agreed today that
employers need not give strikers 60 days' notice they are being
laid off.
   An amendment by Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, including that
exemption was approved 91-0.
   President Reagan last month vetoed a massive trade bill
primarily because of the mandatory-notice provision. The issues has
become a major domestic political issue in this year's election.
   Marjority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., made it clear Monday
that he wants final congressional votes on the legislation before
lawmakers leave town to spend July 4th on the hustings.
   The same urgency was expressed on the House side, where Speaker
Jim Wright, D-Texas, said his chamber would vote in fairly quick
succession Wednesday on the plant-closing legislation and then on
the 1,000-page omnibus trade bill.
   Byrd said he had hoped for a Senate vote today but to be on the
safe side he took steps to invoke cloture, or halt debate, if that
were needed to bring the matter to a vote later in the week.
   The plant-closing measure, newly detached from the trade bill,
would require companies with at least 100 employees to provide
advance notice of large-scale layoffs and plant closings. President
Reagan singled it out for special criticism in his May 24 veto of
the trade legislation.
   Reagan said it would rob managers of flexibility needed to
operate their companies at peak economic health. Proponents say
advance notice is the only decent way to treat breadwinners facing
layoffs.
   The Senate on Monday voted 64-32 to kill a move by Sen. Nancy
Kassebaum, R-Kan., to drop advance notice of layoffs from the bill.
   Critics said the overall bill was too broad and that dropping
the layoff provision represented one way to impose limits.
   ``A layoff of 50 employees at a 10,000-employee manufacturing
plant would not be a plant closing to most people but it is under
terms of this legislation,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
   Sen. Howard M. Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, called the plan a ``blueprint
for employers who want to disobey the plant-closings law itself.''
   ``Employers would simply lay them off, piece by piece, bit by
bit, until there was nothing left,'' Metzenbaum said.
   The plant-closing provision was dropped from the trade bill and
reconstituted as a separate piece of legislation after the Senate
was unable to override Reagan's trade bill veto.
   Labor unions have been seeking plant-closing legislation in one
form or another for 15 years.
   Reagan is expected to veto the legislation if, as seems likely,
it reaches his desk in its new, stand-alone form.
   The trade bill was initially viewed as an ideal vehicle to
propel the plant-closing provision through Congress. But sponsors
are now saying that they might have a better chance to override a
veto without being tied to the numerous other controversies in the
trade bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
