<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Payless-Edelman     06-28 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Payless-Edelman,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Edelman Denied Information For Possible Payless Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group led by New York
financier Asher Edelman complained Tuesday that Payless Cashways
Inc. refused to provide information in connection with a possible
takeover bid for the building materials retailer.
   Edelman's group twice requested information used by Payless
senior management to formulate the $26-a-share bid they offered
last week to take the company private in an $875 million leveraged
buyout.
   Edelman spokesman Corey Horowitz said the group received a
letter Friday denying the information. He did not say why the
request was denied.
   ``We believe the failure to give us the information is unfair
and without legal precedent,'' Horowitz said. ``It certainly works
to the detriment of the shareholders.''
   Payless officials confirmed the letter was sent but declined
further comment.
   The Edelman group, which once held a 9.9 percent stake in
Payless and said it might make a bid for the entire company, now
controls about 8.1 percent of the company's 33.6 million
outstanding shares.
   In addition to Edelman, the group also includes Payless
competitor Sutherland Lumber Southwest Inc., also of Kansas City.
   Payless spokeswoman Brenda Nolte declined comment on whether the
board's special committee had received other bids or has acted on
the management officials' leveraged buyout offer.
   Separately, two Payless shareholders filed suit Monday in
Jackson County Circuit Court against Payless Chairman and Chief
Executive David Stanley, Larry Kunz, the president, and the board
of directors.
   The suit contends that the defendants are ``carrying out a
preconceived plan to eliminate the public common stockholders of
Payless at a grossly inadequate price.''
   The shareholders _ Robert Gillespie of Westtown, Pa., and Terry
Shickler of New York _ also contend that the primary objective of
the management buy-out is to allow those involved to acquire
Payless at a ``fraudulently low and unfair price.''
</TEXT>
