<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Share Prices Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: new throughout to UPDATE with closing index, comments; no
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose Tuesday after investors were
pleasantly surprised by a smaller-than-expected hike in a benchmark
British interest rate.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index gained 15.4
points, or 0.8 percent, to close at 1,856.9.
   Trading volume totaled 386.7 million shares, compared with
Monday's 390.7 million shares.
   The market was initially little affected by the midday news that
the Bank of England signaled a rise in the commercial banks' base
lending rate to 9.5 percent from 9.0 percent. But investors soon
became heartened that the increase had only been a half-point, and
not a full point as had been widely expected in the market.
   An advance on Wall Street added a bit of upward stimulus to
rising London equities, dealers said.
   Charles Larkum, equity analyst with James Capel & Co., said the
market's rise was ``an expression of relief.''
   The widely anticipated rate increase followed a government
report Monday that showed the Briitsh merchandise trade deficit
widened sharply to a record 1.705 billion pounds, or $2.9 billion,
in May, while its current account gap also widened to a record
1.205 billion pounds.
   The trade figures drove equities and the pound sharply lower on
Monday.
</TEXT>
