<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 1510EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-28 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0285</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corn and soybean futures prices plummeted to
their daily limits Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in a wild
reversal based on concerns that rain may fall across the Midwest
and bring relief to drought-stricken crops.
   ``That dirty word was being heard on the floor today, r-a-i-n.
Not a lot, just a little bit, but that's all it takes to scare
anybody,'' said Victor Lespinasse, an analyst with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   ``That caused massive liquidation,'' he said, among buyers in
the corn and soybean pits who had been anticipating the drought
would continue to damage crops and tighten supplies.
   Those were the same traders who a day earlier had pushed prices
up the limit in expectation of another hot, dry forecast.
   Corn prices closed down the daily limit _ expanded Tuesday to 15
cents a bushel _ in all but two months; while soybeans fell the
expanded 45-cents-a bushel limit in all months except November 1989.
   ``We're at a turning point here,'' Lespinasse said, as nobody
knows the impact rains forecast for the next few days over much of
the Midwest will have on thirsty crops.
   ``Everybody's scared to death because of that dirty word,'' he
said.
   At the close, wheat was .22{ cent to .28{ cent lower, with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.73 a bushel; corn was .01{ cent
to .15 cent lower with July at $3.37{ a bushel; oats were .15 cent
lower across the board with July at $3.63 a bushel; and soybeans
were .26 cent to .45 cent lower with July at $10.14{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
