<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ConstructionContracts     06-28 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Construction Contracts,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Contracting Gains In May</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: for release 6:30 p.m. EDT, time set by source.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The value of new construction projects rose 9
percent in May, reversing a declining trend, according to a report
released Tuesday.
   But the improvement, which translated to an annualized $246.4
billion in new construction projects, was dominated by a cluster of
major, non-building projects, said the F.W. Dodge Division of
McGraw-Hill Information Systems Co.
   General construction activity, which includes housing and
commercial buildings, was up only slightly from the previous month
and still held below last year's levels.
   The contract statistics measure the value of newly started
construction that will be completed in the upcoming months. They
indicate the amount and direction of future expenditures of the
building industry.
   George Christie, F.W. Dodge vice president and chief economist,
called the surge in contracting ``an isolated event affecting a
narrow slice of the construction sector'' and not a turnaround.
   He noted that commercial building markets ``remain overbuilt,
public funding is under restraint and homeuilding is vulnerable to
rising interest rates.''
   Contracting for nonbuilding construction leaped 30 percent to an
annualized $52.9 billion in May, largely on the strength of three
major projects: a fuel processing plant in Idaho, an oil products
distribution center in California and a New Jersey waste-to-energy
facility.
   Nonresidential building construction rose 3 percent to an
annualized $79.4 billion, while the value of newly started
residential buildings rose 4 percent to an annualized $114 billion.
   Christie attributed the weak showing in the nonresidential
sector to ``acceleration of the office building cutback,'' which
had been confined to a few regions but now is becoming a national
trend.
   He also noted that higher interest rates might make doubtful the
``prospect of achieving a total of 1.5 million housing starts this
year.''
   For the year to date, construction contracts totaled $97.8
billion, down 2 percent from the same period a year earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
