<1ST_LINE>r f AM-American-Simmons     06-28 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American-Simmons ,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Airlines to Buy Simmons for $78 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines' parent said Tuesday
it has entered an agreement to acquire Simmons Airlines, the
fourth-largest regional carrier in the country.
   AMR Corp. said its subsidiary, AMR Eagle-Central, has signed an
agreement to purchase Simmons for $17.50 a share, or a total of
about $78 million.
   Under the agreement, AMR Eagle-Central will commence a cash
tender offer within five days for all of the outstanding shares of
Simmons. The board of directors of Simmons has unanimously approved
the agreement, officials said.
   Since Oct. 1, 1985, Chicago-based Simmons has been an American
Eagle commuter partner of American Airlines, providing service in
the Great Lakes region. Simmons will continue in that role after
the acquisition, the two companies said.
   American officials said the purchase makes sound business sense.
   ``We think it was just a smart business decision. The company
was for sale and we think that by applying the marketing expertise
and financial strengths of American Airlines, we can do a much
better job of operating the company, although it was doing a fine
job for us as a partner of American Eagle,'' said American
spokesman Al Becker.
   Simmons, founded in 1978, operates about 350 weekday departures
from 34 airports in seven states.
   American spokesman Steve McGregor said Simmons employs about
1,500 workers and owns 28 percent of the commuter slots at
Chicago's O'Hare International Airport, its major feeder point.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
