<1ST_LINE>r f AM-S&L-Bass     06-28 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L-Bass,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deadline Extended For Bass Takeover Of S&L</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials on Tuesday extended the
negotiating deadline for Texas billionaire Robert M. Bass in his
effort to take over the troubled American Savings and Loan
Association, the nation's second largest thrift.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates the S&L
industry, had announced on April 21 that it would negotiate
exclusively with the Robert M. Bass Group for a period of 75 days,
ending on July 5.
   But the bank board said that because of the ``complexity of the
transaction,'' it would extend the deadline until Aug. 1. The
agency said that substantial progress had been made in the
negotiations and the extension did not reflect any problems.
   The bank board has been trying for more than a year to find a
rescuer for American Savings, which currently has about $30 billion
in assets. However, its liabilities exceeded its assets by $106
million at the end of 1987.
   American Savings, based in Stockton, Calif., is the main unit of
Financial Corp. of America of Irvine, Calif.
   Sources have said that the proposed deal would require the Bass
Group to pump in several hundred million dollars of new capital and
for the bank board to provide at least several hundred million
dollars of federal assistance.
   The bank board said that its assurances to protect depositors
and general creditors of American Savings would remain in force
during the extension of the negotiating period.
</TEXT>
