<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Belzbergs     06-28 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Belzbergs,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Belzbergs Ordered To Pay Penalties On Trading Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ordered a holding company
owned by Canada's Belzberg family to pay $476,000 in interest
penalties on the $2.7 million in stock trading profits it must
forfeit for violating federal securities law.
   U.S. District Judge Barrington Parker, in an order issued last
Friday, gave First City Financial Corp. Ltd. five days to surrender
the profits from its unsuccessful attempt to takeover Ashland Oil
Co. in 1986.
   The interest penalty was assessed as part of the final judgment
that Parker entered in favor of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, which brought the complaint against the Belzberg family
company.
   Earlier this month, Parker ruled that the Vancouver-based
company and Marc Belzberg, a vice president, violated the 1934
Securities Exchange Act by concealing ownership of Ashland stock.
   Parker found that First City's failure to publicly disclose
ownership of its 5 percent stake in the oil company was intended to
prevent the price of Ashland stock from soaring while the company
continued to buy more shares in the oil company.
   First City sold its 890,100 shares back to Ashland for $51 a
share after the takeover bid was thwarted.
   The company has said it will appeal Parker's ruling that it
violated the disclosure provisions of the 1934 securities law.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
