<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PlantPlans     06-28 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Plans,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Approves Sale of Shuttered Flint Body Plant to Office
Developers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FLINT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. directors approved the
sale of the shuttered, gutted Flint Body assembly plant to a pair
of Detroit developers who specialize in making use of old
factories, GM said Tuesday.
   GM will sell the plant, which closed Dec. 10, to the partnership
of Ralph Vigliotti Realty Inc. and J.C. Miller Construction Co.,
said J.T. Battenberg III, GM vice president and product manager of
the Flint Automotive Division.
   The partnership plans to convert the historic plant, known for
decades as Fisher 1, into the Great Lakes Technology Center Inc., a
complex of offices, light industrial manufacturing, retail shops
and restaurants.
   The price of the sale was not disclosed. The sale was approved
Monday by GM's board of directors at a meeting in New York,
Battenberg said.
   Thomas Vigliotti and Miller said they will complete the purchase
only if the Flint City Council grants an immediate tax break. The
plant is in a special district where developers can receive breaks
for up to 12 years on the improvements they make.
   ``If they're going to tax it at a top rate, we won't do it,''
Vigliotti said.
   GM's Flint Automotive Division plans to lease about a half
million square feet of the plant for its engineering and materials
management complex, which will house engineers and staffs now
scattered in offices in Troy and Flint.
   The Flint Automotive Division is responsible for the
development, design, engineering and manufacture of large, luxury,
Buick-Oldsmobile-Cadillac models such as the Cadillac Fleetwood,
Oldsmobile 98 and Buick Park Avenue.
   Many of the 600 Flint Automotive Division employees in Troy,
along with 700 in Flint, will be moved to the plant after its
renovation is completed in December 1989.
   Vigliotti and Miller expect about 2,500 people will eventually
work at the renovated plant. About 3,000 GM workers lost their jobs
when it closed late last year, the last body-only GM assembly plant
in the United States.
</TEXT>
