<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Closing, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0233,0836</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought-Affected Businesses Exempted From Layoff Notices</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 new grafs to UPDATE approval of drought
amendment and new moves by Democrats to cut off debate. Picks up
4th graf pvs, bgng: ``I think; Also moved on general newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Tuesday agreed to exempt
businesses affected by the Farm Belt drought from legislation to
make employers provide 60 days advance notice of large layoffs and
plant closings.
   The amendment by Senate Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., was
approved unanimously after farm state lawmakers said they have been
told by bakeries, flour mills and meatpacking, poultry, egg,
ethanol and farm equipment plants they anticipate future layoffs
resulting from the drought currently afflicting much of the country.
   ``I don't think we ought to get carried away by the demands from
organized labor,'' Dole said. ``If we're serious about alleviating
the effects of the drought on the economy, then we ought not to be
hitting businesses with both barrels.''
   Meanwhile, Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., filed
motions for three more votes to cut off debate on the plant closing
measure _ now in its fifth day _ and threatened to hold lawmakers
in session the rest of this week or most of next week.
   ``We're going to pass this bill sooner or later, it's
inevitable,'' Byrd said. ``If necessary, we'll stay here until 9
o'clock every night until we do it.''
   Dole denied that Republicans were trying to delay final action
but admitted both sides are playing ``hard-ball politics'' on it.
   ``I don't know precisely what's happening myself,'' Dole said of
a string of Republican amendments, many of them approved
unanimously Tuesday but some of them rejected.
   Byrd admitted he does not have the 60 votes necessary to end the
debate and bring the bill to a final vote Wednesday.
   But Republicans leading the opposition to the layoff notices
indicated they may throw in the towel Wednesday, particularly after
Byrd threatened to cut short a July Fourth holiday that many
senators on both sides planned to spend in their home states
campaigning for re-election.
   ``I think we can finish plant closing by tomorrow,'' Sen. Orrin
Hatch of Utah, the chief Republican opponent of the legislation,
replied when asked about Byrd's carrot-stick offer.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said the House would likely
vote on the bill Thursday, assuming the Senate approves it before
recessing Wednesday night.
   Meanwhile, the House Rules Committee delayed acting on a revised
trade bill that President Reagan vetoed last month largely because
it included the plant-closing notification requirements.
   Democratic leaders, fulfilling a promise to the nation's labor
leaders, have agreed to delay final congressional action on the
trade bill until after first acting on the plant closing and layoff
notices.
   Wright also had hoped to win passage of the trade bill before
the House recesses Thursday.
   However, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, a chief author of the
trade measure, said Tuesday he doesn't anticipate Senate action on
it until August _ after Congress has had a chance to override
Reagan's expected veto of the plant-closing bill but before the
Republican National Convention.
   Without a separate plant-closing law, AFL-CIO officials have
vowed to withdraw what congressional supporters of the trade bill
agree is organized labor's pivotal backing of it.
   House and Senate Republican leaders met Tuesday with Reagan at
the White House, where officials said they continue to recommend
that he veto ``any mandatory notice legislation.''
   But opposition among some Republicans and a few one-time
Democratic opponents of the measure appeared to be softening.
   Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., chairman of the Senate Small Business
Committee, had opposed the notifications in two previous Senate
votes, but he said he now supports them.
   And Hatch said Tuesday that he would urge Reagan not to veto the
bill if the notices were limited only to plant closings and
excluded other layoffs. However, a Republican attempt to do that
was defeated Monday.
   ``As long as the layoff provisions are in there, I think he'll
veto it,'' Hatch said of Reagan. ``I've lost on the major issues.''
   Asked if the administration's opposition to the bill was
weakening, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said, ``I would
have no way to judge that.''
   The Senate on Tuesday unanimously accepted four minor amendments
by Hatch, including one to exempt replaced strikers from having to
get the 60-day advance layoff notices.
   But it rejected an amendment by Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind., that
would exempt companies from having to give the notices to
non-strikers whose jobs might be lost from a plant closing or
layoffs that results from a strike or lockout.
   Also turned down was an amendment by Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M.,
that would have limited the notices in layoffs only to workers
losing their jobs as a result of hostile corporate takeovers.
</TEXT>
