<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AT&TForecast     06-28 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-AT&T Forecast,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AT&T Doesn't Have An Earnings Forecast, Financial Chief Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AT&T is not projecting earnings per share to
increase 15 percent this year as its chairman seemed to say two
months ago, the company's chief financial officer said Tuesday.
   Morris Tanenbaum told reporters at a briefing that American
Telephone & Telegraph Co. does not make earnings forecasts. He said
Chairman Robert E. Allen misspoke or was misunderstood when he
seemed to project a 15 percent increase at a news conference in
April.
   Tanenbaum's statement did not shake up AT&T's stock, which rose
25 cents to $26.75 in consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading.
   Lapp Lee, an analyst for Salomon Brothers Inc., said he had been
slightly skeptical of the statement attributed to Allen anyway
because of the possibility Allen was misquoted or had been speaking
of a goal rather than a forecast.
   At a news conference at AT&T's annual meeting in Denver in
April, Allen was asked whether AT&T would be able to sustain for
all of 1988 the 15 percent increase in earnings per share that it
achieved in the first quarter. Allen answered, ``That's our firm
commitment.''
   Tanenbaum, who did not attend the press conference, said he had
reviewed a transcript of it and said it seemed possible either that
Allen misspoke or that reporters had misunderstood his response.
</TEXT>
