<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Doctors-Consumers     06-28 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doctors-Consumers,0558</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AMA Tackles Tough Consumer Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debates on AIDS and the nursing shortage might
grab the most attention, but medical policy-makers meeting this
week are also tackling such issues as the hazards of tanning
parlors and a ban on real-looking toy guns.
   The American Medical Association's law-making body began acting
Tuesday on more than 100 reports and 200 resolutions, ranging from
proposals to require health warnings in alcohol advertising to
cautions about of clove cigarettes.
   The annual meeting of delegates, who represent 295,000 members,
continues throught Thursday.
   The AMA's 420 delegates considered proposals to double the
federal tobacco tax from 16 cents per pack to 32 cents and end
federal price supports to tobacco farmers.
   Delegates were to vote Tuesday on proposals to work for a ban on
the manufacture and sale of realistic-looking toy guns and real
guns made from plastic or other non-metallic materials that are
hard to detect with screening devices.
   The growth of tanning parlors across the country spawned two
proposals aimed at requiring tanning booths to post warning labels
describing the health hazards of exposure to ultraviolet rays.
   Dr. Russell Kridel of Houston, representing the American Academy
of Facial Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery, said at one hearing
that advertising for tanning parlors mislead many people into
thinking exposure to ultraviolet radiation from tanning booths is
safer than the sun's rays.
   ``There are a number of myths that the tanning parlors are
putting out to the general public and we need to debunk these. We
need to have warning labels on these booths like the warning labels
you have on cigarettes,'' Kridel said.
   The committee agreed and Tuesday urged the delegates to adopt
the policy and work to educate the public about the hazards of
ultraviolet radiation.
   While on the subject of warning labels, Dr. Jack Menendez of
Macon, Ga., called on the AMA to work to force alcoholic beverage
manufacturers to put warnings about the dangers of alcohol abuse in
their advertisements.
   ``I think the idea would be to say something like abuse of
alcohol is bad for your health,'' he said.
   The committee recommended the AMA investigate the need for such
warnings.
   The AMA's Council on Scientific Affairs also issued a report on
the health hazards of smoking clove cigarettes, a mixture of 30
percent to 40 percent clove buds with tobacco.
   A committee recommended that the AMA adopt a policy opposing the
use of Indonesian-imported clove cigarettes, which may be linked to
severe respiratory illnesses.
   The growing use of steroids by athletes to build up their
muscles produced a proposal for AMA action. Improper steroid use
poses such dangers as permanently impairing the one's sexual
functions.
   ``This is not a matter of a few athletes popping some pills,''
said Dr. Dave Richards of Salt Lake City. ``These young athletes
are taking intravenous steroids in doses far larger than are
considered therapeutic. They are spending amounts of money that
approach the amount spent for illicit drugs.''
   The committee urged the AMA delegates to adopt a policy
declaring that using steroids to enhance athletic ability is
``entirely inappropriate'' and calling on state legislatures to
enact laws to control their use and distribution.
</TEXT>
