<HEAD>Rain Fears Bring Corn and Bean Prices Down The Limit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBs 8th graf pvs bgng Wheat prices... to CORRECT price
changes by removing decimals . Closing prices as sent are cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A forecast for rain and possible relief for drought-stricken
crops brought corn and soybean futures prices down their daily
limits Tuesday in a wild turnaround at the Chicago Board of Trade.
   A day earlier, prices were limit-up as corn and bean traders
anticipated a continuation of the drought and further crop
deterioration. The new forecast calling for showers to move into
the Midwest later Tuesday and Wednesday made buyers nervous and
sparked a massive selloff, and other markets dipped in sympathy.
   In other markets, cattle and hog futures prices were mixed at
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange; cotton prices fell at the New York
Cotton Exchange; crude oil and heating oil declined at the New York
Mercantile Exchange; gold and silver prices dipped at the New York
Commodity Exchange and sugar prices rallied at the New York Coffee,
Sugar & Cocoa Exchange.
   ``That dirty word was being heard on the floor today, r-a-i-n.
Not a lot, just a little bit, but that's all it takes to scare
anybody,'' said Victor Lespinasse, an analyst with Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc.
   Corn prices closed down the daily limit _ expanded Tuesday to 15
cents a bushel _ in all but two months; while soybeans fell the
expanded 45-cents-a bushel limit in all months except November 1989.
   ``We're at a turning point here,'' Lespinasse said, as nobody
knows the impact rains forecast for the next few days over much of
the Midwest will have on thirsty crops.
   Wheat prices settled 23 cents to 27{ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.73\ a bushel; corn settled 2\
cents to 15 cents lower with July at $3.37{ a bushel; oats settled
15 cents lower across the board; and soybeans settled 25} cents
lower to 45 cents lower with July at $10.14{ a bushel.
   The sharp drop in the corn and soybean markets added a negative
tone to trading in cattle and hog futures at the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, analysts said.
   ``All of a sudden with the corn and soybeans limit down, that
gave a signal to those people who had been maintaining the
drought-type spread to kind of cash in,'' said Chuck Levitt, an
analyst in Chicago with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   But losses were tempered by a USDA announcement after the close
of trading ``that they intended to expand beef purchases under the
food assistance programs by $50 million,'' Levitt said.
   The result will be ``that ranchers who are liquidating cows on
the market will find a little better price than what they've been
experiencing of late,'' he said.
   Hog prices were pressured by a fresh round of price decreases on
the wholesale pork market ``when a stronger market was
anticipated,'' Levitt said.
   Cattle prices settled .55 cent lower to .55 cent higher, with
the contract for delivery in August at 64.62 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were unchanged to 1.50 cents higher with August at 73.05
cents a pound; live hogs were .85 cent lower to .22 cent higher
with July at 45.57 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were 1.27
cents lower to 1.65 cents higher, with July at 37.85 cents a pound.
   Cotton prices followed the lead of grains and soybeans, falling
down the daily 2-cents-a-pound limit on concerns of crop-enhancing
rains, after surging up the limit on Monday.
   Cotton settled 1.25 cents lower to 2.38 cents lower for the July
contract, which has no limit. The July contract was 66.42 cents a
pound.
   Precious metals also felt pressure from the selling wave in corn
and beans, said Jack Barbanel, an analyst with Gruntal & Co. in New
York.
   ``When the agriculturals could not sustain a rally ... there
were quite substantial selloffs'' in gold and silver, he said.
   Gold prices settled $5.40 to $5.60 lower with the June contract
at $437.50 a troy ounce; silver settled 17.9 cents to 18.7 cents
lower with June at $6.757 a troy ounce.
   Sugar prices rallied on talk of bottleneck in shipments of
imports, as well as expectations that a drought-induced shortfall
in corn production will lead to high corn syrup prices; persuading
manufacturers to use more sugar instead, analysts said.
   Sugar prices settled .50 cent to .66 cent higher, with the
contract for delivery in July at 12.62 cents a pound. New York
Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange Tuesday:
   Energy futures were lower in lackluster trading pressured by an
oversupply of crude oil, said Peter Beutel, an analyst with Elders
Futures Inc. in New York.
   Crude oil settled 8 cents to 21 cents lower with the August
contract at $15.78 a barrel; heating oil settled .28 cent to .53
cent lower with July at 42.31 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline
was .42 cent lower to .48 cent higher with July at 51.43 cents a
gallon.
</TEXT>
