<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Canada-AirlineMeals 1stLd-Writethru f024down.rra 06-28
0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Airline Meals, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0245,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toronto-Bound Airlines May Have To Fly Without Food for Passengers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 new grafs to UPDATE with city agreeing to keep
the incinerator open for several days, recast, edit to conform.
Picks up 6th graf, A spokesman...; DELETES now-outdated 11th graf
pvs An airline...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The closing of an old garbage incinerator Tuesday
raised the prospect that up to 200 daily overseas flights into
Toronto's international airport soon may have to fly without food
for passengers.
   Under Canadian government regulations, garbage from incoming
international flights must be incinerated to prevent the
importation of disease.
   But the old Toronto incinerator used for that purpose closed
Tuesday because of fears that it was spewing dioxins and other
pollutants into the air.
   Temporary disposal facilities at the airport may be ready in
about four weeks, but in the interim, the 52 airlines using Toronto
airport have been unable to find a place to burn 25 tons a day of
waste, said Transport Canada spokesman Ian Taylor.
   The executive committee of the Metropolitan Toronto Council
agreed Tuesday night to keep the old incinerator open, at least for
a few days, to avert a crisis on Wednesday.
   Earlier, Taylor had said that without the incinerator,
``...we'll have nowhere to store the garbage and nowhere to
incinerate it,'' he said. ``The airlines have said that as a last
resort, they may have to withdraw food service. It's a major
problem.''
   A spokesman for Minneapolis-based Northwest Airlines, whose only
direct flight into Toronto is from Detroit, said his airline will
simply take any garbage from the short flight back to Detroit.
   Airlines making stopovers at other airports can empty their
garbage there.
   But carriers operating longer direct flights, serving two or
three meals, have no such solution.
   ``You can't fly airplanes around full of garbage,'' said
spokesman Barry Corbett of the Canadian airline Wardair, which has
regular service between Toronto and London, Paris and Honolulu.
   ``It would only take a day or so and your plane would be full of
garbage with no room for baggage. We believe this is resolvable
somehow, before that happens,'' Corbett said.
   The airlines had hoped to ship the waste to a new incinerator in
Hamilton, an hour south of Toronto by road. But Hamilton officials
announced June 22 they will not take the garbage unless airlines
schedule more flights to their city _ a sore point in a steel town
jealous of Toronto's economic dominance.
   As a stopgap, Taylor said, the government will allow the
airlines to install compacting and dehydration machines at the
airport to turn the waste into odorless pellets. The pellets can
then be stored in an airport building until a permanent solution is
found, he said.
   ``But that equipment can't be up and running for about four
weeks,'' he added.
   Other Canadian airports have their own incinerators, operated by
the airlines. But Toronto residents objected to a similar proposal
here.
   Taylor said Canada insisted on the incineration of garbage from
overseas flights after a major outbreak of hoof-and-mouth disease
in 1952 was blamed on contaminated imported sausage. Waste from
domestic flights is taken to landfills.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880628-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0625EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NuclearStandardization     06-28 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Standardization,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Staff Proposal Would Expedite Licensing of Nuclear Plants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The staff of the Nuclear Regulatory Commission
unveiled a proposal Monday aimed at making it easier to license new
nuclear plants and warned that no one will ever build one again
unless something like it is adopted.
   Under the proposal, the commission could grant a conditional
operating license at the same time it grants a construction permit,
provided that the plant design conformed with previously tested and
approved models.
   The NRC still would have to decide when construction was
complete if the conditions for operation had been met, but the
procedure would entail far less time and effort than the current
licensing system, in which some plants have remained idle for years
even after construction was complete.
   The draft regulation would sharply restrict the required public
hearings on operating licenses to allegations of ``material and
uncorrected nonconformance'' with the conditional license or
allegations ``that adequate protection is threatened.''
   The commission has long sought congressional authority to grant
the operating license and the construction permit at the same time
for standardized plants. But various bills to encourage
standardization and allow such ``one-stop'' licensing have not
gotten beyond the hearing stage.
   In presenting the regulatory proposal, William C. Parler, the
NRC's general counsel, told the commissioners, ``It is my judgment
that unless the (licensing) process is changed, it is not likely to
be used by people who have to make the decisions about obtaining
bulk power supply in the future.''
   Utility executives have voiced similar sentiments for years.
   Commission Chairman Lando Zech said he hoped to publish the
proposal for public comment soon. He said it was ``perhaps the most
important initiative we are engaged in this year.''
   Loring Mills, vice president for nuclear matters at the Edison
Electric Institute, the nation's principal trade association of
private utilities, said later, ``We are in favor of whatever the
NRC can do administratively to move forward on standardized plant
design and one-stop licensing.''
   Though 107 commercial plants provide more than 18 percent of the
nation's electricity, huge construction costs, delays and
controversy over safety have meant no new plant orders since the
1970s.
   The 107 plants encompass more than 60 reactor designs from five
providers and built by more than a dozen engineering companies. At
Connecticut's Millstone plant, three different builders provided
reactors.
   Standard designs to which modifications are strictly limited are
bound to save costs, make operation easier and facilitate the
transfer of expertise and safety information from one operator to
another, the commission believes.
   The new plan would permit utilities to win approval for a site
in advance of approval of plant design, with such authorization
good for 20 years to permit ``banking'' of sites.
   The commission would also certify standard plant designs as
safe, normally after operation of a demonstration reactor.
   According to the draft regulation, ``the (site) application
shall contain emergency plans which are as fully developed as
circumstances permit and which show that the area surrounding the
site is amenable to emergency planning which would provide
reasonable assurance that adequate protective measures could be
taken in the even of a radiological emergency at the site.''
   The construction application would require a showing that the
utility had made a ``good faith'' effort to win approval of
emergency plans by local and state governments.
   Refusal by the state and local governments to cooperate in an
evacuation plan has kept the Shoreham plant on Long Island from
winning an operating license, and similar objections by
Massachusetts have kept the Seabrook plant just over the border on
New Hampshire's seacoast from operating.
   The commission insists as a general matter that it can license
plants in such circumstances and to require state and local
approval would give those authorities a veto that Congress never
intended.
   Under the proposed plan, a utility failing to get that
cooperation would still have to show that its proposed emergency
plans ``nonetheless provide reasonable assurance that adequate
protective measures can be taken in the event of a radiological
emergency at the site.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
