<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     06-28 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Generally Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An overabundance of crude oil on world markets
has depressed most energy futures.
   The August contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, fell 15 cents to $15.86 per barrel Monday on the New
York Mercantile Exchange.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, the July contract
for home heating oil slipped 0.55 cent to 42.59 cents a gallon. The
July contract for unleaded gasoline rose 0.14 cent to 51.05 cents a
gallon, but other months declined.
   John Azarow, a trader for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said
crude prices fell in response to a report that United Arab Emirates
oil officials want to raise the oil production ceiling allotted to
them by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   The UAE's current daily quota is 940,000 barrels of crude, but
the emirates already are producing 1.3 million barrels daily. The
UAE's oil council wants to raise its official ceiling to 1.5
million, Azarow said.
   Gasoline prices, which rose last week as crude prices dropped,
apparently fell victim to profit-taking, Azarow said. The declines
in later-month contracts for gas accelerated the drop in the crude
pit, he said.
   ``It made the crude market even more nervous,'' Azarow said.
</TEXT>
