<FILEID>AP-NR-06-28-88 0306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EECSummit     06-28 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EEC Summit,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC To Set Up Central Bank Study Committee</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Meeting scheduled to resume at 4 a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although European Economic
Community leaders have agreed to study what steps they could take
to establish a European monetary union, they will not necessarily
be seeking to establish a multi-nation central bank.
   Leaders of the 12 European Economic Community nations, meeting
in a two-day summit in Hanover, agreed to create a panel that will
be chaired by EEC Commission President Jaques Delors, aimed at
recommending ``concrete steps'' toward establishment of a European
monetary union.
   Dutch Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers told reporters early today the
panel also would include central bank presidents from the EEC
nations.
   The committee will prepare a report with proposals for leading
to increased European monetary integration, although there probably
would not be any mention of a European central bank in the panel's
mandate, Lubbers said.
   A senior British official said Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher,
who opposes the idea of a European central bank, did not oppose the
initiative. He also said the concept of monetary union would have
to be better-defined in the coming year.
   European finance ministers would review the panel's
recommendations before their proposals are discussed at the EEC
summit slated to be held in Spain a year from now, Lubbers said.
   Establishment of a centralized European bank is one of the main
topics at the EEC gathering.
   A spokesman for the British delegation said Mrs. Thatcher was
still skeptical such a development could ever occur.
   ``You will only have it (a European central bank) when you
dissolve the (British) House of Commons, among other'' political
institutions, said the British official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   ``We do not think it would be fruitful to set up a European
central bank,'' he said.
   The British official also said Mrs. Thatcher had proposed six
near-term priorities for the EEC to focus on in its drive to create
a barrier-free internal market by 1992.
   According to the official, Thatcher suggested the EEC
concentrate on, among other things: further liberalization of
financial services to include banking, securities and life
insurance markets; streamlining of testing and product standards
throughout the EEC; further opening of markets for public works
projects; and liberalization of the European transportation market.
   Supporters of the creation of a European central bank and a
common EEC currency say those aims are important to the community's
plans for achieving a totally barrier-free market by 1992.
   Britain also has been reluctant to join the European Monetary
System.
   The EMS is a program under which the currency exchange rates of
participating EEC nations are kept within a certain range to
prevent wide fluctuations. Eight of the 12 EEC countries
participate in the system.
   Mrs. Thatcher has been reluctant to connect the pound with the
EMS because that would decrease domestic control over monetary
policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
